s $x \\rightarrow 0$?','First the table of values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{f(x)}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-0.100$</td>\n		    <td>$4.540 \\times 10^{-5}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-0.010$</td>\n		    <td>$3.720 \\times 10^{-44}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-0.001$</td>\n		    <td>$5.076 \\times 10^{-435}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$0.001$</td>\n		    <td>$1.970 \\times 10^{434}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$0.010$</td>\n		    <td>$2.688 \\times 10^{43}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$0.100$</td>\n		    <td>$2.203 \\times 10^4$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nwhich provides evidence to state that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^-} f(x) &= 0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} f(x) &= \\infty\n	}$\n</div>\nSince the limits do not equate, the general limit is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} f(x) = \\text{DNE}\n	}$\n</div>'),(340,'Example_7',7,109,'Prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{x - 2|x|}{|x|} = \\text{DNE}\n	}$\n</div>','The function of interest can be rewritten as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{x - 2|x|}{|x|} = \\begin{cases}\n		-3 & x < 0 \\\\\n		-1 & x > 0\n		\\end{cases}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich provides evidence to state that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^-} f(x) &= -3 \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} f(x) &= -1\n	}$\n</div>\nSince the limits do not equate, the general limit is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} f(x) = \\text{DNE}\n	}$\n</div>'),(341,'Example_8',8,109,'Prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{1}{1 + 2^{-\\frac{1}{x}}} = \\text{DNE}\n	}$\n</div>','First the table of values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{f(x)}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-0.100$</td>\n		    <td>$9.756 \\times 10^{-4}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-0.010$</td>\n		    <td>$7.889 \\times 10^{-31}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-0.001$</td>\n		    <td>$9.333 \\times 10^{-302}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$0.001$</td>\n		    <td>$1.000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$0.010$</td>\n		    <td>$1.000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$0.100$</td>\n		    <td>$0.999$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nwhich provides evidence to state that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^-} f(x) &= 0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} f(x) &= 1\n	}$\n</div>\nSince the limits do not equate, the general limit is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} f(x) = \\text{DNE}\n	}$\n</div>'),(342,'Example_9',9,109,'Prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 4^+} \\frac{\\sqrt{x} - 2}{x - 4} = \\frac{1}{4}\n	}$\n</div>','By using the conjugate of the numerator and simpliying:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 4} \\frac{\\sqrt{x} - 2}{x - 4} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 4} \\frac{\\sqrt{x} - 2}{x - 4} \\cdot \\frac{\\sqrt{x} + 2}{\\sqrt{x} + 2} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 4} \\frac{x - 4}{(x - 4)(\\sqrt{x} + 2)} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 4} \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{x} + 2} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{4}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow if the general limit exists, then we know:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 4^+} \\frac{\\sqrt{x} - 2}{x - 4} = \\frac{1}{4}\n	}$\n</div>'),(343,'Example_10',10,109,'In the context of Special Relativity, the $\\textit{Lorentz Factor}$ is defined as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\gamma(v) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1 - \\frac{v^2}{c^2}}}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $c$ is the speed of light. The theory of relativity states that nothing can travel faster than the speed of light, therefore, only the left side as $v \\rightarrow c$ interests us. Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{v \\rightarrow c^-} \\gamma(v)\n	}$\n</div>\nNext consider that momentum in Classical Mechanics is defined as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		p_{\\text{CM}}(v) = mv\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $m$ is the mass of the object and in Special Relativity:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		p_{\\text{SR}}(v) = \\gamma(v)mv\n	}$\n</div>\nwhat happens to momentum in Special Relativity that does not seem to occur in Classical Mechanics?','First the table of values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$v$</td>\n		    <td>$\\gamma(v)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$0.900000c$</td>\n		    <td>$2.294$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$0.990000c$</td>\n		    <td>$7.089$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$0.999000c$</td>\n		    <td>$22.366$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$0.999900c$</td>\n		    <td>$70.712$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$0.999990c$</td>\n		    <td>$223.607$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$0.999999c$</td>\n		    <td>$707.107$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nwhich provides evidence to state that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{v \\rightarrow c^-} \\gamma(v) = \\infty\n	}$\n</div>\nIn Classical Mechanics the notion of the speed of light was never a part of the theory, thereby providing that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{v \\rightarrow c^-} p_{\\text{CM}}(v) = mc\n	}$\n</div>\nmomentum is clearly defined. Experimentally this was found not to hold true, but rather what happens is that near the speed of light the momentum skyrockets so much that it becomes infinite when traveling at the speed of the light for an object with mass:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{v \\rightarrow c^-} p_{\\text{SR}}(v) = \\infty\n	}$\n</div>'),(344,'Example_1',1,110,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} (x^2 - 2x + 1)\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} (x^2 - 2x + 1) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} x^2 - 2 \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} x + \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} 1 \\\\\n		&= \\Big[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} x \\Big]^2 - 2(2) + (1) \\\\\n		&= 4 - 4 + 1 \\\\\n		&= 1\n	}$\n</div>'),(345,'Example_2',2,110,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{x^2 + 1}{\\cos(x)}\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{x^2 + 1}{\\cos(x)} \\\\\n		&= \\Big[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} x^2 + \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} 1 \\Big] \\Big[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} \\cos(x) \\Big]^{-1} \\\\\n		&= (1)(1)^{-1} \\\\\n		&= 1\n	}$\n</div>'),(346,'Example_3',3,110,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} (x^3 + 3)\\csc\\Big( x - \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} (x^3 + 3)\\csc\\Big( x - \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\Big[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} x^3 + \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} 3 \\Big] \\cdot \\Big[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} \\csc\\Big( x - \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\Big) \\Big] \\\\\n		&= (3)(-1) \\\\\n		&= -3\n	}$\n</div>'),(347,'Example_4',4,110,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{2(-3 + h)^2 - 18}{h}\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{2(-3 + h)^2 - 18}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{2(9 - 6h + h^2) - 18}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{h^2 - 12h}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} (h - 12) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} h - \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} 12 \\\\\n		&= -12\n	}$\n</div>'),(348,'Example_5',5,110,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{h \\rightarrow 4} \\frac{h - \\sqrt{3h + 4}}{4 - h}\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{h \\rightarrow 4} \\frac{h - \\sqrt{3h + 4}}{4 - h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 4} \\frac{h - \\sqrt{3h + 4}}{4 - h} \\cdot \\frac{h + \\sqrt{3h + 4}}{h + \\sqrt{3h + 4}} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 4} \\frac{h^2 - 3h - 4}{(4 - h)(h + \\sqrt{3h + 4})} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 4} \\frac{(h - 4)(h + 1)}{-(h - 4)(h + \\sqrt{3h + 4})} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 4} -\\frac{h + 1}{h + \\sqrt{3h + 4}} \\\\\n		&= -\\Big[ \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 4} (h + 1) \\Big] \\Big[ \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 4} (h + \\sqrt{3h + 4}) \\Big]^{-1} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{5}{8}\n	}$\n</div>'),(349,'Example_6',6,110,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 5} \\frac{x^2 - 25}{x^2 + x - 30}\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 5} \\frac{x^2 - 25}{x^2 + x - 30} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 5} \\frac{(x - 5)(x + 5)}{(x + 6)(x - 5)} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 5} \\frac{x + 5}{x + 6} \\\\\n		&= \\Big[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 5} (x + 5) \\Big] \\Big[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 5} (x + 6) \\Big]^{-1} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{10}{11}\n	}$\n</div>'),(350,'Example_7',7,110,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{x^2 + 1}{x - 2}\n	}$\n</div>','Note that when plugged in directly we arrive at division by zero. To make sense of this lets observe what happens on each side. The numerator in this scenario is always positive so we only have to watch out for the behavior of the denominator. Specifically, from the left side the denominator will always be negative giving:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2^-} \\frac{x^2 + 1}{x - 2} &= -\\infty\n	}$\n</div>\nOn the right side the denominator is always positive giving:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2^+} \\frac{x^2 + 1}{x - 2} &= \\infty\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this we are allowed to say:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{x^2 + 1}{x - 2} &= \\text{DNE}\n	}$\n</div>'),(351,'Example_8',8,110,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{x^2 + 4x - 12}{|x - 2|}\n	}$\n</div>','With the absolute value in play we have to be a little careful at $x = 2$. Formally:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{x^2 + 4x - 12}{|x - 2|} = \\begin{cases}\n			\\frac{x^2 + 4x - 12}{-(x - 2)} & x < 2 \\\\\n			\\frac{x^2 + 4x - 12}{x - 2} & x > 2\n		\\end{cases}\n	}$\n</div>\nLooking at the left side of the limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2^-} \\frac{x^2 + 4x - 12}{-(x - 2)} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2^-} \\frac{(x + 6)(x - 2)}{-(x - 2)} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2^-} -(x + 6) \\\\\n		&= -8\n	}$\n</div>\nand the right side:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2^+} \\frac{x^2 + 4x - 12}{x - 2} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2^+} \\frac{(x + 6)(x - 2)}{x - 2} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2^+} (x + 6) \\\\\n		&= 8\n	}$\n</div>\nThis provides enough evidence to state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} \\frac{x^2 + 4x - 12}{|x - 2|} = \\text{DNE}\n	}$\n</div>'),(352,'Example_9',9,110,'Find numbers $a$ and $b$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\sqrt{ax + b} - 2}{x} = 1\n	}$\n</div>','Begin by reorganizing the fraction:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{\\sqrt{ax + b} - 2}{x} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{\\sqrt{ax + b} - 2}{x} \\cdot \\frac{\\sqrt{ax + b} + 2}{\\sqrt{ax + b} + 2} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{ax + b - 4}{x(\\sqrt{ax + b} + 2)}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow notice that we ultimately want to get rid of the $x$ in the denominator because it causes issues for the limit. So let $b = 4$ to get:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{ax + b - 4}{x(\\sqrt{ax + b} + 2)} &= \\frac{ax}{x(\\sqrt{ax + 4} + 2)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{a}{\\sqrt{ax + 4} + 2}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow taking the limit gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{a}{\\sqrt{ax + 4} + 2} = \\frac{a}{4}\n	}$\n</div>\nTo make this limit equate to one, we let $a = 4$.'),(353,'Example_10',10,110,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{|2x - 1| - |2x + 1|}{x}\n	}$\n</div>','Approaching this directly is too hard, so instead lets simplify the expression at hand. First:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|2x - 1| &= \\begin{cases}\n			-(2x - 1) & x < \\frac{1}{2} \\\\\n			2x - 1 & x \\geq \\frac{1}{2}\n		\\end{cases} \\\\\n		|2x + 1| &= \\begin{cases}\n			-(2x + 1) & x < -\\frac{1}{2} \\\\\n			2x + 1 & x \\geq -\\frac{1}{2}\n		\\end{cases}\n	}$\n</div>\nNotice that this breakup produces three regions of interest in relation to our original expression. Explicitly we have:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{|2x - 1| - |2x + 1|}{x} = \\begin{cases}\n			\\frac{2}{x} & x < -\\frac{1}{2} \\\\\n			-4 & |x| \\leq \\frac{1}{2} \\\\\n			-\\frac{2}{x} & x > \\frac{1}{2}\n		\\end{cases}\n	}$\n</div>\nClearly we have no issue at our point of interest so:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{|2x - 1| - |2x + 1|}{x} = -4\n	}$\n</div>'),(354,'Example_1',1,111,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{x^2 + 1}{x - 2}\n	}$\n</div>','As $x$ approaches large values the constants in the numerator and denominator become insignificant:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{x^2 + 1}{x - 2} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{x^2}{x} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} x \\\\\n		&= \\infty\n	}$\n</div>'),(355,'Example_2',2,111,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{3x^2}{4x^2 + 2x - 1}\n	}$\n</div>','As $x$ approaches large values the constant and linear factor in the denominator become insignificant:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{3x^2}{4x^2 + 2x - 1} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{3x^2}{4x^2} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{3}{4} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{3}{4}\n	}$\n</div>'),(356,'Example_3',3,111,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} \\frac{x - 1}{2x^2 + 3}\n	}$\n</div>','As $x$ approaches small values the constants in the numerator and denominator become insignificant:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} \\frac{x - 1}{2x^2 + 3} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} \\frac{x}{2x^2} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} \\frac{1}{2x} \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(357,'Example_4',4,111,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{3x}{\\sqrt{16x^2 + 1}}\n	}$\n</div>','As $x$ approaches large values the constant in the denominator becomes insignificant:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{3x}{\\sqrt{16x^2 + 1}} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{3x}{\\sqrt{16x^2}} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{3x}{4x} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{3}{4} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{3}{4}\n	}$\n</div>'),(358,'Example_5',5,111,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\sqrt{x^2 + x + 1} - x\n	}$\n</div>','Multiply the numerator and denominator by the conjugate. Then as $x$ approaches large values throw out the insignificant components:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\sqrt{x^2 + x + 1} - x \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{x + 1}{\\sqrt{x^2 + x + 1} + x} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{x + 1}{\\sqrt{x^2} + x} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{x}{2x} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{1}{2} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(359,'Example_6',6,111,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{5^x}{3^x + 2^x}\n	}$\n</div>','Ignoring  the smallest exponential term at large values of $x$ yields:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{5^x}{3^x + 2^x} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\Big( \\frac{5}{3} \\Big)^x \\\\\n		&= \\infty\n	}$\n</div>'),(360,'Example_7',7,111,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} (3^x + 3^{2x})^{\\frac{1}{x}}\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} (3^x + 3^{2x})^{\\frac{1}{x}} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\Big( 3^{2x}(3^{-x} + 1) \\Big)^{\\frac{1}{x}} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} 9(1 + 3^{-x})^{\\frac{1}{x}} \\\\\n		&= 9(1 + 0)^0 \\\\\n		&= 9\n	}$\n</div>'),(361,'Example_8',8,111,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} \\frac{e^x}{4 + 5e^{3x}}\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} \\frac{e^x}{4 + 5e^{3x}} \\\\\n		&= \\Big[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} e^x \\Big] \\Big[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} (4 + 5e^{3x}) \\Big]^{-1} \\\\\n		&= (0)(4 + 5(0))^{-1} \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(362,'Example_9',9,111,'You are told that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} \\ln(f(x)) = \\ln\\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>\nUse this information to evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\log\\Big( \\frac{x^6 - 500}{x^6 + 500} \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\log\\Big( \\frac{x^6 - 500}{x^6 + 500} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\log\\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{x^6 - 500}{x^6 + 500} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\log(1) \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(363,'Example_10',10,111,'You are told that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} \\ln(f(x)) = \\ln\\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>\nUse this information to evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} n^{\\frac{1}{n}}\n	}$\n</div>','To begin let:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(n) = n^{\\frac{1}{n}}\n	}$\n</div>\nand continue by taking the logarithm of both sides and applying a limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(n) &= n^{\\frac{1}{n}} \\\\\n		\\ln(y(n)) &= \\ln\\Big( n^{\\frac{1}{n}} \\Big) \\\\\n		\\ln(y(n)) &= \\frac{\\ln(n)}{n} \\\\\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} \\ln(y(n)) &= \\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{\\ln(n)}{n} \\\\\n		\\ln\\Big( \\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} y(n) \\Big) &= 0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} y(n) &= e^0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} y(n) &= 1\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the limit of the logarithm over the polynomial approaches zero because polynomials dominate logarithms at large values of $n$.'),(364,'Example_1',1,112,'Is the given function continuous?\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(t) = \\frac{45t^3 - 47}{t^3 - t}\n	}$\n</div>\nIf not, where are the discontinuities?','The rational function will be discontinuous whenever the denominator equates to zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= t^3 - t \\\\\n		0 &= t(t^2 - 1) \\\\\n		0 &= t(t - 1)(t + 1) \\\\\n		t &= -1, 0, 1\n	}$\n</div>\nIn other words the above represents the vertical asymptotes.'),(365,'Example_2',2,112,'Given that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\begin{cases}\n			A + x & x < 2 \\\\\n			1 + x^2 & x \\geq 2\n		\\end{cases}\n	}$\n</div>\nFind a value for $A$ s.t. the function is continuous at the point $x = 2$.','To make the function continuous at $x = 2$ we want to equate the two components to each other at the point:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		A + (2) &= 1 + (2)^2 \\\\\n		A &= 3\n	}$\n</div>'),(366,'Example_3',3,112,'Given that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\begin{cases}\n			x & x \\leq 3 \\\\\n			A + \\frac{x}{2} & x > 3\n		\\end{cases}\n	}$\n</div>\nFind a value for $A$ s.t. the function is continuous at the point for all values of $x$.','The only part where the function may not be continuous is the splitting. So to make the function continuous at $x = 3$ we want to equate the two components to each other at the point:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(3) &= A + \\frac{(3)}{2} \\\\\n		A &= \\frac{3}{2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(367,'Example_4',4,112,'Given that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\begin{cases}\n			x^2 + 2x & x < a \\\\\n			-1 & x \\geq a\n		\\end{cases}\n	}$\n</div>\nFind all values of $a$ s.t. the function is continuous everywhere.','Independently, the components are already continuous. So we just have to make sure that at the splitting point the function is continuous. At $x = a$ we must have the components equate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(a)^2 + 2(a) &= -1 \\\\\n		a^2 + 2a + 1 &= 0 \\\\\n		(a + 1)^2 &= 0 \\\\\n		a &= -1\n	}$\n</div>'),(368,'Example_5',5,112,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\ln\\Big( \\frac{e^{-x} + 25}{e^x + 5} \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\ln\\Big( \\frac{e^{-x} + 25}{e^x + 5} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\ln\\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{e^{-x} + 25}{e^x + 5} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\ln\\Big( \\frac{(0) + 25}{(0) + 5} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\ln(5)\n	}$\n</div>'),(369,'Example_6',6,112,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\pi} e^{\\cos\\Big( x + \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\Big)}\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\pi} e^{\\cos\\Big( x + \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\Big)} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\pi} \\cos\\Big( x + \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\Big)} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\cos\\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\pi} \\Big( x + \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\Big) \\Big)} \\\\\n		&= e^{\\cos\\Big( \\frac{3\\pi}{2} \\Big)} \\\\\n		&= e^0 \\\\\n		&= 1\n	}$\n</div>'),(370,'Example_7',7,112,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} x^2\\sin\\Big( \\frac{1}{x} \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>','We know that the range of the sine function is restricted as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		-1 \\leq \\sin(u) \\leq 1 \\hspace{.3cm} \\forall u \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nThis gives the perfect setup for the squeeze theorem:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		-1 \\leq &\\sin\\Big( \\frac{1}{x} \\Big) \\leq 1 \\\\\n		-x^2 \\leq &x^2\\sin\\Big( \\frac{1}{x} \\Big) \\leq x^2 \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} -x^2 \\leq \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} &x^2\\sin\\Big( \\frac{1}{x} \\Big) \\leq \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} x^2 \\\\\n		0 \\leq \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} &x^2\\sin\\Big( \\frac{1}{x} \\Big) \\leq 0\n	}$\n</div>\nSince both sides approach zero, then so must the middle giving:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} x^2\\sin\\Big( \\frac{1}{x} \\Big) = 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(371,'Example_8',8,112,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{\\sin(x)}{x}\n	}$\n</div>','We know that the range of the sine function is restricted as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		-1 \\leq \\sin(u) \\leq 1 \\hspace{.3cm} \\forall u \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nThis gives the perfect setup for the squeeze theorem:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		-1 \\leq &\\sin(x) \\leq 1 \\\\\n		-\\frac{1}{x} \\leq &\\frac{\\sin(x)}{x} \\leq \\frac{1}{x} \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} -\\frac{1}{x} \\leq \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} &\\frac{\\sin(x)}{x} \\leq \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{1}{x} \\\\\n		0 \\leq \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} &\\frac{\\sin(x)}{x} \\leq 0\n	}$\n</div>\nSince both sides approach zero, then so must the middle giving:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{\\sin(x)}{x} = 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(372,'Example_9',9,112,'Given the polynomial:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		p(x) = 2x^3 - 5x^2 - 10x + 5\n	}$\n</div>\nShow that it has a root in the interval $[-1,2]$.','To have a root is the same thing as saying there exists a value for $x$ in the interval s.t. $p(x) = 0$. Notice that the endpoints evaluate out to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		p(-1) &= 8 \\\\\n		p(2) &= -19\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we state that by the Intermediate Value Theorem since $p(x)$ is a continuous function on the interval and $0 \\in [-19,8]$, then there must exist a number in the interval, $c \\in [-1,2]$, s.t. $p(c) = 0$.'),(373,'Example_10',10,112,'Show that there exists some $u \\in (0,2)$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u^2 + \\cos(\\pi u) = 4\n	}$\n</div>','Denote the general function of interest to be:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(u) = u^2 + \\cos(\\pi u)\n	}$\n</div>\nNotice that the endpoints evaluate out to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(0) &= (0)^2 + \\cos(\\pi \\cdot 0) = 1 \\\\\n		f(2) &= (2)^2 + \\cos(\\pi \\cdot 2) = 5\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we state that by the Intermediate Value Theorem since $p(x)$ is a continuous function on the interval and $4 \\in (1,5)$, then there must exist a number in the interval, $c \\in (0,2)$, s.t. $f(c) = 4$.'),(374,'Example_1',1,113,'Using the Bisection Method determine $x_5$, the fifth iteration up to five decimal places, as an approximation of the root to the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^3 - x + 1\n	}$\n</div>\non the interval $[-2,-1]$.','The iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		    <td>$f(\\textbf{x}_n)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.50000$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.87500$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.25000$</td>\n		    <td>$0.29688$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.37500$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.22461$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.31250$</td>\n		    <td>$0.05151$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.34375$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.08261$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.32813$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.01458$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(375,'Example_2',2,113,'Given the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sin(x) = x^2\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate the solution up to $5$ decimal places by using the Bisection Method to determine $x_5$, the fifth iteration, on the interval $\\Big[ \\frac{1}{2}, 1 \\Big]$.','First we rewrite the equation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = \\sin(x) - x^2\n	}$\n</div>\nand identify the function of interest to be:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\sin(x) - x^2\n	}$\n</div>\nThe iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		    <td>$f(\\textbf{x}_n)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$0.75000$</td>\n		    <td>$0.11914$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$0.87500$</td>\n		    <td>$0.00192$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$0.93750$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.07283$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$0.90625$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.03409$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$0.89063$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.015753$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$0.88281$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.00683$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(376,'Example_3',3,113,'Given the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\cos(x) = 2x\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate the solution up to $5$ decimal places by using the Bisection Method to determine $x_5$, the fifth iteration, on the interval $[0,1]$.','First we rewrite the equation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = \\cos(x) - 2x\n	}$\n</div>\nand identify the function of interest to be:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\cos(x) - 2x\n	}$\n</div>\nThe iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		    <td>$f(\\textbf{x}_n)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$0.50000$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.12242$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$0.25000$</td>\n		    <td>$0.46891$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$0.37500$</td>\n		    <td>$0.18051$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$0.43750$</td>\n		    <td>$0.03081$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$0.46875$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.04537$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$0.45313$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.00717$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(377,'Example_4',4,113,'Given the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		6x = \\sqrt{1 - x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate the solution up to $5$ decimal places by using the Bisection Method to determine $x_5$, the fifth iteration.','Before anything else we need to determine a suitable interval to search. This can be accomplished by graphing the left and right hand sides independently:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Limits/Bisection_Method/Example_4.png\">\n</div>\nLooking at the graph shows that $[0,1]$ is a proper interval. Now we rewrite the equation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = 6x - \\sqrt{1 - x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nand identify the function of interest to be:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = 6x - \\sqrt{1 - x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nThe iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		    <td>$f(\\textbf{x}_n)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$0.50000$</td>\n		    <td>$2.13397$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$0.25000$</td>\n		    <td>$0.53175$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$0.12500$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.24216$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$0.18750$</td>\n		    <td>$0.14274$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$0.15625$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.05022$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$0.17188$</td>\n		    <td>$0.04613$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(378,'Example_5',5,113,'Given the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\ln(x) = x^2 - 4\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate the rightmost solution up to $5$ decimal places by using the Bisection Method to determine $x_5$, the fifth iteration.','Before anything else we need to determine a suitable interval to search. This can be accomplished by graphing the left and right hand sides independently:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Limits/Bisection_Method/Example_5.png\">\n</div>\nLooking at the graph shows that $[1,3]$ is a proper interval. Now we rewrite the equation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = \\ln(x) - x^2 + 4\n	}$\n</div>\nand identify the function of interest to be:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\ln(x) - x^2 + 4\n	}$\n</div>\nThe iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		    <td>$f(\\textbf{x}_n)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$2.00000$</td>\n		    <td>$0.69315$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$2.50000$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.33371$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$2.25000$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.25157$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$2.12500$</td>\n		    <td>$0.23815$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$2.18750$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.00240$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$2.15625$</td>\n		    <td>$0.11896$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(379,'Example_6',6,113,'Given the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		e^{\\sin(x)} = -x\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate the solution up to $5$ decimal places by using the Bisection Method to determine $x_5$, the fifth iteration, on the interval $[-1,0]$.','First we rewrite the equation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = e^{\\sin(x)} + x\n	}$\n</div>\nand identify the function of interest to be:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = e^{\\sin(x)} + x\n	}$\n</div>\nThe iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		    <td>$f(\\textbf{x}_n)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.50000$</td>\n		    <td>$0.11914$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.75000$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.24421$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.62500$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.06795$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.56250$</td>\n		    <td>$0.02416$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.59375$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.02224$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.57813$</td>\n		    <td>$0.00087$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(380,'Example_7',7,113,'Using the Bisection Method determine $x_5$, the fifth iteration up to five decimal places, as an approximation of the root to the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\sin(x)\n	}$\n</div>\non the interval $[1,99]$. Does the Bisection Method manage to find all the roots on the interval? What does this indicate about the algorithm?','The iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		    <td>$f(\\textbf{x}_n)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$50.00000$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.26237$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$25.50000$</td>\n		    <td>$0.35906$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$37.75000$</td>\n		    <td>$0.05087$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$43.87500$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.10709$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$40.81250$</td>\n		    <td>$0.02820$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$42.34375$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.99771$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nUnfortunately the method only produced one root, but it is a known fact that there are more. This indicates that the algorithm in general does not find all the roots on a given interval, nor does it even indicate where the other ones are.'),(381,'Example_8',8,113,'Determine the number of steps needed for the Bisection Method on the interval $[a,b]$ given we want the error to be $\\epsilon$ at most?','From the notes we know that the subintervals satisfy the relation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|I_n| = \\frac{|I_0|}{2^n}\n	}$\n</div>\nand so we can rewrite this as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|c_n - c| = \\frac{|b - a|}{2^n}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $c_n$ is the $n$th approximation and $c$ is the desired value. The left side represents the error and can be used to solve for the number of steps:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\epsilon &= \\frac{\\epsilon_0}{2^n} \\\\\n		2^n &= \\frac{\\epsilon_0}{\\epsilon} \\\\\n		n &= \\log_2\\Big( \\frac{\\epsilon_0}{\\epsilon} \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>\nObviously we should account for the fact that $n$ is strictly a natural number in real life, and thus to guarantee a whole number we round up:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\text{# of steps} \\hspace{.2cm} = \\Bigg\\lceil \\log_2\\Big( \\frac{\\epsilon_0}{\\epsilon} \\Big) \\Bigg\\rceil\n	}$\n</div>'),(382,'Example_9',9,113,'Use the Bisection Method to approximate $\\sqrt{2}$ up to $5$ decimal places at $x_5$, the fifth iteration.','The number of interest is a root of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^2 - 2\n	}$\n</div>\nand looking at the graph:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Limits/Bisection_Method/Example_9.png\">\n</div>\nshows that a suitable interval to restrict ourselves to is $[1,2]$. Next up the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		    <td>$f(\\textbf{x}_n)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$1.50000$</td>\n		    <td>$0.25000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$1.25000$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.43750$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$1.37500$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.10937$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$1.43750$</td>\n		    <td>$0.06641$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$1.40625$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.02246$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$1.42188$</td>\n		    <td>$0.02173$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(383,'Example_10',10,113,'Use the Bisection Method to approximate $\\sqrt{11}$ up to $5$ decimal places at $x_5$, the fifth iteration.','The number of interest is a root of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^2 - 11\n	}$\n</div>\nand looking at the graph:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Limits/Bisection_Method/Example_10.png\">\n</div>\nshows that a suitable interval to restrict ourselves to is $[3,4]$. Next up the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		    <td>$f(\\textbf{x}_n)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$3.50000$</td>\n		    <td>$1.25000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$3.25000$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.43750$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$3.37500$</td>\n		    <td>$0.39063$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$3.31250$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.02734$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$3.34375$</td>\n		    <td>$0.18066$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$3.32813$</td>\n		    <td>$0.07642$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(384,'Example_1',1,105,'Given the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^2 + 5\n	}$\n</div>\nDetermine $f\'(3)$.','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(3) &= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(3 + h) - f(3)}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{((3 + h)^2 + 5) - (9 + 5)}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{9 + 6h + h^2 + 5 - 14}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{6h + h^2}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} (6 + h) \\\\\n		&= 6\n	}$\n</div>'),(385,'Example_2',2,105,'Given the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\frac{1}{x}\n	}$\n</div>\nDetermine $f\'(7)$.','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(7) &= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(7 + h) - f(7)}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\frac{1}{7 + h} - \\frac{1}{7}}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\frac{7 - (7 + h)}{7(7 + h)}}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} -\\frac{1}{7(7 + h)} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{1}{49}\n	}$\n</div>'),(386,'Example_3',3,105,'Given the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = |x|\n	}$\n</div>\nDetermine $f\'(0)$.','From the left side:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^-} \\frac{f(0 + h) - f(0)}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^-} \\frac{-(0 + h) - (-0)}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^-} \\frac{-h}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^-} -1 \\\\\n		&= -1\n	}$\n</div>\nand from the right side:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^+} \\frac{f(0 + h) - f(0)}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^+} \\frac{(0 + h) - (0)}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^+} \\frac{h}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^+} 1 \\\\\n		&= 1\n	}$\n</div>\nSince the limit does not exist, then neither does the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(0) = \\text{DNE}\n	}$\n</div>'),(387,'Example_4',4,105,'Prove:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} (mx + b) = m\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} (mx + b) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{(m(x + h) + b) - (mx + b)}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{mh}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} m \\\\\n		&= m\n	}$\n</div>'),(388,'Example_5',5,105,'Determine:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dt} \\frac{t}{t + 1}\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dt} \\frac{t}{t + 1} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\frac{t + h}{t + h + 1} - \\frac{t}{t + 1}}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\frac{(t + h)(t + 1) - t(t + h + 1)}{(t + h + 1)(t + 1)}}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{(t^2 + t + ht + h) - (t^2 + th + t)}{h(t + h + 1)(t + 1)} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{1}{(t + h + 1)(t + 1)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{(t + 1)^2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(389,'Example_6',6,105,'Determine the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\sqrt{x + 1}\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{df}{dx} &= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\sqrt{x + h + 1} - \\sqrt{x + 1}}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{x + h + 1 - (x + 1)}{h(\\sqrt{x + h + 1} + \\sqrt{x + 1})} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{x + h + 1} + \\sqrt{x + 1}} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{2\\sqrt{x + 1}}\n	}$\n</div>'),(390,'Example_7',7,105,'Suppose the position of a particle is modeled by the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = 2x^2 - 16x + 30\n	}$\n</div>\nAt what position is the particle not moving? On what intervals is the distance increasing and decreasing?','To accomplish all of this we need the derivative first:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{df}{dx} &= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{2(x + h)^2 - 16(x + h) + 30}{h} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{2x^2 - 16x + 30}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{4hx + 2h^2 - 16h}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} (4x + 2h - 16) \\\\\n		&= 4x - 16\n	}$\n</div>\nNow for the particle to not be moving, then the instantaneous rate of change has to equate to zero. This occurs when the derivative is zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= \\frac{df}{dx} \\\\\n		0 &= 4x - 16 \\\\\n		x &= 4\n	}$\n</div>\nSo at $x = 4$ the particle is not moving. Observe that to the left of $x = 4$, the derivative is negative thus giving a negative rate of change. So the distance is decreasing on the interval $(-\\infty, 4)$. On the opposite side the derivative is positive, thus producing a positive rate of change. As a result the distance is increasing on the interval $(4, \\infty)$. '),(391,'Example_8',8,105,'Determine:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow -2} \\frac{\\sqrt{x + 4} - \\sqrt{2}}{x + 2}\n	}$\n</div>\nWhat does this physically represent?','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow -2} \\frac{\\sqrt{x + 4} - \\sqrt{2}}{x + 2} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -2} \\frac{\\sqrt{x + 4} - \\sqrt{2}}{x + 2} \\cdot \\frac{\\sqrt{x + 4} + \\sqrt{2}}{\\sqrt{x + 4} + \\sqrt{2}} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -2} \\frac{x + 4 - 2}{(x + 2)(\\sqrt{x + 4} + \\sqrt{2})} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -2} \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{x + 4} + \\sqrt{2}} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{6} + \\sqrt{2}}\n	}$\n</div>\nThis limit represents the derivative of $\\sqrt{x + 4}$ at $x = -2$.'),(392,'Example_9',9,105,'Determine the equation of the tangent line to the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\pi\\sqrt{x^2 + 1}\n	}$\n</div>\nat $x = 1$.','To accomplish this we are going to find the instantaneous rate of change and the point through which the line passes. For the point we just have to evaluate the function at $x = 1$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(1) = \\frac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2}}\n	}$\n</div>\nAs for the slope:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&f\'(1) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(1 + h) - f(1)}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\pi \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\sqrt{(1 + h)^2 + 1} - \\sqrt{2}}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\pi \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{((1 + h)^2 + 1) - 2}{h(\\sqrt{(1 + h)^2 + 1} + \\sqrt{2})} \\\\\n		&= \\pi \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{h^2 + 2h}{h(\\sqrt{(1 + h)^2 + 1} + \\sqrt{2})} \\\\\n		&= \\pi \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{h + 2}{(\\sqrt{(1 + h)^2 + 1} + \\sqrt{2})} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2}}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we form the line as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x) = \\frac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2}}x + b\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere we evaluate $b$ by using the point already known:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(1) &= \\frac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2}} + b \\\\\n		\\pi\\sqrt{2} &= \\frac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2}} + b \\\\\n		b &= \\pi\\Big( \\sqrt{2} - \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>\nSo the final solution is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x) = \\frac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{2}}x + \\pi\\Big( \\sqrt{2} - \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{2}} \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>'),(393,'Example_10',10,105,'Explain why a function that is differentiable at a point is also continuous at that point. Does the reverse hold true?','A function, $f(x)$, that is differentiable at a point states that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(a) = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(x) - f(a)}{x - a}\n	}$\n</div>\nand $f\'(a)$ is guaranteed to exist. Now assuming that $x \\neq a$ we have:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (f(x) - f(a)) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} \\Big[ \\frac{f(x) - f(a)}{x - a} \\cdot (x - a) \\Big] \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(x) - f(a)}{x - a} \\cdot \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (x - a) \\\\\n		&= f\'(a) \\cdot 0 \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nSo we have proven:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (f(x) - f(a)) = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand by using properties of limits:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (f(x) - f(a)) \\\\\n		0 &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) - \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(a) \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(a) \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) &= f(a)\n	}$\n</div>\nThe above statement is the exact definition of continuity. As for the reverse order consider the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k(x) = |x|\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich is known to be continuous at $x = 0$, but not differentiable. With a single counter example present, the statement does not hold true. '),(394,'Example_1',1,106,'Given:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^3y^5 + 3x = 8y^3 + 1\n	}$\n</div>\nDetermine $y\'(x)$.','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ x^3y^5 + 3x \\Big] &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ 8y^3 + 1 \\Big] \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} x^2y^5 + 3\\frac{d}{dx} x &= 8\\frac{d}{dx} y^3 + \\frac{d}{dx} 1 \\\\\n		2xy^5 + 5x^2y^4y\' + 3 &= 24y^2y\' \\\\\n		y\'(5x^2y^4 - 24y^2) &= -2xy^5 \\\\\n		y\' &= -\\frac{2xy^5}{5x^2y^4 - 24y^2} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{2xy^5}{24y^2 - 5x^2y^4}\n	}$\n</div>'),(395,'Example_2',2,106,'Given:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = \\sin(3x + 4y)\n	}$\n</div>\nDetermine $y\'(x)$.','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} y &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\sin(3x + 4y) \\\\\n		y\' &= \\cos(3x + 4y) \\cdot (3 + 4y\') \\\\\n		y\' &= 3\\cos(3x + 4y) + 4\\cos(3x + 4y)y\' \\\\\n		y\' &= \\frac{3\\cos(3x + 4y)}{1 - 4\\cos(3x + 4y)}\n	}$\n</div>'),(396,'Example_3',3,106,'Given:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		e^{xy} = e^{4x} - e^{5y}\n	}$\n</div>\nDetermine $y\'(x)$.','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} e^{xy} &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ e^{4x} - e^{5y} \\Big] \\\\\n		(y + xy\')e^{xy} &= 4e^{4x} - 5y\'e^{5y} \\\\\n		y\'(xe^{xy} + 5e^{5y}) &= 4e^{4x} - ye^{xy} \\\\\n		y\' &= \\frac{4e^{4x} - ye^{xy}}{xe^{xy} + 5e^{5y}}\n	}$\n</div>'),(397,'Example_4',4,106,'Given:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\cos^2(x) + \\cos^2(y) = \\cos(2x + 2y)\n	}$\n</div>\nDetermine $y\'(x)$.','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= \\cos^2(x) + \\cos^2(y) - \\cos(2x + 2y) \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} 0 &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ \\cos^2(x) + \\cos^2(y) \\Big] \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - \\frac{d}{dx} \\cos(2x + 2y) \\\\\n		0 &= -2\\cos(x)\\sin(x) - 2\\cos(y)\\sin(y)y\' \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - \\sin(2x + 2y) \\cdot (2 + 2y\') \\\\\n		y\' &= \\frac{\\cos(x)\\sin(x) - \\sin(2x + 2y)}{\\sin(2x + 2y) - \\cos(y)\\sin(y)}\n	}$\n</div>'),(398,'Example_5',5,106,'Given:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{y}{x^3} + \\frac{x}{y^3} = x^2y^4\n	}$\n</div>\nDetermine $y\'(x)$.','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= \\frac{y}{x^3} + \\frac{x}{y^3} - x^2y^4 \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} 0 &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ \\frac{y}{x^3} + \\frac{x}{y^3} - x^2y^4 \\Big] \\\\\n		0 &= y\'x^{-3} - 3yx^{-4} + y^{-3} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 3xy^{-4}y\' - 2xy^4 - 4x^2y^3y\' \\\\\n		y\' &= \\frac{2xy^4 + 3yx^{-4} - y^{-3}}{x^{-3} - 3xy^{-4} - 4x^2y^3} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{2xy^4 + 3yx^{-4} - y^{-3}}{x^{-3} - 3xy^{-4} - 4x^2y^3} \\cdot \\frac{x^4y^4}{x^4y^4} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{2x^5y^8 + 3y^5 - x^4y}{xy^4 - 3x^5 - 4x^6y^7}\n	}$\n</div>'),(399,'Example_6',6,106,'Find the equation of the tangent line to the graph of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(x^2 + y^2)^3 = 8x^2y^2\n	}$\n</div>\nat the point $(-1,1)$.','To accomplish this we are going to find the instantaneous rate of change at the point of interest. First the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= (x^2 + y^2)^3 - 8x^2y^2 \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} 0 &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ (x^2 + y^2)^3 - 8x^2y^2 \\Big] \\\\\n		0 &= 3(x^2 + y^2)^2 \\cdot (2x + 2yy\') \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 16xy^2 - 16x^2yy\' \\\\\n		y\' &= \\frac{16xy^2 - 6x(x^2 + y^2)^2}{6y(x^2 + y^2)^2 - 16x^2y}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to determine the slope:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{dy}{dx} \\Bigg|_{(-1,1)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{16(-1)(1)^2 - 6(-1)((-1)^2 + (1)^2)^2}{6(1)((-1)^2 + (1)^2)^2 - 16(-1)^2(1)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{8}{8} \\\\\n		&= 1\n	}$\n</div>\nNext we form the line as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x) = x + b\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere we evaluate $b$ by using the point already known:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(-1) &= -1 + b \\\\\n		1 &= -1 + b \\\\\n		b &= 2\n	}$\n</div>\nSo the final solution is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x) = x + 2\n	}$\n</div>'),(400,'Example_7',7,106,'Find the equation of the tangent line to the graph of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^2 + (y - x)^3 = 9\n	}$\n</div>\nat $x = 1$.','To accomplish this we are going to find the point of interest and instantaneous rate of change. For the point:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(1)^2 + (y - (1))^3 &= 9 \\\\\n		(y - 1)^3 &= 8 \\\\\n		y - 1 &= 2 \\\\\n		y &= 3\n	}$\n</div>\nNext we need the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} 9 &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ x^2 + (y - x)^3 \\Big] \\\\\n		0 &= 2x + 3(y - x)^2 \\cdot (y\' - 1) \\\\\n		3y\'(y - x)^2 &= 3(y - x)^2 - 2x \\\\\n		y\' &= 1 - \\frac{2x}{3(y - x)^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to determine the slope:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} \\Bigg|_{(1,3)} &= 1 - \\frac{2(1)}{3((3) - (1))^2} \\\\\n		&= 1 - \\frac{2}{12} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{5}{6}\n	}$\n</div>\nNext we form the line as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y - 3 = \\frac{5}{6}(x - 1)\n	}$\n</div>'),(401,'Example_8',8,106,'Determine all points where the lines tangent to the graph of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^{\\frac{2}{3}} + y^{\\frac{2}{3}} = 8\n	}$\n</div>\nhave a slope of $-1$.','To observe the slope at all points we need the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ x^{\\frac{2}{3}} + y^{\\frac{2}{3}} \\Big] &= \\frac{d}{dx} 8 \\\\\n		\\frac{2}{3}x^{-\\frac{1}{3}} + \\frac{2}{3}y^{-\\frac{1}{3}}y\' &= 0 \\\\\n		y^{-\\frac{1}{3}}y\' &= -x^{-\\frac{1}{3}} \\\\\n		y\' &= -\\Big( \\frac{y}{x} \\Big)^{\\frac{1}{3}}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow if we want the slope to be $-1$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		-1 &= -\\Big( \\frac{y}{x} \\Big)^{\\frac{1}{3}} \\\\\n		1 &= \\Big( \\frac{y}{x} \\Big)^{\\frac{1}{3}} \\\\\n		1 &= \\frac{y}{x} \\\\\n		y &= x\n	}$\n</div>\nSo we now have two equations that have to be satisfied: the original equation of the graph and the condition on the slope. Plugging in the latter into the equation of the graph:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^{\\frac{2}{3}} + x^{\\frac{2}{3}} &= 8 \\\\\n		2x^{\\frac{2}{3}} &= 8 \\\\\n		x^{\\frac{2}{3}} &= 4 \\\\\n		x &= -8, 8\n	}$\n</div>\nWe now know the $x$-coordinates, and the $y$ counterparts are exactly the same due to the slope condition. Therefore, the points where the lines tangent to the graph have a slope of $-1$ are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(-8,-8) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} (8,8)\n	}$\n</div>'),(402,'Example_9',9,106,'Use implicit differentiation to prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\arcsin(x) = \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1 - x^2}}\n	}$\n</div>\nYou are allowed to use the derivative of sine.','Rewrite the equation and differentiate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= \\arcsin(x) \\\\\n		\\sin(y) &= x \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\sin(y) &= \\frac{d}{dx} x \\\\\n		\\cos(y)y\' &= 1 \\\\\n		y\' &= \\frac{1}{\\cos(y)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{\\cos(\\arcsin(x))}\n	}$\n</div>\nTo make sense of the last line let $\\theta = \\arcsin(x)$ which implies $\\sin(\\theta) = x$. A right triangle with such an angle has a opposite side with length $x$ and hypotenuse length $1$. Using the Pythagorean Theorem, the adjacent side has length $\\sqrt{1 - x^2}$. So the cosine of the angle is $\\cos(\\theta) = \\sqrt{1 - x^2}$. With this the derivative takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' &= \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1 - x^2}}\n	}$\n</div>'),(403,'Example_10',10,106,'Determine $y\'(x)$ for:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = y^x\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} y &= \\frac{d}{dx} y^x \\\\\n		y\' &= \\frac{d}{dx} e^{x\\ln(y)} \\\\\n		y\' &= \\Big( \\ln(y) + \\frac{x}{y}y\' \\Big) e^{x\\ln(y)} \\\\\n		y\'\\Big( 1 - \\frac{x}{y}y^x \\Big) &= \\ln(y)y^x \\\\\n		y\' &= \\frac{\\ln(y)y^x}{1 - xy^{x - 1}}\n	}$\n</div>'),(404,'Example_1',1,107,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = x^x\n	}$\n</div>','Take the logarithm of both sides and differentiate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) &= x^x \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= \\ln(x^x) \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= x\\ln(x) \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\ln(y(x)) &= \\frac{d}{dx} x\\ln(x) \\\\\n		\\frac{y\'(x)}{y(x)} &= \\ln(x) + 1 \\\\\n		y\'(x) &= y(x)(\\ln(x) + 1) \\\\\n		&= x^x(\\ln(x) + 1)\n	}$\n</div>'),(405,'Example_2',2,107,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = x^{e^x}\n	}$\n</div>','Take the logarithm of both sides and differentiate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) &= x^{e^x} \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= \\ln\\Big( x^{e^x} \\Big) \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= e^x\\ln(x) \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\ln(y(x)) &= \\frac{d}{dx} e^x\\ln(x) \\\\\n		\\frac{y\'(x)}{y(x)} &= e^x\\ln(x) + \\frac{e^x}{x} \\\\\n		y\'(x) &= y(x)\\Big( e^x\\ln(x) + \\frac{e^x}{x} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= x^{e^x} \\Big( e^x\\ln(x) + \\frac{e^x}{x} \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>'),(406,'Example_3',3,107,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = (3x^2 + 5)^{\\frac{1}{x}}\n	}$\n</div>','Take the logarithm of both sides and differentiate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) &= (3x^2 + 5)^{\\frac{1}{x}} \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= \\ln\\Big( (3x^2 + 5)^{\\frac{1}{x}} \\Big) \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= \\frac{\\ln(3x^2 + 5)}{x} \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\ln(y(x)) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\frac{\\ln(3x^2 + 5)}{x} \\\\\n		\\frac{y\'(x)}{y(x)} &= \\frac{\\frac{6x^2}{3x^2 + 5} - \\ln(3x^2 + 5)}{x^2} \\\\\n		y\'(x) &= y(x) \\cdot \\frac{\\frac{6x^2}{3x^2 + 5} - \\ln(3x^2 + 5)}{x^2} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{6(3x^2 + 5)^{\\frac{1}{x}}}{3x^2 + 5} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - \\frac{(3x^2 + 5)^{\\frac{1}{x}}\\ln(3x^2 + 5)}{x^2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(407,'Example_4',4,107,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = (\\sin(x))^{x^3}\n	}$\n</div>','Take the logarithm of both sides and differentiate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) &= (\\sin(x))^{x^3} \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= \\ln((\\sin(x))^{x^3}) \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= x^3\\ln(\\sin(x)) \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\ln(y(x)) &= \\frac{d}{dx} x^3\\ln(\\sin(x)) \\\\\n		\\frac{y\'(x)}{y(x)} &= 3x^2\\ln(\\sin(x)) + \\frac{\\cos(x)x^3}{\\sin(x)} \\\\\n		y\'(x) &= 3x^2\\ln(\\sin(x))y(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\frac{\\cos(x)x^3}{\\sin(x)}y(x) \\\\\n		&= 3x^2(\\sin(x))^{x^3}\\ln(\\sin(x)) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\cos(x)x^3(\\sin(x))^{x^3 - 1}\n	}$\n</div>'),(408,'Example_5',5,107,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = 7x(\\cos(x))^{\\frac{x}{2}}\n	}$\n</div>','Take the logarithm of both sides and differentiate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) &= 7x(\\cos(x))^{\\frac{x}{2}} \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= \\ln(7x(\\cos(x))^{\\frac{x}{2}}) \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= \\ln(7x) + \\frac{x}{2}\\ln(\\cos(x)) \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\ln(y(x)) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ \\ln(7x) + \\frac{x}{2}\\ln(\\cos(x)) \\Big] \\\\\n		\\frac{y\'(x)}{y(x)} &= \\frac{1}{x} + \\frac{1}{2}\\ln(\\cos(x)) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - \\frac{x\\sin(x)}{2\\cos(x)} \\\\\n		y\'(x) &= \\frac{1}{x}y(x) + \\frac{1}{2}\\ln(\\cos(x))y(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - \\frac{x\\sin(x)}{2\\cos(x)}y(x) \\\\\n		&= 7(\\cos(x))^{\\frac{x}{2}} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\frac{7}{2}\\ln(\\cos(x))x(\\cos(x))^{\\frac{x}{2}} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - \\frac{7x^2\\sin(x)(\\cos(x))^{\\frac{x}{2} - 1}}{2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(409,'Example_6',6,107,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = x^{\\ln(x)}(\\sec(x))^{3x}\n	}$\n</div>','Take the logarithm of both sides and differentiate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) &= x^{\\ln(x)}(\\sec(x))^{3x} \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= \\ln(x^{\\ln(x)}(\\sec(x))^{3x}) \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= \\ln(x)\\ln(x) + 3x\\ln(\\sec(x)) \\\\\n		(\\ln(y(x)))\' &= \\Big[ (\\ln(x))^2 + 3x\\ln(\\sec(x)) \\Big]\' \\\\\n		\\frac{y\'(x)}{y(x)} &= \\frac{2\\ln(x)}{x} + 3\\ln(\\sec(x)) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 3x\\tan(x) \\\\\n		y\'(x) &= \\frac{2\\ln(x)}{x}y(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 3\\ln(\\sec(x))y(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 3x\\tan(x)y(x) \\\\\n		&= 2\\ln(x)x^{\\ln(x) - 1}(\\sec(x))^{3x} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 3\\ln(\\sec(x))x^{\\ln(x)}(\\sec(x))^{3x} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 3x^{\\ln(x) + 1}(\\sec(x))^{3x}\\tan(x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(410,'Example_7',7,107,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = \\frac{(\\ln(x))^x}{2^{3x + 1}}\n	}$\n</div>','Take the logarithm of both sides and differentiate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) &= \\frac{(\\ln(x))^x}{2^{3x + 1}} \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= \\ln\\Big( \\frac{(\\ln(x))^x}{2^{3x + 1}} \\Big) \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= x\\ln(\\ln(x)) - (3x + 1)\\ln(2) \\\\\n		(\\ln(y(x)))\' &= \\Big[ x\\ln(\\ln(x)) - (3x + 1)\\ln(2) \\Big]\' \\\\\n		\\frac{y\'(x)}{y(x)} &= \\ln(\\ln(x)) + \\frac{1}{\\ln(x)} - 3\\ln(2) \\\\\n		y\'(x) &= \\ln(\\ln(x))y(x) + \\frac{y(x)}{\\ln(x)} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 3\\ln(2)y(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{(\\ln(x))^x\\ln(\\ln(x))}{2^{3x + 1}} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\frac{(\\ln(x))^{x - 1}}{2^{3x + 1}} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - \\frac{(3\\ln(2)\\ln(x))^x}{2^{3x + 1}}\n	}$\n</div>'),(411,'Example_8',8,107,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = (1 - 3x)^{\\cos(x)}\n	}$\n</div>','Take the logarithm of both sides and differentiate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) &= (1 - 3x)^{\\cos(x)} \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= \\ln((1- 3x)^{\\cos(x)}) \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= \\cos(x)\\ln(1 - 3x) \\\\\n		(\\ln(y(x)))\' &= \\Big[ \\cos(x)\\ln(1 - 3x) \\Big]\' \\\\\n		\\frac{y\'(x)}{y(x)} &= -\\sin(x)\\ln(1 - 3x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - \\frac{3\\cos(x)}{1 - 3x} \\\\\n		y\'(x) &= -\\sin(x)\\ln(1 - 3x)y(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - \\frac{3\\cos(x)y(x)}{1 - 3x} \\\\\n		&= \\ln\\Bigg( \\Big( \\frac{1}{1 - 3x} \\Big)^{\\sin(x)(1 - 3x)^{\\cos(x)}} \\Bigg) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 3\\cos(x)(1 - 3x)^{\\cos(x) - 1}\n	}$\n</div>'),(412,'Example_9',9,107,'Consider the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = \\pi^2 + 2^x + x^2 + x^{\\frac{1}{x}}\n	}$\n</div>\nDetermine the slope of the line perpendicular to the graph at $x = 1$.','First we need to determine:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) &= x^{\\frac{1}{x}} \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= \\ln(x^{\\frac{1}{x}}) \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= \\frac{\\ln(x)}{x} \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\ln(y(x)) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\frac{\\ln(x)}{x} \\\\\n		\\frac{y\'(x)}{y(x)} &= \\frac{1 - \\ln(x)}{x^2} \\\\\n		y\'(x) &= y(x) \\frac{1 - \\ln(x)}{x^2} \\\\\n		&= x^{\\frac{1}{x}} \\frac{1 - \\ln(x)}{x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to determine the slope we need the derivative of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'(x) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ \\pi^2 + 2^x + x^2 + x^{\\frac{1}{x}} \\Big] \\\\\n		&= \\ln(2)2^x + 2x + x^{\\frac{1}{x}} \\frac{1 - \\ln(x)}{x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nAt $x = 1$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&y\'(1) \\\\\n		&= \\ln(2)2^{(1)} + 2(1) + (1)^{\\frac{1}{(1)}} \\frac{1 - \\ln((1))}{(1)^2} \\\\\n		&= 2\\ln(2) + 3\n	}$\n</div>\nSince we want the slope to the perpendicular line, we want the negative reciprocal:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		m = -\\frac{1}{2\\ln(2) + 3}\n	}$\n</div>'),(413,'Example_10',10,107,'You are given that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} x^x = x^x (\\ln(x) + 1)\n	}$\n</div>\nand tetration, the next hyperoperation after exponentiation, is defined as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		{\\ ^{n}x = \\ \\atop {\\ }} {{\\underbrace{x^{x^{\\cdot^{\\cdot^{x}}}}}} \\atop n}\n	}$\n</div>\nDetermine the first derivative of the general tetration function by developing a recursive algorithm.','We are given the base case, so all that is left is the general step:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) &= {}^{n}x \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= \\ln({}^{n}x) \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= \\ln\\Bigg( x^{x^{\\cdot^{\\cdot^{x}}}} \\Bigg) \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= {}^{n - 1}x \\ln(x) \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\ln(y(x)) &= \\frac{d}{dx} ({}^{n - 1}x \\ln(x)) \\\\\n		\\frac{y\'(x)}{y(x)} &= \\ln(x) \\frac{d}{dx} ({}^{n - 1}x) + \\frac{{}^{n - 1}x}{x} \\\\\n		y\'(x) &= y(x)\\ln(x) \\frac{d}{dx} ({}^{n - 1}x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\frac{{}^{n - 1}x}{x}y(x) \\\\\n		&= {}^{n}x \\ln(x) \\frac{d}{dx} ({}^{n - 1}x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\frac{{}^{n - 1}x \\cdot {}^{n}x}{x}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we have everything we need. The algorithm involves a function that performs the following:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{Procedure}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$> 2$</td>\n		    <td>Take the derivative of the function according to the general rule and have it call on itself inside with the parameter $n - 1$ instead of $n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$= 2$</td>\n		    <td>Take the derivative of the function according to the base case</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(414,'Example_1',1,114,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\pi\\sin(x) + \\cos(x)\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} f(x) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ \\pi\\sin(x) + \\cos(x) \\Big] \\\\\n		&= \\pi\\frac{d}{dx} \\sin(x) + \\frac{d}{dx} \\cos(x) \\\\\n		&= \\pi\\cos(x) - \\sin(x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(415,'Example_2',2,114,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\frac{3^{2x}}{\\pi}\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} f(x) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\frac{3^{2x}}{\\pi} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{\\pi} \\frac{d}{dx} 9^x \\\\\n		&= \\frac{\\ln(9)9^x}{\\pi}\n	}$\n</div>'),(416,'Example_3',3,114,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\log_{7}(x^e)\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} f(x) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\log_{7}(x^e) \\\\\n		&= e\\frac{d}{dx} \\log_{7}(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{e}{\\ln(7)x}\n	}$\n</div>'),(417,'Example_4',4,114,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\pi\\arcsin(x) + 2\\tan(x)\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} f(x) &= \\frac{d}{dx} (\\pi\\arcsin(x) + 2\\tan(x)) \\\\\n		&= \\pi\\frac{d}{dx} \\arcsin(x) + 2\\frac{d}{dx} \\tan(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{\\pi}{\\sqrt{1 - x^2}} + 2\\sec^2(x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(418,'Example_5',5,114,'Find the derivative of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = e^{\\alpha x} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} \\alpha \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} f(x) &= \\frac{d}{dx} e^{\\alpha x} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} (e^{\\alpha})^x \\\\\n		&= \\ln(e^{\\alpha})(e^{\\alpha})^x \\\\\n		&= \\alpha e^{\\alpha x}\n	}$\n</div>'),(419,'Example_6',6,114,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\frac{\\log_{22}(x)}{\\log_{22}(\\pi)}\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\frac{\\log_{22}(x)}{\\log_{22}(\\pi)} &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\log_{\\pi}(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{\\ln(\\pi)x}\n	}$\n</div>'),(420,'Example_7',7,114,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} (\\cos^2(\\kappa x) + \\sin^2(\\kappa x)) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} \\kappa \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} (\\cos^2(\\kappa x) + \\sin^2(\\kappa x)) &= \\frac{d}{dx} 1 \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(421,'Example_8',8,114,'Evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} (\\cosh^2(\\kappa x) - \\sinh^2(\\kappa x)) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} \\kappa \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} (\\cosh^2(\\kappa x) + \\sinh^2(\\kappa x)) &= \\frac{d}{dx} 1 \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(422,'Example_9',9,114,'Using $\\textit{Euler\'s Formula}$ the following can be deduced:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sin(x) = \\frac{e^{ix} - e^{-ix}}{2i} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} \\cos(x) = \\frac{e^{ix} + e^{-ix}}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $i$ is the imaginary number. Using these definitions prove:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\sin(x) = \\cos(x)\n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\sin(x) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\frac{e^{ix} - e^{-ix}}{2i} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{2i} \\Big[ \\frac{d}{dx} (e^i)^x - (e^{-i})^x \\Big] \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{2i} \\Big[ \\ln(e^i)e^{ix} - \\ln(e^{-i})e^{-ix} \\Big] \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{2i} \\Big[ ie^{ix} + ie^{-ix} \\Big] \\\\\n		&= \\frac{e^{ix} - e^{-ix}}{2} \\\\\n		&= \\cos(x)\n	}$\n</div>'),(423,'Example_10',10,114,'Prove:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\ln\\Big( \\prod_{i = 1}^n (f_i(x))^{\\alpha_i} \\Big) = \\sum_{i = 1}^n \\alpha_i \\frac{d}{dx} \\ln(f_i(x)) \n	}$\n</div>','<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} \\ln\\Big( \\prod_{i = 1}^n (f_i(x))^{\\alpha_i} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\sum_{i = 1}^n \\ln((f_i(x))^{\\alpha_i}) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\sum_{i = 1}^n \\alpha_i \\ln(f_i(x)) \\\\\n		&= \\sum_{i = 1}^n \\frac{d}{dx} \\alpha_i \\ln(f_i(x)) \\\\\n		&= \\sum_{i = 1}^n \\alpha_i \\frac{d}{dx} \\ln(f_i(x))\n	}$\n</div>'),(424,'Example_1',1,115,'For the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^2 - 8x + 4\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the intervals on which the function is increasing or decreasing, and any relative extremas.','To observe the behavior we need the first derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = 2x - 8\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the only critical point is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x = 4\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we observe, for any value to the left of the critical point the derivative is negative. To the right of the critical point the derivative is positive. Therefore:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is decreasing on} \\hspace{.3cm} (-\\infty, 4) \\\\\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is increasing on} \\hspace{.3cm} (4, \\infty) \\\\\n		x = 4 \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is a relative minimum}\n	}$\n</div>'),(425,'Example_2',2,115,'For the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = 2x^3 - 9x^2 - 108x + 2\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine all of the critical points and identify the relative extremas.','To observe the behavior we need the first derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = 6x^2 - 18x - 108\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the critical points are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= x^2 - 3x - 18 \\\\\n		&= (x - 6)(x + 3) \\\\\n		x &= -3, 6\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we observe the behavior of the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>Domain</td>\n		    <td>$f\'(x)$ Behavior</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(-\\infty, -3)$</td>\n		    <td>$+$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(-3, 6)$</td>\n		    <td>$-$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(6, \\infty)$</td>\n		    <td>$+$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nWith this we can state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x = -3 \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is a relative maximum} \\\\\n		x = 6 \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is a relative minimum}\n	}$\n</div>'),(426,'Example_3',3,115,'For the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^2e^x\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the intervals on which the function is increasing or decreasing, and any relative extremas.','To observe the behavior we need the first derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = 2xe^x + x^2e^x\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the critical points are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 2xe^x + x^2e^x \\\\\n		&= (x^2 + 2x)e^x \\\\\n		&= x(x + 2) \\\\\n		x &= -2, 0\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we observe the behavior of the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>Domain</td>\n		    <td>$f\'(x)$ Behavior</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(-\\infty, -2)$</td>\n		    <td>$+$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(-2, 0)$</td>\n		    <td>$-$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(0, \\infty)$</td>\n		    <td>$+$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nWith this we can state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is decreasing on} \\hspace{.3cm} (-2, 0) \\\\\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is increasing on} \\\\\n		&(-\\infty, -2) \\cup (0, \\infty) \\\\\n		x = -2 \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is a relative maximum} \\\\\n		x = 0 \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is a relative minimum}\n	}$\n</div>'),(427,'Example_4',4,115,'For the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = |x^2 - 9|\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the intervals on which the function is increasing or decreasing, and any relative extremas.','To observe the behavior we need the first derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = \\begin{cases}\n			2x & x < -3 \\\\\n			-2x & -3 < x < 3 \\\\\n			2x & x > 3\n		\\end{cases}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the critical points are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x = -3, 0, 3\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we observe the behavior of the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>Domain</td>\n		    <td>$f\'(x)$ Behavior</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(-\\infty, -3)$</td>\n		    <td>$-$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(-3, 0)$</td>\n		    <td>$+$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(0, 3)$</td>\n		    <td>$-$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(3, \\infty)$</td>\n		    <td>$+$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nWith this we can state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is decreasing on} \\\\\n		&(-\\infty, -3) \\cup (0, 3) \\\\\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is increasing on} \\\\\n		&(-3, 0) \\cup (3, \\infty) \\\\\n		x = 0 \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is a relative maximum} \\\\\n		x = -3,3 \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{are relative minimums}\n	}$\n</div>'),(428,'Example_5',5,115,'For the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\ln(x^2 + 1)\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the intervals on which the function is increasing or decreasing, and any relative extremas.','To observe the behavior we need the first derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = \\frac{2x}{x^2 + 1}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the only critical point is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we observe the behavior of the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>Domain</td>\n		    <td>$f\'(x)$ Behavior</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(-\\infty, 0)$</td>\n		    <td>$-$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(0, \\infty)$</td>\n		    <td>$+$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nWith this we can state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is decreasing on} \\hspace{.3cm} (-\\infty, 0) \\\\\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is increasing on} \\hspace{.3cm} (0, \\infty) \\\\\n		x = 0 \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is a relative minimum}\n	}$\n</div>'),(429,'Example_6',6,115,'For the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\sqrt{4x - x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\ndetermine the intervals on which the function is increasing or decreasing, and any relative extremas.','To observe the behavior we need the first derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = \\frac{4 - 2x}{2\\sqrt{4x - x^2}}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere we restrict ourselves to the open interval $(0,4)$ for the derivative. We do not consider boundaries as we only know behavior of one side and so the only critical point is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 4 - 2x \\\\\n		x &= 2\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we observe the behavior of the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>Domain</td>\n		    <td>$f\'(x)$ Behavior</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(0, 2)$</td>\n		    <td>$+$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(2, 4)$</td>\n		    <td>$-$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nWith this we can state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is decreasing on} \\hspace{.3cm} (2, 4) \\\\\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is increasing on} \\hspace{.3cm} (0, 2) \\\\\n		x = 2 \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is a relative maximum}\n	}$\n</div>'),(430,'Example_7',7,115,'For the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^4 - 4x^3\n	}$\n</div>\nprovide a rough sketch based on the behavior of the derivative.','To observe the behavior we need the first derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = 4x^3 - 12x^2\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the critical points are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 4x^3 - 12x^2 \\\\\n		&= 4x^2(x - 3) \\\\\n		x &= 0, 3\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we observe the behavior of the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>Domain</td>\n		    <td>$f\'(x)$ Behavior</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(-\\infty, 0)$</td>\n		    <td>$-$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(0, 3)$</td>\n		    <td>$-$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(3, \\infty)$</td>\n		    <td>$+$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nWith this we can state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is decreasing on} \\hspace{.3cm} (-\\infty, 0) \\cup (0, 3) \\\\\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is increasing on} \\hspace{.3cm} (3, \\infty) \\\\\n		x = 3 \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is a relative minimum}\n	}$\n</div>\nSomething else that may interest us are the roots:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= x^4 - 4x^3 \\\\\n		&= x^3(x - 4) \\\\\n		x &= 0, 4\n	}$\n</div>\nWith all of this information we make the graph:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/Implications_of_the_First_Derivative/Example_7.png\">\n</div>'),(431,'Example_8',8,115,'Let:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = ax^2 + bx + c \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} a \\neq 0\n	}$\n</div>\nShow that $f$ has exactly one critical point and give conditions on $a$ and $b$ which guarantee that the critical point will be a maximum.','First we need the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = 2ax + b\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the critical point is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 2ax + b \\\\\n		x &= -\\frac{b}{2a}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we observe that the derivative is nothing but a straight line and if we want the critical point to be a relative maximum then by the First Derivative Test the derivative has to transition from positive to negative. This transition can only occur if the slope is negative and no matter the value for $b$. Therefore, to always attain a maximum we enforce:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		a < 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} b \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>'),(432,'Example_9',9,115,'Find the point $(x,y)$ on the graph:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = 4 - x^{\\frac{1}{2}}\n	}$\n</div>\nthat is closest to the point $(3,4)$.','We setup the distance function to be:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		d^2(x) &= (x - x_0)^2 + (y - y_0)^2 \\\\\n		&= (x - 3)^2 + (4 - x^{\\frac{1}{2}} - 4)^2 \\\\\n		&= (x - 3)^2 + x\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we want to minimize the distance function, which is equivalent to minimizing the distance squared. So let:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = d^2(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the derivative is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = 2(x - 3) + 1 = 2x - 5\n	}$\n</div>\nproviding the critical point:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x = \\frac{5}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we observe the behavior of the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>Domain</td>\n		    <td>$f\'(x)$ Behavior</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\Big( -\\infty, \\frac{5}{2} \\Big)$</td>\n		    <td>$-$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\Big( \\frac{5}{2}, \\infty \\Big)$</td>\n		    <td>$+$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nAccording to the First Derivative Test we can state that our critical point is a relative minimum. Therefore, the closest point is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\Bigg( \\frac{5}{2}, 4 - \\sqrt{\\frac{5}{2}} \\Bigg)\n	}$\n</div>'),(433,'Example_10',10,115,'Determine two real numbers with difference $\\kappa$ and minimum possible product. You can assume $\\kappa \\in \\mathbb{R}_{> 0}$.','We setup our product function as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x,y) = xy\n	}$\n</div>\nwith the condition that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = x + \\kappa\n	}$\n</div>\nprovides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x(x + \\kappa) = x^2 + \\kappa x\n	}$\n</div>\nTo find a minimum we need the first derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = 2x + \\kappa\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the critical point is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x = -\\frac{\\kappa}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we observe the behavior of the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>Domain</td>\n		    <td>$f\'(x)$ Behavior</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\Big( -\\infty, -\\frac{\\kappa}{2} \\Big)$</td>\n		    <td>$-$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\Big( -\\frac{\\kappa}{2}, \\infty \\Big)$</td>\n		    <td>$+$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nAccording to the First Derivative Test we can state that our critical point is a relative minimum. Therefore, the two real numbers we want are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x = -\\frac{\\kappa}{2} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} y = \\frac{\\kappa}{2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(434,'Example_1',1,116,'Describe the concavity of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = 2x^3 - 3x^2 - 4\n	}$\n</div>\nand classify the critical points according to the Second Derivative Test.','To get everything we need, we have to determine both the first and second derivatives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= 6x^2 - 6x \\\\\n		f\'\'(x) &= 12x - 6\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to determine the critical points we equate the first derivative to zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 6x^2 - 6x \\\\\n		0 &= 6x(x - 1) \\\\\n		x &= 0, 1\n	}$\n</div>\nand to classify the points we plug them into the second derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'\'(0) &= -6 \\\\\n		f\'\'(1) &= 6\n	}$\n</div>\nSo we arrive at stating that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x &= 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{is a relative maximum} \\\\\n		x &= 1 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{is a relative minimum}\n	}$\n</div>\nTo observe the concavity behavior we need to determine where the second derivative is zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 12x - 6 \\\\\n		x &= \\frac{1}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich allows us to state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is concave downwards on} \\\\\n		&\\Big( -\\infty, \\frac{1}{2} \\Big) \\\\\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is concave upwards on} \\hspace{.3cm} \\Big( \\frac{1}{2}, \\infty \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>'),(435,'Example_2',2,116,'Describe the concavity of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\sin(2x)\n	}$\n</div>\nand classify the critical points according to the Second Derivative Test on the interval $(0, \\pi)$.','To get everything we need, we have to determine both the first and second derivatives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= 2\\cos(2x) \\\\\n		f\'\'(x) &= -4\\sin(2x)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to determine the critical points we equate the first derivative to zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 2\\cos(2x) \\\\\n		2x &= \\frac{\\pi}{2} + \\kappa \\pi \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} \\kappa \\in \\mathbb{Z} \\\\\n		x &= \\frac{\\pi(1 + 2\\kappa)}{4}\n	}$\n</div>\nand to classify the points we plug the only ones in the region into the second derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'\'\\Big( \\frac{\\pi}{4} \\Big) &= -4 \\\\\n		f\'\'\\Big( \\frac{3\\pi}{4} \\Big) &= 4\n	}$\n</div>\nSo we arrive at stating that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x &= \\frac{\\pi}{4} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{is a relative maximum} \\\\\n		x &= \\frac{3\\pi}{4} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{is a relative minimum}\n	}$\n</div>\nTo observe the concavity behavior we need to determine where the second derivative is zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= -4\\sin(2x) \\\\\n		2x &= \\alpha \\pi \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} \\alpha \\in \\mathbb{Z} \\\\\n		x &= \\frac{\\alpha \\pi}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich allows us to state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x)& \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{is concave downwards on} \\hspace{.3cm} \\Big( 0, \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\Big) \\\\\n		f(x)& \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{is concave upwards on} \\hspace{.3cm} \\Big( \\frac{\\pi}{2}, \\pi \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>'),(436,'Example_3',3,116,'Describe the concavity of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^4 - 2x^2 + 3\n	}$\n</div>\nand classify the critical points according to the Second Derivative Test.','To get everything we need, we have to determine both the first and second derivatives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= 4x^3 - 4x \\\\\n		f\'\'(x) &= 12x^2 - 4\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to determine the critical points we equate the first derivative to zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 4x^3 - 4x \\\\\n		0 &= 4x(x^2 - 1) \\\\\n		0 &= 4x(x - 1)(x + 1)\n	}$\n</div>\nand to classify the points we plug them into the second derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'\'(-1) &= 8 \\\\\n		f\'\'(0) &= -4 \\\\\n		f\'\'(1) &= 8\n	}$\n</div>\nSo we arrive at stating that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x &= -1 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{is a relative minimum} \\\\\n		x &= 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{is a relative maximum} \\\\\n		x &= 1 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{is a relative minimum}\n	}$\n</div>\nTo observe the concavity behavior we need to determine where the second derivative is zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 12x^2 - 4 \\\\\n		1 &= 3x^2 \\\\\n		x &= \\pm \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich allows us to state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is concave upwards on} \\\\\n		&\\Big( -\\infty, -\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} \\Big) \\\\\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is concave downwards on} \\\\\n		&\\Big( -\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}, \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}} \\Big) \\\\\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is concave upwards on} \\\\\n		&\\Big( \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{3}}, \\infty \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>'),(437,'Example_4',4,116,'Describe the concavity of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = 6x + \\sin(3x)\n	}$\n</div>\nand classify the critical points according to the Second Derivative Test on the interval $\\Big( 0, \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\Big)$.','To get everything we need, we have to determine both the first and second derivatives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= 6 + 3\\cos(3x) \\\\\n		f\'\'(x) &= -9\\sin(3x)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to determine the critical points we equate the first derivative to zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 6 + 3\\cos(3x) \\\\\n		0 &= 3 + \\cos(3x)\n	}$\n</div>\nSo we arrive at stating that there are no critical points. To observe the concavity behavior we need to determine where the second derivative is zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= -9\\sin(3x) \\\\\n		0 &= \\sin(3x) \\\\\n		3x &= \\kappa \\pi \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} \\kappa \\in \\mathbb{Z} \\\\\n		x &= \\frac{\\kappa \\pi}{3}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich allows us to state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x)& \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{is concave downwards on} \\hspace{.3cm} \\Big( 0, \\frac{\\pi}{3} \\Big) \\\\\n		f(x)& \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{is concave wpwards on} \\hspace{.3cm} \\Big( \\frac{\\pi}{3}, \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>'),(438,'Example_5',5,116,'Describe the concavity of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^2 + \\frac{1}{x}\n	}$\n</div>\nand classify the critical points according to the Second Derivative Test.','To get everything we need, we have to determine both the first and second derivatives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= 2x - \\frac{1}{x^2} \\\\\n		f\'\'(x) &= 2 + \\frac{2}{x^3}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to determine the critical points we equate the first derivative to zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 2x - \\frac{1}{x^2} \\\\\n		0 &= \\frac{2x^3 - 1}{x^2} \\\\\n		0 &= 2x^3 - 1 \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{2} &= x^3 \\\\\n		x &= \\frac{1}{2^{\\frac{1}{3}}}\n	}$\n</div>\nand to classify the point we plug it into the second derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'\'(0) &= \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{DNE} \\\\\n		f\'\'\\Big( \\frac{1}{2^{\\frac{1}{3}}} \\Big) &= 6 \n	}$\n</div>\nSo we arrive at stating that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x = \\frac{1}{2^{\\frac{1}{3}}} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{is a relative minimum} \n	}$\n</div>\nTo observe the concavity behavior we need to determine where the second derivative is zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 2 + \\frac{2}{x^3} \\\\\n		0 &= \\frac{2x^3 + 2}{x^3} \\\\\n		0 &= x^3 + 1 \\\\\n		x &= -1\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich allows us to state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x)& \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{is concave upwards on} \\hspace{.3cm} (-\\infty, -1) \\\\\n		f(x)& \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{is concave downwards on} \\hspace{.3cm} (-1, 0) \\\\\n		f(x)& \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{is concave upwards on} \\hspace{.3cm} (0, \\infty)\n	}$\n</div>'),(439,'Example_6',6,116,'Describe the concavity of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\ln(x) - x\n	}$\n</div>\nand classify the critical points according to the Second Derivative Test.','To get everything we need, we have to determine both the first and second derivatives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= \\frac{1}{x} - 1 \\\\\n		f\'\'(x) &= -\\frac{1}{x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to determine the critical points we equate the first derivative to zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= \\frac{1}{x} - 1 \\\\\n		1 &= \\frac{1}{x} \\\\\n		x &= 1\n	}$\n</div>\nand to classify the points we plug them into the second derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'\'(0) &= \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{DNE} \\\\\n		f\'\'(1) &= -1\n	}$\n</div>\nSo we arrive at stating that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x = 1 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{is a relative maximum}\n	}$\n</div>\nTo observe the concavity behavior we need to determine where the second derivative is zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = -\\frac{1}{x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich allows us to state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{is concave negative on} \\hspace{.3cm} ( 0, \\infty )\n	}$\n</div>'),(440,'Example_7',7,116,'Given the graph of a function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/Implications_of_the_Second_Derivative/Example_7_Problem.png\">\n</div>\nsketch out the second derivative.','Observing the given function we can make the following notes:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is increasing on} \\\\\n		&(-1.6, 0) \\cup (1.6, 3.1) \\\\\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is decreasing on} \\\\\n		&(-3.1, -1.6) \\cup (0, 1.6) \\\\\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{has relative maximums at} \\\\\n		&x = -2.4, 0.8 \\\\\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{has relative minimums at} \\\\\n		&x = -0.8, 2.4 \\\\\n	}$\n</div>\nSo at the extremas the first derivative is exactly zero and we know the rest of the behavior on the intervals, so we should have something similar to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/Implications_of_the_Second_Derivative/Example_7_First_Derivative.png\">\n</div>\nNow we observe the behavior of slope to the first derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is increasing on} \\hspace{.3cm} (-3.1, -2.4) \\\\\n		&\\cup \\hspace{.1cm} (-0.8, 0.8) \\cup (2.4, 3.1) \\\\\n		f\'(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is decreasing on} \\\\\n		&(-2.4, -0.8) \\cup (0.8, 2.4) \\\\\n		f\'(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{has a relative maximum at} \\\\\n		&x = 0 \\\\\n		f\'(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{has relative minimums at} \\\\\n		&x = -1.6, 1.6 \\\\\n	}$\n</div>\nand graph the behavior as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/Implications_of_the_Second_Derivative/Example_7_Second_Derivative.png\">\n</div>'),(441,'Example_8',8,116,'Given the graph of a function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/Implications_of_the_Second_Derivative/Example_8_Problem.png\">\n</div>\nsketch out the second derivative.','Observing the given function we can make the following notes:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x)& \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{is increasing on} \\hspace{.3cm} (-5,0) \\\\\n		f(x)& \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{is decreasing on} \\hspace{.3cm} (0, 5) \\\\\n		f(x)& \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{has relative maximums at} \\hspace{.3cm} x = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nSo at the extremas the first derivative is exactly zero and we know the rest of the behavior on the intervals, so we should have something similar to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/Implications_of_the_Second_Derivative/Example_8_First_Derivative.png\">\n</div>\nNow we observe the behavior of slope to the first derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is increasing on} \\hspace{.3cm} (-5, -3) \\\\\n		f\'(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is decreasing on} \\hspace{.3cm} (-3, 5) \\\\\n		f\'(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{is decreasing approximately} \\\\\n		&\\text{at a constant rate on} \\hspace{.3cm} (-2, 2) \\\\\n		f\'(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{has a relative maximum at} \\\\\n		&x = -3\n	}$\n</div>\nand graph the behavior as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/Implications_of_the_Second_Derivative/Example_8_Second_Derivative.png\">\n</div>'),(442,'Example_9',9,116,'Describe the concavity along with the inflection points of the graph corresponding to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^2 + y^2 = c^2 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} c \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>','To get a feeling for the concavity we need the second derivative, but before that we determine the first derivative using implicit differentiation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ x^2 + y^2 \\Big] &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ c^2 \\Big] \\\\\n		2x + 2yy\' &= 0 \\\\\n		y\' &= -\\frac{x}{y}\n	}$\n</div>\nApplying the differentiation operator again:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ y\' \\Big] &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ -\\frac{x}{y} \\Big] \\\\\n		y\'\' &= -\\frac{y - xy\'}{y^2} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{y + \\frac{x^2}{y}}{y^2} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{y^2 + x^2}{y^3}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we observe the behavior of the above. Notice that the numerator is strictly positive, and thus the overall sign behavior will depend strictly on the denominator. So if $y$ is positive the second derivative is overall negative, and vice versa for negative $y$. When observing that the original implicit function represents a circle centered at the origin with radius $c$, the results make sense since the top half is concave down corresponding to positive $y$, and bottom half is concave up corresponding to negative $y$.'),(443,'Example_10',10,116,'Describe the concavity along with the inflection points of the graph corresponding to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = x^x \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} x \\in \\mathbb{R}_{> 0}\n	}$\n</div>','To get a feeling for the concavity we need the second derivative, but before that we determine the first derivative using logarithmic differentiation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= x^x \\\\\n		\\ln(y) &= \\ln(x^x) \\\\\n		\\ln(y) &= x\\ln(x) \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ \\ln(y) \\Big] &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ x\\ln(x) \\Big] \\\\\n		\\frac{y\'}{y} &= \\ln(x) + 1 \\\\\n		y\' &= y(\\ln(x) + 1)\n	}$\n</div>\nApplying the differentiation operator again:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ y\' \\Big] &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big[ y(\\ln(x) + 1) \\Big] \\\\\n		y\'\' &= y\'(\\ln(x) + 1) + y\\Big( \\frac{1}{x} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= y(\\ln(x) + 1)^2 + \\frac{y}{x} \\\\\n		&= x^x \\Big[ (\\ln(x) + 1)^2 + \\frac{1}{x} \\Big]\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we observe the behavior of the above. Since we have already restricted ourselves to the non-negative real numbers, the term from the original function all the way on the left is strictly positive. Alongside this fact, the rest is also strictly positive because any positive number squared with the addition of another positive number is still positive. So overall we can state that the original function has no points of inflection and is strictly concave up on its entire domain.'),(444,'Example_1',1,117,'Determine the absolute maximum and minimum of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^2 - 5x + 7 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} x \\in [-1,3]\n	}$\n</div>','First we need the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = 2x - 5\n	}$\n</div>\nand the critical point:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 2x - 5 \\\\\n		x &= \\frac{5}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we compare the necessary evaluations:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\\Big( -1 \\Big) &= 13 \\\\\n		f\\Big( \\frac{5}{2} \\Big) &= \\frac{3}{4} \\\\\n		f\\Big( 3 \\Big) &= 1\n	}$\n</div>\nThis allows us to state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{has a absolute maximum of} \\hspace{.3cm} 13 \\\\\n		&\\text{achieved at} \\hspace{.3cm} x = -1 \\\\\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{has a absolute minimum of} \\hspace{.3cm} \\frac{3}{4} \\\\\n		&\\text{achieved at} \\hspace{.3cm} x = \\frac{5}{2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(445,'Example_2',2,117,'Determine the absolute maximum and minimum of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\sin(2x) + \\cos(x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} x \\in [0, \\pi]\n	}$\n</div>','First we need the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = 2\\cos(2x) - \\sin(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nand the critical points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 2\\cos(2x) - \\sin(x) \\\\\n		0 &= 2\\Big[ 1 - 2\\sin^2(x) \\Big] - \\sin(x) \\\\\n		0 &= -4\\sin^2(x) - \\sin(x) + 2 \\\\\n		0 &= 4\\sin^2(x) + \\sin(x) - 2 \\\\\n		\\sin(x) &= \\frac{-1 + \\sqrt{33}}{8} \\\\\n		x &= \\arcsin\\Big( \\frac{-1 + \\sqrt{33}}{8} \\Big) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} ,\\pi - \\arcsin\\Big( \\frac{-1 + \\sqrt{33}}{8} \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we compare the necessary evaluations:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(0) &= 1 \\\\\n		f(0.63487) &\\approx 1.76017 \\\\\n		f(2.50673) &\\approx -1.76017 \\\\\n		f(\\pi) &= -1\n	}$\n</div>\nThis allows us to state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{has a absolute maximum of} \\\\\n		&1.76017 \\hspace{.4cm} \\text{achieved at} \\hspace{.3cm} \\\\\n		&x = 0.63487 \\\\\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{has a absolute minimum of} \\\\\n		&-1.76017 \\hspace{.4cm} \\text{achieved at} \\hspace{.3cm} \\\\\n		&x = 2.50673\n	}$\n</div>'),(446,'Example_3',3,117,'Determine the absolute maximum and minimum of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^2e^x \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} x \\in [-5,1]\n	}$\n</div>','First we need the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = 2xe^x + x^2e^x\n	}$\n</div>\nand the critical points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 2xe^x + x^2e^x \\\\\n		0 &= (2 + x)xe^x \\\\\n		x &= -2, 0\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we compare the necessary evaluations:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(-5) &= 25e^{-5} \\\\\n		f(-2) &= 4e^{-2} \\\\\n		f(0) &= 0 \\\\\n		f(1) &= e\n	}$\n</div>\nThis allows us to state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{has a absolute maximum of} \\hspace{.3cm} e \\\\\n		&\\text{achieved at} \\hspace{.3cm} x = 1 \\\\\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{has a absolute minimum of} \\hspace{.3cm} 0 \\\\\n		&\\text{achieved at} \\hspace{.3cm} x = 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(447,'Example_4',4,117,'Determine the absolute maximum and minimum of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\ln(x^2 + 2x + 4) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} x \\in [-4,3]\n	}$\n</div>','First we need the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = \\frac{2x + 2}{x^2 + 2x + 4}\n	}$\n</div>\nand the critical point:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 2x + 2 \\\\\n		x &= -1\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we compare the necessary evaluations:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(-4) &= \\ln(12) \\\\\n		f(-1) &= \\ln(3) \\\\\n		f(3) &= \\ln(19)\n	}$\n</div>\nThis allows us to state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{has a absolute maximum of} \\hspace{.3cm} \\ln(19) \\\\\n		&\\text{achieved at} \\hspace{.3cm} x = -1 \\\\\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{has a absolute minimum of} \\hspace{.3cm} \\ln(3) \\\\\n		&\\text{achieved at} \\hspace{.3cm} x = 3\n	}$\n</div>'),(448,'Example_5',5,117,'Determine the absolute maximum and minimum of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = (x + 1)^{\\frac{2}{3}} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} x \\in [-3,4]\n	}$\n</div>','First we need the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = \\frac{2}{3(x + 1)^{\\frac{1}{3}}}\n	}$\n</div>\nand the critical point:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 3(x + 1)^{\\frac{1}{3}} \\\\\n		x &= -1\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we compare the necessary evaluations:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(-3) &= 2^{\\frac{2}{3}} \\\\\n		f(-1) &= 0 \\\\\n		f(4) &= 5^{\\frac{2}{3}}\n	}$\n</div>\nThis allows us to state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{has a absolute maximum of} \\hspace{.3cm} 5^{\\frac{2}{3}} \\\\\n		&\\text{achieved at} \\hspace{.3cm} x = 4 \\\\\n		f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{has a absolute minimum of} \\hspace{.3cm} 0 \\\\\n		&\\text{achieved at} \\hspace{.3cm} x = -1\n	}$\n</div>'),(449,'Example_6',6,117,'A stone is thrown straight up from the roof of an 80-ft building. The height, in feet, of the stone at any time $t$, in seconds, measured from the ground is given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(t) = -16t^2 + 64t + 80\n	}$\n</div>\nWhat is the maximum height the stone reaches?','First we need the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h\'(t) = -32t + 64\n	}$\n</div>\nand the critical point:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= -32t + 64 \\\\\n		t &= 2\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we compare the necessary evaluations:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(0) &= 80 \\\\\n		f(2) &= 144 \\\\\n		f(5) &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the last value corresponds to the time when the stone hits the ground. The above allows us to state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(t) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{has a absolute maximum of} \\hspace{.3cm} 144 \\\\\n		&\\text{achieved at} \\hspace{.3cm} t = 2\n	}$\n</div>'),(450,'Example_7',7,117,'A square sheet of tin $a$ inches on a side is to be used to make an open-top box by cutting a small square of tin from each corner and bending up the sides. How large a square should be cut from each corner in order that the box shall have as large a volume as possible?','On the square bottom we shall end up with sides of length:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		l = a - 2x\n	}$\n</div>\nsince $x$ is taken away from each side. As for the height it will exactly correspond to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h = x\n	}$\n</div>\nbecause it represents the width of the piece that gets bend upwards. Now we define the volume as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		V &= l^2h \\\\\n		&= x(a - 2x)^2\n	}$\n</div>\nand to determine the extrema we need the first derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		V\' = (a - 2x)^2 - 4x(a - 2x)\n	}$\n</div>\nEquating to zero will provide us the critical points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= (a - 2x)^2 - 4x(a - 2x) \\\\\n		0 &= (a - 2x)((a - 2x) - 4x) \\\\\n		0 &= (a - 2x)(a - 6x) \\\\\n		x &= \\frac{a}{6}, \\frac{a}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow using the fact that $x \\in \\Big[ 0, \\frac{a}{2} \\Big]$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		V\\Big( 0 \\Big) &= 0 \\\\\n		V\\Big( \\frac{a}{6} \\Big) &= \\frac{2a}{27} \\\\\n		V\\Big( \\frac{a}{2} \\Big) &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this we can state that in order to form the largest possible volume the optimal choice is $x = \\frac{a}{6}$.'),(451,'Example_8',8,117,'Show that the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = xe^x\n	}$\n</div>\nattains the same critical point as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x) = \\ln(x) + x\n	}$\n</div>\nand that at the critical point $x = c$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(c) = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} e^{g(x)}\n	}$\n</div>','Differentiating both functions gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= e^x + xe^x \\\\\n		g\'(x) &= \\frac{1}{x} + 1\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the critical points are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= e^x + xe^x \\\\\n		0 &= (1 + x)e^x \\\\\n		x &= -1 \\\\\n		&\\vdots \\\\\n		0 &= \\frac{1}{x} + 1 \\\\\n		-1 &= \\frac{1}{x} \\\\\n		x &= -1\n	}$\n</div>\nThe critical point is exactly the same and:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(-1) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -1} e^{g(x)} \\\\\n		-e^{-1} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -1} e^{\\ln(x) + x} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -1} xe^x \\\\\n		&= -e^{-1}\n	}$\n</div>'),(452,'Example_9',9,117,'Show that the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x) = \\ln(f(x))\n	}$\n</div>\nattains the same critical point(s) as $f(x)$ and that at the critical point(s) $x = c$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(c) = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} e^{g(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\nAlso show how on a bounded interval, $[a,b]$, the absolute extremas for $f(x)$ can be obtained through $g(x)$.','Differentiating the function gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g\'(x) = \\frac{f\'(x)}{f(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the critical points are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g\'(x) &= 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} f(x) \\neq 0, f\'(x) = 0 \\\\\n		g\'(x) &= \\text{DNE} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} f(x) = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nSince we care about $f\'(x)$ equating to zero typically we only care about the first scenario. Next we can use the original relationship:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\ln(f(x)) &= g(x) \\\\\n		f(x) &= e^{g(x)} \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} f(x) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} e^{g(x)} \\\\\n		f(c) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} e^{g(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\nand so if we wanted to determine the absolute extremas we would compare the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(a) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^+} e^{g(x)} \\\\\n		f(c) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} e^{g(x)} \\\\\n		f(b) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow b^-} e^{g(x)}\n	}$\n</div>'),(453,'Example_10',10,117,'Show that the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x) = \\sqrt{f(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\nattains the same critical point(s) as $f(x)$ and that at the critical point(s) $x = c$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(c) = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} (g(x))^2\n	}$\n</div>\nAlso show how on a bounded interval, $[a,b]$, the absolute extremas for $f(x)$ can be obtained through $g(x)$.','Differentiating the function gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g\'(x) = \\frac{f\'(x)}{2\\sqrt{f(x)}}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the critical points are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g\'(x) &= 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} f(x) \\neq 0, f\'(x) = 0 \\\\\n		g\'(x) &= \\text{DNE} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} f(x) = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nSince we care about $f\'(x)$ equating to zero typically we only care about the first scenario. Next we can use the original relationship:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sqrt{f(x)} &= g(x) \\\\\n		f(x) &= (g(x))^2 \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} f(x) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} (g(x))^2 \\\\\n		f(c) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} (g(x))^2\n	}$\n</div>\nand so if we wanted to determine the absolute extremas we would compare the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(a) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^+} (g(x))^2 \\\\\n		f(c) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} (g(x))^2 \\\\\n		f(b) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow b^-} (g(x))^2\n	}$\n</div>'),(454,'Example_1',1,118,'Find two non-negative numbers whose sum is $9$ and so that the product of one number and the square of the other number is a maximum.','First identify the objective function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x,y) = xy^2\n	}$\n</div>\nand the constraint function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x + y = 9 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} 0 \\leq x,y \\leq 9\n	}$\n</div>\nNow the objective function can be rewritten as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k(y) &= f(9 - y, y) \\\\\n		&= (9 - y)y^2\n	}$\n</div>\nDifferentiation gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k\'(y) &= -y^2 + 2y(9 - y)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the critical points are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= -y^2 + 2y(9 - y) \\\\\n		0 &= y(-y + 2(9 - y)) \\\\\n		0 &= y(18 - 3y) \\\\\n		y &= 0, 6\n	}$\n</div>\nNow the necessary evaluations are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k(0) &= 0 \\\\\n		k(6) &= 108 \\\\\n		k(9) &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this we can state the maximum product achieved is $108$ given the two numbers $3$ amd $6$ where $6$ is the number being squared.'),(455,'Example_2',2,118,'An open rectangular box with square base is to be made from $48$ $\\text{ft}^2$ of material. What dimensions will result in a box with the largest possible volume?','First identify the objective function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x,y) = x^2y\n	}$\n</div>\nand the constraint function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^2 + 4xy = 48 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} 0 \\leq x \\leq \\sqrt{48}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow the objective function can be rewritten as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k(x) &= f\\Big( x, \\frac{48 - x^2}{4x} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= 12x - \\frac{1}{4}x^3\n	}$\n</div>\nDifferentiation gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k\'(x) &= 12 - \\frac{3}{4}x^2\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the critical points are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\require{cancel}\n		0 &= 12 - \\frac{3}{4}x^2 \\\\\n		0 &= 16 - x^2 \\\\\n		x &= \\cancel{-4}, 4\n	}$\n</div>\nand the negative value is ignored due to restrictions on the problem. Now the necessary evaluations are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k(0) &= 0 \\\\\n		k(4) &= 32 \\\\\n		k(\\sqrt{48}) &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this we can state the maximum possible volume achieved is $32$ $\\text{ft}^3$ given a height of $2$ $\\text{ft}$ and square side length of $4$ $\\text{ft}$.'),(456,'Example_3',3,118,'A container in the shape of a right circular cylinder with no top has surface area $3\\pi$ $\\text{ft}^2$. What height, $h$, and base radius, $r$, will maximize the volume of the cylinder?','First identify the objective function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(r,h) = \\pi r^2h\n	}$\n</div>\nand the constraint function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		2\\pi rh + \\pi r^2 = 3\\pi \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} 0 \\leq r \\leq \\sqrt{3}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow the objective function can be rewritten as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k(r) &= f\\Big( r, \\frac{3\\pi - \\pi r^2}{2\\pi r} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{3\\pi}{2}r - \\frac{\\pi}{2}r^3\n	}$\n</div>\nDifferentiation gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k\'(r) &= \\frac{3\\pi}{2} - \\frac{3\\pi}{2}r^2\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the critical points are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\require{cancel}\n		0 &= \\frac{3\\pi}{2} - \\frac{3\\pi}{2}r^2 \\\\\n		0 &= 1 - r^2 \\\\\n		r &= \\cancel{-1}, 1\n	}$\n</div>\nand the negative value is ignored due to restrictions on the problem. Now the necessary evaluations are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k(0) &= 0 \\\\\n		k(1) &= \\pi \\\\\n		k(\\sqrt{3}) &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this we can state the maximum possible volume achieved is $\\pi$ $\\text{ft}^3$ given a height of $1$ $\\text{ft}$ and base radius of $1$ $\\text{ft}$.'),(457,'Example_4',4,118,'A farmer has $2400$ $\\text{ft}$ of fencing and wants to fence off a rectangular field that borders a straight river. He needs no fence along the river. What are the dimensions of the field that has the largest area?','First identify the objective function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x,y) = xy\n	}$\n</div>\nand the constraint function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		2y + x = 2400 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} 0 \\leq y \\leq 1200\n	}$\n</div>\nNow the objective function can be rewritten as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k(y) &= f(2400 - 2y, y) \\\\\n		&= (2400 - 2y)y \\\\\n		&= 2400y - 2y^2\n	}$\n</div>\nDifferentiation gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k\'(y) &= 2400 - 4y\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the critical points are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 2400 - 4y \\\\\n		0 &= 600 - y \\\\\n		y &= 600\n	}$\n</div>\nNow the necessary evaluations are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k(0) &= 0 \\\\\n		k(600) &= 720,000 \\\\\n		k(1200) &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this we can state the maximum possible area achieved is $720,000$ $\\text{ft}^2$ given a height of $600$ $\\text{ft}$ and length of $1200$ $\\text{ft}$.'),(458,'Example_5',5,118,'A manufacturer needs to make a cylindrical can that will hold $1500$ $\\text{cm}^3$ of liquid. Determine the dimensions of the can that will minimize the amount of material used in its construction.','First identify the objective function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(r,h) = 2\\pi rh + 2\\pi r^2\n	}$\n</div>\nand the constraint function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\pi r^2h = 1500 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} 0 \\leq r \\leq \\infty\n	}$\n</div>\nNow the objective function can be rewritten as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k(r) &= f\\Big( r, \\frac{1500}{\\pi r^2} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{3000}{r} + 2\\pi r^2\n	}$\n</div>\nDifferentiation gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k\'(r) &= -\\frac{3000}{r^2} + 4\\pi r\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the critical points are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\require{cancel}\n		0 &= -\\frac{3000}{r^2} + 4\\pi r \\\\\n		0 &= -3000 + 4\\pi r^3 \\\\\n		r &= \\Big( \\frac{750}{\\pi} \\Big)^{\\frac{1}{3}}\n	}$\n</div>\nNotice that to the left of the point the derivative is negative and positive afterwards. Therefore, by the First Derivative Test we can state this is a relative minimum and since the boundaries are not included in this case, this is the only minimum, thus it is also the absolute minimum. With this we can state the minimum amount of material that can be achieved is $\\approx 725.3964$ $\\text{cm}^2$ given a height of $\\approx 12.4070$ $\\text{cm}$ and base radius of $\\approx 6.2035$ $\\text{cm}$.'),(459,'Example_6',6,118,'Determine the area of the largest rectangle that can be inscribed in a circle of radius $4$.','Let each variable represent the length in a particular direction in reference to the origin. Therefore, we identify the objective function as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x,y) = 4xy\n	}$\n</div>\nand the constraint function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^2 + y^2 = 16 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} -4 \\leq x,y \\leq 4\n	}$\n</div>\nNow the setup we have is good to go, but there is a better way to reduce stress. If we want to maximize the area, we may as well maximize the area squared. So first define the substitution:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		u &= x^2 \\\\\n		v &= y^2\n	}$\n</div>\nand use it to rewrite the objective and constraint functions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(f(u,v))^2 &= 16uv \\\\\n		u + v &= 16\n	}$\n</div>\nNow the objective function can be rewritten as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k(u) &= (f(u, 16 - u))^2 \\\\\n		&= 16u(16 - u) \\\\\n		&= 256u - 16u^2\n	}$\n</div>\nDifferentiation gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k\'(u) &= 256 - 32u\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the critical points are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 256 - 32u \\\\\n		u &= 8\n	}$\n</div>\nNow the necessary evaluations are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k(0) &= 0 \\\\\n		k(8) &= 1024 \\\\\n		k(16) &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this we can state the maximum possible area achieved is $1024$ given height and length $\\sqrt{8}$, which turns out to be a square.'),(460,'Example_7',7,118,'Construct a window in the shape of a semi-circle over a rectangle. If the distance around the outside of the window is $12$ $\\text{ft}$, what dimensions will result in the rectangle having largest possible area?','First identify the objective function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x,y) = xy\n	}$\n</div>\nand the constraint function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x + 2y + \\frac{\\pi}{2}x = 12 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} 0 \\leq x \\leq \\frac{24}{2 + \\pi}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow the objective function can be rewritten as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k(x) &= f\\Big( x, 6 - \\frac{1}{2}x - \\frac{\\pi}{4}x \\Big) \\\\\n		&= 6x - \\frac{1}{2}x^2 - \\frac{\\pi}{4}x^2\n	}$\n</div>\nDifferentiation gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k\'(x) &= 6 - x - \\frac{\\pi}{2}x\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the critical points are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\require{cancel}\n		0 &= 6 - x - \\frac{\\pi}{2}x \\\\\n		6 &= x\\Big( 1 + \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\Big) \\\\\n		x &= \\frac{6}{1 + \\frac{\\pi}{2}}\n	}$\n</div>\nand the negative value is ignored due to restrictions on the problem. Now the necessary evaluations are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k\\Big( 0 \\Big) &= 0 \\\\\n		k\\Big( \\frac{6}{1 + \\frac{\\pi}{2}} \\Big) &= \\frac{32}{2 + \\pi} \\\\\n		k\\Big( \\frac{24}{2 + \\pi} \\Big) &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this we can state the maximum possible area for the rectangle achieved is $\\approx 7.0017$ $\\text{ft}^2$ given a height of $\\approx 3$ $\\text{ft}$ and length of $\\approx 2.3339$ $\\text{ft}$.'),(461,'Example_8',8,118,'Of all lines tangent to the graph of:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = \\frac{6}{x^2 + 3}\n	}$\n</div>\nFind the tangent lines of minimum and maximum slope.','First identify that the function of interest is really the first derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) &= y\' \\\\\n		&= \\frac{-12x}{(x^2 + 3)^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhose extremas we want to determine. To accomplish this we look at the second derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'\' &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\frac{-12x}{(x^2 + 3)^2} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{-12(x^2 + 3)^2 + 48x^2(x^2 + 3)}{(x^2 + 3)^4}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich gives the critical points of the first derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= \\frac{-12(x^2 + 3)^2 + 48x^2(x^2 + 3)}{(x^2 + 3)^4} \\\\\n		0 &= -12(x^2 + 3)^2 + 48x^2(x^2 + 3) \\\\\n		0 &= 12(x^2 + 3)(-(x^2 + 3) + 4x^2) \\\\\n		0 &= 12(x^2 + 3)(3x^2 - 3) \\\\\n		x &= \\pm 1\n	}$\n</div>\nNow the neccesary evaluations are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(-\\infty) &= 0 \\\\\n		f(-1) &= \\frac{3}{4} \\\\\n		f(1) &= -\\frac{3}{4} \\\\\n		f(\\infty) &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nThus we can state that the maximum and minimum slopes occur at $x = -1$ and $x = 1$ respectively. To determine the tangent lines we use the point-slope form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y - \\frac{3}{2} &= \\frac{3}{4}(x + 1) \\\\\n		y - \\frac{3}{2} &= -\\frac{3}{4}(x - 1)\n	}$\n</div>'),(462,'Example_9',9,118,'There are $50$ apple trees in an orchard. Each tree produces $800$ apples and for each additional tree planted in the orchard, the output per tree drops by $10$ apples. How many trees should be added to the existing orchard in order to maximize the total output of trees?','First identify the objective function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = (50 + x)(800 - 10x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $x$ is the number of additional trees. Now to identify the optimal number of trees we take the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = (800 - 10x) - 10(50 + x)\n	}$\n</div>\nand determine the critical point:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 300 - 20x \\\\\n		x &= 15\n	}$\n</div>\nNow the necessary evaluations are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(0) &= 40,000 \\\\\n		f(15) &= 42,250 \\\\\n		f(\\infty) &= -\\infty\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this we can state the maximum possible output achieved is $42,250$ $\\text{apples}$ given $15$ additional trees.'),(463,'Example_10',10,118,'A cylindrical can is to hold $20\\pi$ $\\text{m}^3$ of liquid. The material for the top and bottom costs $\\frac{\\$ 10}{\\text{m}^2}$ and $\\frac{\\$ 8}{\\text{m}^2}$ for the side. Find the radius, $r$, and height, $h$ of the most economical can.','First identify the objective function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(r,h) = 20\\pi r^2 + 16\\pi rh\n	}$\n</div>\nand the constraint function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\pi r^2h = 20\\pi \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} 0 \\leq r \\leq \\infty\n	}$\n</div>\nNow the objective function can be rewritten as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k(r) &= f\\Big( r, \\frac{28}{r^2} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= 20\\pi r^2 + \\frac{320\\pi}{r}\n	}$\n</div>\nDifferentiation gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k\'(r) &= 40\\pi r - \\frac{320\\pi}{r^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the critical points are:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= 40\\pi r - \\frac{320\\pi}{r^2} \\\\\n		0 &= 40r^3 - 320 \\\\\n		r &= 2\n	}$\n</div>\nNotice that to the left of the point the derivative is negative and positive afterwards. Therefore, by the First Derivative Test we can state this is a relative minimum and since the boundaries are not included in this case, this is the only minimum, thus it is also the absolute minimum. With this we can state the minimum cost that can be achieved is $\\$240\\pi$ given a height of $7$ $\\text{m}$ and base radius of $2$ $\\text{m}$.'),(464,'Example_1',1,119,'Determine a linear approximation to the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\sin(x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{near} \\hspace{.3cm} x = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand use it to approximate $\\sin(0.1)$. What is the error up to $5$ decimal places?','To determine a linear approximation we need the first derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = \\cos(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich evaluated at $x = 0$ produces:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(0) = 1\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we can write down the approximation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) &\\approx f(0) + f\'(0)(x - 0) \\\\\n		&= x\n	}$\n</div>\nSo now by direct computation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sin(0.1) &= 0.09983 \\\\\n		\\sin(0.1) &\\approx 0.10000\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich gives the error:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\Delta &= |f(x) - x| \\\\\n		&= |f(0.1) - 0.1| \\\\\n		&= |0.09983 - 0.10000| \\\\\n		&= 0.90017\n	}$\n</div>'),(465,'Example_2',2,119,'Determine a linear approximation to the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\sin(x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{near} \\hspace{.3cm} x = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand use it to evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\sin(x)}{x}\n	}$\n</div>','To determine a linear approximation we need the first derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = \\cos(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich evaluated at $x = 0$ produces:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(0) = 1\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we can write down the approximation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) &\\approx f(0) + f\'(0)(x - 0) \\\\\n		&= x\n	}$\n</div>\nSo now by direct computation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\sin(x)}{x} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{x}{x} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} 1 \\\\\n		&= 1\n	}$\n</div>'),(466,'Example_3',3,119,'Determine a linear approximation to the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\ln(1 + 3x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{near} \\hspace{.3cm} x = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand use it to approximate $\\ln(0.7)$. What is the error up to $5$ decimal places?','To determine a linear approximation we need the first derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = \\frac{3}{1 + 3x}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich evaluated at $x = 0$ produces:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(0) = 3\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we can write down the approximation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) &\\approx f(0) + f\'(0)(x - 0) \\\\\n		&= 3x\n	}$\n</div>\nSo now by direct computation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\ln(0.7) &= -0.35667 \\\\\n		\\ln(0.7) &= \\ln(1 + 3(-0.1)) \\\\\n		&\\approx 3(-0.10000) \\\\\n		&= -0.30000\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich gives the error:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\Delta &= |f(x) - x| \\\\\n		&= |f(-0.1) + 0.1| \\\\\n		&= |-0.35667 + 0.30000| \\\\\n		&= 0.05667\n	}$\n</div>'),(467,'Example_4',4,119,'Given:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(2) = 5 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} f\'(2) = 3\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate $f(1.9)$ and $f(2.1)$.','With the given information we write down the linear approximation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) &\\approx f(2) + f\'(2)(x - 2) \\\\\n		&= 5 + 3(x - 2)\n	}$\n</div>\nSo now by direct computation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(1.9) &\\approx 5 + 3(1.9 - 2) \\\\\n		&= 4.7 \\\\\n		f(2.1) &\\approx 5 + 3(2.1 - 2) \\\\\n		&= 5.3\n	}$\n</div>'),(468,'Example_5',5,119,'Approximate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sqrt{1.1}\n	}$\n</div>\nusing an appropriate function and center. What is the error up to $5$ decimal places?','With the given setup we can conclude that a good function to choose is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\sqrt{x}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich can be approximated near $x = 1$ as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) &\\approx f(1) + f\'(1)(x - 1) \\\\\n		&= 1 + \\frac{1}{2}(x - 1)\n	}$\n</div>\nSo we approximate the setup as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sqrt{1.1} &= f(1.1) \\\\\n		&\\approx 1 + \\frac{1}{2}(1.1 - 1) \\\\\n		&= 1.05\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich gives the error:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\Delta &= \\Big| f(x) - \\Big( 1 + \\frac{1}{2}(x - 1) \\Big) \\Big| \\\\\n		&= |f(1.1) - 1.05| \\\\\n		&= |1.04881 - 1.05000| \\\\\n		&= 0.00119\n	}$\n</div>'),(469,'Example_6',6,119,'Determine a linear approximation to the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\cos(x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{near} \\hspace{.3cm} x = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand use it to evaluate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\cos(x) - 1}{x}\n	}$\n</div>','To determine a linear approximation we need the first derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = -\\sin(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich evaluated at $x = 0$ produces:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(0) = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we can write down the approximation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) &\\approx f(0) + f\'(0)(x - 0) \\\\\n		&= 1\n	}$\n</div>\nSo now by direct computation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\cos(x) - 1}{x} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{0}{x} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0} 0 \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(470,'Example_7',7,119,'Determine a linear approximation to the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = mx + b \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{near} \\hspace{.3cm} x = 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} m,b \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nWhy does the approximation come out to be the original function?','To determine a linear approximation we need the first derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = m\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich evaluated at $x = 0$ produces:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(0) = m\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we can write down the approximation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) &\\approx f(0) + f\'(0)(x - 0) \\\\\n		&= b + m(x - 0) \\\\\n		&= mx + b\n	}$\n</div>\nand it should be no surprise that the approximation is in fact the original function. This happens in this scenario specifically because a linear approximation uses a line to approximate, and so when approximating a line with a line you get back the result that the original line is the best one for approximation.'),(471,'Example_8',8,119,'Using $\\textit{Euler\'s Formula}$ the following can be deduced:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sin(x) = \\frac{e^{ix} - e^{-ix}}{2i}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $i$ is the imaginary number. Determine a linear approximation for the right side near $x = 0$ to prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sin(x) \\approx x \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{near} \\hspace{.3cm} x = 0\n	}$\n</div>','To determine a linear approximation we need to focus on the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x) = e^x\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the first derivative is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g\'(x) = e^x\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich evaluated at $x = 0$ produces:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g\'(0) = 1\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we can write down the approximation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x) &\\approx g(0) + g\'(0)(x - 0) \\\\\n		&= 1 + x\n	}$\n</div>\nApplying this to our scenario gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{e^{ix} - e^{-ix}}{2i} &\\approx \\frac{(1 + ix) - (1 - ix)}{2i} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{2ix}{2i} \\\\\n		&= x\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich states that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sin(x) \\approx x \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{near} \\hspace{.3cm} x = 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(472,'Example_9',9,119,'Determine a linear approximation to the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\sqrt{1 + x} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{near} \\hspace{.3cm} x = 0\n	}$\n</div>','To determine a linear approximation we need the first derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = \\frac{1}{2\\sqrt{1 + x}}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich evaluated at $x = 0$ produces:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(0) = \\frac{1}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we can write down the approximation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) &\\approx f(0) + f\'(0)(x - 0) \\\\\n		&= 1 + \\frac{1}{2}x\n	}$\n</div>'),(473,'Example_10',10,119,'In the context of Special Relativity, the $\\textit{Kinetic Energy}$ is defined as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		E_k = \\sqrt{p^2c^2 + m^2c^4} - mc^2\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $p$ is the momentum, $m$ is the rest mass, and $c$ is the speed of light. By using a linear approximation with respect to $p$, and the classical definition:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		p = mv\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $v$ is the velocity, show that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		E_k \\approx \\frac{1}{2}mv^2\n	}$\n</div>','From the previous example we know the following:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sqrt{1 + x} \\approx 1 + \\frac{1}{2}x\n	}$\n</div>\nSo in our scenario we have:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		E_k &= \\sqrt{p^2c^2 + m^2c^4} - mc^2 \\\\\n		&= mc^2\\sqrt{1 + \\Big( \\frac{p}{m^2c^2} \\Big)^2} - mc^2 \\\\\n		&= mc^2\\Big[ \\sqrt{1 + \\Big( \\frac{p}{m^2c^2} \\Big)^2} - 1 \\Big] \\\\\n		&\\approx mc^2\\Big[ \\Big( 1 + \\frac{p^2}{2m^2c^2} \\Big) - 1 \\Big] \\\\\n		&= mc^2\\Big[ \\frac{p^2}{2m^2c^2} \\Big] \\\\\n		&= \\frac{p^2}{2m} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{(mv)^2}{2m} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{2}mv^2 \\\\\n	}$\n</div>'),(474,'Example_1',1,120,'Evaluate the following using L\'Hospital\'s Rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{x^2 - 9x + 4}{3x^2 + 7x + 8}\n	}$\n</div>','The initial limit will approach:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{x^2 - 9x + 4}{3x^2 + 7x + 8} = \\frac{\\infty}{\\infty}\n	}$\n</div>\nThis provides reasoning to use L\'Hospital\'s Rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{x^2 - 9x + 4}{3x^2 + 7x + 8} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{2x - 9}{6x + 7} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{\\infty}{\\infty}\n	}$\n</div>\nSince the result is still an indeterminate form, we use the rule once more:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{2x - 9}{6x + 7} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{2}{6} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{3}\n	}$\n</div>'),(475,'Example_2',2,120,'Evaluate the following using L\'Hospital\'s Rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{\\ln(x)}{x^2}\n	}$\n</div>','The initial limit will approach:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{\\ln(x)}{x^2} = \\frac{\\infty}{\\infty}\n	}$\n</div>\nThis provides reasoning to use L\'Hospital\'s Rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{\\ln(x)}{x^2} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{\\frac{1}{x}}{2x} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{1}{2x^2} \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(476,'Example_3',3,120,'Evaluate the following using L\'Hospital\'s Rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} xe^{-3x}\n	}$\n</div>','The initial limit will approach:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{x}{e^{3x}} = \\frac{\\infty}{\\infty}\n	}$\n</div>\nThis provides reasoning to use L\'Hospital\'s Rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{x}{e^{3x}} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{1}{3e^{3x}} \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(477,'Example_4',4,120,'Evaluate the following using L\'Hospital\'s Rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} x\\tan\\Big( \\frac{7}{x} \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>','The initial limit will approach:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{\\tan\\Big( \\frac{7}{x} \\Big)}{\\frac{1}{x}} = \\frac{0}{0}\n	}$\n</div>\nThis provides reasoning to use L\'Hospital\'s Rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{\\tan\\Big( \\frac{7}{x} \\Big)}{\\frac{1}{x}} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{-\\frac{7}{x^2}\\sec^2\\Big( \\frac{7}{x} \\Big)}{-\\frac{1}{x^2}} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} 7\\sec^2\\Big( \\frac{7}{x} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= 7\n	}$\n</div>'),(478,'Example_5',5,120,'Evaluate the following using L\'Hospital\'s Rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{x^2 + 4}{8^x}\n	}$\n</div>','The initial limit will approach:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{x^2 + 4}{8^x} = \\frac{\\infty}{\\infty}\n	}$\n</div>\nThis provides reasoning to use L\'Hospital\'s Rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{x^2 + 4}{8^x} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{2x}{\\ln(8)8^x} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{\\infty}{\\infty}\n	}$\n</div>\nSince the result is still an indeterminate form, we use the rule once more:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{2x}{\\ln(8)8^x} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{2}{(\\ln(8))^2 8^x} \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>'),(479,'Example_6',6,120,'Evaluate the following using L\'Hospital\'s Rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{\\arctan(3x) - \\frac{\\pi}{2}}{\\arctan(7x) - \\frac{\\pi}{2}}\n	}$\n</div>','The initial limit will approach:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{\\arctan(3x) - \\frac{\\pi}{2}}{\\arctan(7x) - \\frac{\\pi}{2}} = \\frac{0}{0}\n	}$\n</div>\nThis provides reasoning to use L\'Hospital\'s Rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{\\arctan(3x) - \\frac{\\pi}{2}}{\\arctan(7x) - \\frac{\\pi}{2}} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{\\frac{3}{1 + 9x^2}}{\\frac{7}{1 + 49x^2}} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{3(1 + 49x^2)}{7(1 + 9x^2)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{\\infty}{\\infty}\n	}$\n</div>\nSince the result is still an indeterminate form, we use the rule once more:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{3(1 + 49x^2)}{7(1 + 9x^2)} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{3 \\cdot 98x}{7 \\cdot 18x} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{7}{3}\n	}$\n</div>'),(480,'Example_7',7,120,'Evaluate the following using L\'Hospital\'s Rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} x^{\\sin(x)}\n	}$\n</div>','The initial limit will approach:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} x^{\\sin(x)} = 0^0\n	}$\n</div>\nThe result is an indeterminate form, and so using the logarithm:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= x^{\\sin(x)} \\\\\n		\\ln(y) &= \\sin(x) \\ln(x) \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} \\ln(y) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} \\sin(x) \\ln(x) \\\\\n		\\ln\\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} y \\Big) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} \\sin(x) \\ln(x) \n	}$\n</div>\nNow the limit approaches:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} \\frac{\\ln(x)}{\\csc(x)} = \\frac{\\infty}{\\infty}\n	}$\n</div>\nThis provides reasoning to use L\'Hospital\'s Rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} \\frac{\\ln(x)}{\\csc(x)} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} -\\frac{\\frac{1}{x}}{\\csc(x)\\cot(x)} \\\\\n		&= -\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} \\frac{\\sin(x)\\tan(x)}{x} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{0}{0}\n	}$\n</div>\nSince the result is still an indeterminate form, we use the rule once more:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} -\\frac{\\sin(x)\\tan(x)}{x} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} -(\\sin(x) + \\sec(x)\\tan(x)) \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nThis allows us to state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\ln\\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} y \\Big) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} \\sin(x) \\ln(x) \\\\\n		\\ln\\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} y \\Big) &= 0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} y &= 1 \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} x^{\\sin(x)} &= 1\n	}$\n</div>'),(481,'Example_8',8,120,'Evaluate the following using L\'Hospital\'s Rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} (\\ln(x))^{\\frac{1}{x}}\n	}$\n</div>','The initial limit will approach:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 0^+} (\\ln(x))^{\\frac{1}{x}} = \\infty^0\n	}$\n</div>\nThe result is an indeterminate form, and so using the logarithm:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y &= (\\ln(x))^{\\frac{1}{x}} \\\\\n		\\ln(y) &= \\frac{1}{x}\\ln(\\ln(x)) \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\ln(y) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{1}{x}\\ln(\\ln(x)) \\\\\n		\\ln\\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} y \\Big) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{1}{x}\\ln(\\ln(x))\n	}$\n</div>\nNow the limit approaches:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{\\ln(\\ln(x))}{x} = \\frac{\\infty}{\\infty}\n	}$\n</div>\nThis provides reasoning to use L\'Hospital\'s Rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{\\ln(\\ln(x))}{x} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{\\frac{1}{x}}{\\ln(x)} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{1}{x\\ln(x)} \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nThis allows us to state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\ln\\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} y \\Big) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{1}{x}\\ln(\\ln(x)) \\\\\n		\\ln\\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} y \\Big) &= 0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} y &= 1 \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} (\\ln(x))^{\\frac{1}{x}} &= 1\n	}$\n</div>'),(482,'Example_9',9,120,'Evaluate the following using L\'Hospital\'s Rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 