 Theorem:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= \\frac{f(b) - f(a)}{b - a} \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} (x - x^2)^{\\frac{1}{2}} &= \\frac{\\sqrt{0} - \\sqrt{0}}{1 - 0} \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{2}(1 - 2x)(x - x^2)^{-\\frac{1}{2}} &= 0 \\\\\n		1 - 2x &= 0 \\\\\n		x &= \\frac{1}{2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(491,'Example_8',8,121,'Use the Mean Value Theorem to prove:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|\\cos(\\kappa b) - \\cos(\\kappa a)| \\leq |\\kappa| |b - a| \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} a,b,\\kappa \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>','Let us consider the setup:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\cos(\\kappa x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} x \\in [a,b]\n	}$\n</div>\nWe are dealing with a trigonometric function which is known to be continuous and differentiable. With all of the conditions satisfied by using the setup for the Mean Value Theorem:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= \\frac{f(b) - f(a)}{b - a} \\\\\n		-\\kappa \\sin(\\kappa x) &= \\frac{\\cos(\\kappa b) - \\cos(\\kappa a)}{b - a} \\\\\n	}$\n</div>\nand using the range of sine:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{\\cos(\\kappa b) - \\cos(\\kappa a)}{b - a} &= -\\kappa \\sin(\\kappa x) \\\\\n		\\Bigg| \\frac{\\cos(\\kappa b) - \\cos(\\kappa a)}{b - a} \\Bigg| &= |-\\kappa \\sin(\\kappa x)| \\\\\n		\\Bigg| \\frac{\\cos(\\kappa b) - \\cos(\\kappa a)}{b - a} \\Bigg| &\\leq |\\kappa| \\\\\n		|\\cos(\\kappa b) - \\cos(\\kappa a)| &\\leq |\\kappa||b - a|\n	}$\n</div>'),(492,'Example_9',9,121,'Show that the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		2x^3 + 3x^2 + 6x + 1 = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nhas exactly one real root.','Consider the two points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(-1) &= -4 \\\\\n		f(0) &= 1\n	}$\n</div>\nand so by the Intermediate Value Theorem we know that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.1cm} \\in [-1,0] \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\hspace{.3cm} f(c) = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to prove that there is exactly one root, we assume that there exist two roots s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(\\alpha) = f(\\beta) = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nIf this holds true, then by Rolle\'s Theorem we have the setup:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= 0 \\\\\n		6x^2 + 6x + 6 &= 0 \\\\\n		x^2 + x + 1 &= 0 \\\\\n		x &= \\frac{-1 \\pm \\sqrt{1 - 4}}{2} \\\\\n		x &= \\frac{-1 \\pm \\sqrt{3}i}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nSince the setup for Rolle\'s Theorem does not have an associated value, we have a contradiction to our original assumption. Thus there is exactly one root that is real.'),(493,'Example_10',10,121,'Prove the following: Given two function, $f(x)$ and $h(x)$, that satisfy all of the following:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&1. \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{Continuous on the closed interval} \\hspace{.1cm} [a,b] \\\\\n		&2. \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{Differentiable on the open interval} \\hspace{.1cm} (a,b)\n	}$\n</div>\nthen:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.1cm} c \\in &(a,b) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\\\\n		f\'(c)(h(b) - h(a)) &= h\'(c)(f(b) - f(a))\n	}$\n</div>\nThis is known as Cauchy\'s Mean Value Theorem and can be approached with a method similar to the proof of the Mean Value Theorem.','To prove the generalized mean value theorem we define a new function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x) = f(x) - \\kappa h(x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} \\kappa \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nthat also satisfies the two conditions. We now want to determine a value for $\\kappa$ s.t. the function satisfies Rolle\'s Theorem:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(a) - \\kappa h(a) &= f(b) - \\kappa h(b) \\\\\n		\\kappa(h(b) - h(a)) &= f(b) - f(a) \\\\\n		\\kappa &= \\frac{f(b) - f(a)}{h(b) - h(a)}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith our constant chosen, all of the conditions are met for Rolle\'s Theorem. Therefore:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.1cm} c \\in (a,b) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\hspace{.3cm} g\'(c) = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand directly by our definition of $g$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g\'(c) &= 0 \\\\\n		f\'(c) - \\kappa h\'(c) &= 0 \\\\\n		f\'(c) &= \\kappa h\'(c) \\\\\n		f\'(c) &= \\frac{f(b) - f(a)}{h(b) - h(a)} h\'(c) \\\\\n		f\'(c)(h(b) - h(a)) &= h\'(c)(f(b) - f(a))\n	}$\n</div>'),(494,'Example_1',1,122,'Using Newton\'s Method determine $x_5$, up to $5$ decimal places, as an approximation of the root to the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^3 - x + 1\n	}$\n</div>\non the interval $[-2,-1]$.','In this scenario Newton\'s Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = x_n - \\frac{x_n^3 - x_n + 1}{3x_n^2 - 1}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe can choose the starting point to be $x = -1$ and the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.50000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.34783$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.32520$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.32472$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.32472$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(495,'Example_2',2,122,'Given the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sin(x) = x^2\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate the solution up to $5$ decimal places by using Newton\'s Method to determine $x_5$ on the interval $\\Big[ \\frac{1}{2}, 1 \\Big]$.','First we rewrite the equation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = \\sin(x) - x^2\n	}$\n</div>\nand in this scenario Newton\'s Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = x_n - \\frac{\\sin(x_n) - x_n^2}{\\cos(x_n) - 2x_n}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe can choose the starting point to be $x = 1$ and the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$1.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$0.89039$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$0.87700$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$0.87673$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$0.87673$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$0.87673$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(496,'Example_3',3,122,'Given the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\sin(x) - x^2\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate the critical point up to $5$ decimal places by using Newton\'s Method to determine $x_5$ on the interval $[0,1]$.','First we differentiate the equation since we want to determine the critical point:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = \\cos(x) - 2x\n	}$\n</div>\nand in this scenario Newton\'s Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = x_n - \\frac{\\cos(x_n) - 2x_n}{-\\sin(x_n) - 2}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe can choose the starting point to be $x = 0$ and the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$0.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$0.50000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$0.45063$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$0.45018$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$0.45018$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$0.45018$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(497,'Example_4',4,122,'Given the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		6x = \\sqrt{1 - x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate the solution up to $5$ decimal places by using Newton\'s Method to determine $x_5$.','Before anything else we need to determine a suitable interval to search. This can be accomplished by graphing the left and right hand sides independently:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/NewtonAPOSTROPHEs_Method/Example_4.png\">\n</div>\nLooking at the graph shows that $[0,1]$ is a proper interval. Now we rewrite the equation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = 6x - \\sqrt{1 - x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nand in this scenario Newton\'s Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} &= x_n - \\frac{6x_n - \\sqrt{1 - x_n^2}}{6 + \\frac{x_n}{\\sqrt{1 - x_n^2}}} \\\\\n		&= x_n - \\frac{6x_n\\sqrt{1 - x_n^2} - 1 + x_n^2}{6\\sqrt{1 - x_n^2} + x_n}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe can choose the starting point to be $x = 0$ and the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$0.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$0.16667$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$0.16440$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$0.16440$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$0.16440$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$0.16440$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(498,'Example_5',5,122,'Given the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\ln(x) = x^2 - 4\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate the rightmost solution up to $5$ decimal places by using Newton\'s Method to determine $x_5$.','Before anything else we need to determine a suitable interval to search. This can be accomplished by graphing the left and right hand sides independently:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/NewtonAPOSTROPHEs_Method/Example_5.png\">\n</div>\nLooking at the graph shows that $[1,3]$ is a proper interval. Now we rewrite the equation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = \\ln(x) - x^2 + 4\n	}$\n</div>\nand in this scenario Newton\'s Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} &= x_n - \\frac{\\ln(x_n) - x_n^2 + 4}{\\frac{1}{x_n} - 2x_n} \\\\\n		&= x_n - \\frac{x_n\\ln(x_n) - x_n^3 + 4x_n}{1 - 2x_n^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe can choose the starting point to be $x = 1$ and the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$1.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$4.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$2.63049$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$2.23049$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$2.18741$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$2.18689$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(499,'Example_6',6,122,'Given the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		e^{\\sin(x)} = -x\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate the solution up to $5$ decimal places by using Newton\'s Method to determine $x_5$ on the interval $[-1,0]$.','First we rewrite the equation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = e^{\\sin(x)} + x\n	}$\n</div>\nand in this scenario Newton\'s Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = x_n - \\frac{e^{\\sin(x_n)} + x_n}{\\cos(x_n)e^{\\sin(x_n)} + 1}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe can choose the starting point to be $x = -1$ and the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.53855$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.57832$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.57871$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.57871$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.57871$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(500,'Example_7',7,122,'Given the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^2 - c \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} c \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nshow that the sequence $x_0, x_1, x_2, \\dots$ of Newton\'s Method satisfies the difference equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = \\frac{x_n + \\frac{c}{x_n}}{2}\n	}$\n</div>','For the given function Newton\'s Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} &= x_n - \\frac{x_n^2 - c}{2x_n} \\\\\n		&= x_n - \\frac{x_n - \\frac{c}{x_n}}{2} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{x_n - \\frac{c}{x_n}}{2}\n	}$\n</div>'),(501,'Example_8',8,122,'Given the recurrence relation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = \\frac{x_n + \\frac{c}{x_n}}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nAssume that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} x_n = L\n	}$\n</div>\nand prove that $L = \\pm\\sqrt{c}$.','Given the limit we can also state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} x_{n + 1} = L\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging all of this into the recurrence relation provides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} &= \\frac{x_n + \\frac{c}{x_n}}{2} \\\\\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} x_{n + 1} &= \\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{x_n + \\frac{c}{x_n}}{2} \\\\\n		L &= \\frac{1}{2} \\Big[ \\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} x_n + c\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} (x_n)^{-1} \\Big] \\\\\n		2L &= L + \\frac{c}{L} \\\\\n		L &= \\frac{c}{L} \\\\\n		L^2 &= c \\\\\n		L &= \\pm\\sqrt{c}\n	}$\n</div>'),(502,'Example_9',9,122,'Use Newton\'s Method to approximate $\\sqrt{2}$ up to $5$ decimal places at $x_5$.','The number of interest is a root of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^2 - 2\n	}$\n</div>\nand looking at the graph:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/NewtonAPOSTROPHEs_Method/Example_9.png\">\n</div>\nshows that a suitable interval to restrict ourselves to is $[1,2]$. Next up Newton\'s Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = x_n - \\frac{x^2 - 2}{2x}\n	}$\n</div>\nStarting at $x = 1$, the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$1.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$1.50000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$1.41667$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$1.41422$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$1.41421$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$1.41421$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(503,'Example_10',10,122,'Use Newton\'s Method to approximate $\\sqrt{11}$ up to $5$ decimal places at $x_5$.','The number of interest is a root of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^2 - 11\n	}$\n</div>\nand looking at the graph:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/NewtonAPOSTROPHEs_Method/Example_10.png\">\n</div>\nshows that a suitable interval to restrict ourselves to is $[3,4]$. Next up Newton\'s Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = x_n - \\frac{x^2 - 11}{2x}\n	}$\n</div>\nStarting at $x = 3$, the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$3.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$3.33333$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$3.31667$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$3.31662$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$3.31662$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$3.31662$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(504,'Example_1',1,123,'Air is being pumped into a spherical balloon at a rate of $20 \\frac{\\text{in}^3}{\\text{min}}$. How fast is the radius of the balloon increasing when the radius is $6 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{in}$?','For a spherical balloon it is known that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		V &= \\frac{4}{3}\\pi r^3 \\\\\n		V(t) &= \\frac{4}{3}\\pi (r(t))^3\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich is rewritten as a function of time since it is the dependent variable in the situation. Now by differentiation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dt} V(t) &= \\frac{d}{dt} \\Big( \\frac{4}{3}\\pi (r(t))^3 \\Big) \\\\\n		\\frac{dV}{dt} &= 4\\pi r^2 \\frac{dr}{dt} \\\\\n		\\frac{dr}{dt} &= \\frac{1}{4\\pi r^2} \\frac{dV}{dt}\n	}$\n</div>\nand evaluation with the given parameters provides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dr}{dt} &= \\frac{1}{4\\pi r^2} \\frac{dV}{dt} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{4\\pi (6 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{in})^2} \\cdot \\Big( 20 \\frac{\\text{in}^3}{\\text{min}} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{5}{36\\pi} \\frac{\\text{in}}{\\text{min}}\n	}$\n</div>'),(505,'Example_2',2,123,'A $25$ foot ladder is leaning against a vertical wall. The floor is slightly slippery and the foot of the ladder slips away from the wall at the rate of $0.2 \\frac{\\text{in}}{\\text{sec}}$. How fast is the top of the ladder sliding down the wall when the top is $20$ feet above the floor?','The situation can be modeled with the following image:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/Related_Rates/Example_2.png\">\n</div>\nwhere by the Pythagorean Theorem we have the setup:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(x(t))^2 + (y(t))^2 &= (25 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{ft})^2 \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dt} \\Big[ (x(t))^2 + (y(t))^2 \\Big] &= \\frac{d}{dt} (25 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{ft})^2 \\\\\n		2x\\frac{dx}{dt} + 2y\\frac{dy}{dt} &= 0 \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dt} &= -\\frac{x}{y} \\frac{dx}{dt}\n	}$\n</div>\nand evaluation with the given parameters provides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{dy}{dt} &= -\\frac{x}{y} \\frac{dx}{dt} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{\\sqrt{(25 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{ft})^2 - (20 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{ft})^2}}{20 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{ft}} \\cdot \\Big( 0.2 \\frac{\\text{in}}{\\text{sec}} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{3}{20} \\frac{\\text{in}}{\\text{sec}}\n	}$\n</div>'),(506,'Example_3',3,123,'A conical paper cup $3 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{in}$ across the top and $4 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{in}$ deep is full of water. The cup springs a leak at the bottom and loses water at the rate of $2 \\frac{\\text{in}^3}{\\text{min}}$. How fast is the water level dropping at the instant when the water is exactly $3 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{in}$ deep?','The situation can be modeled with the following image:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/Related_Rates/Example_3.png\">\n</div>\nwhere the volume of the cone is known to be:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		V &= \\frac{1}{3}\\pi r^2 h \\\\\n		V(t) &= \\frac{\\pi}{3} r^2 h(t)\n	}$\n</div>\nTo compute we need to determine what $r$ is in terms of $h$. Notice that we can use similar triangles to setup the following:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{1.5}{4} &= \\frac{h}{r} \\\\\n		r &= \\frac{3}{8}h \n	}$\n</div>\nNow by differentiation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dt} V(t) &= \\frac{d}{dt} \\frac{\\pi}{3} \\Big( \\frac{3}{8} h(t) \\Big)^2 h(t) \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dt} V(t) &= \\frac{d}{dt} \\frac{3\\pi}{64} (h(t))^3 \\\\\n		\\frac{dV}{dt} &= \\frac{9\\pi}{64} h^2 \\frac{dh}{dt} \\\\\n		\\frac{dh}{dt} &= \\frac{64}{9\\pi h^2} \\frac{dV}{dt} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{64}{9\\pi (3 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{in})^2} \\cdot \\Big( -2 \\frac{\\text{in}^3}{\\text{min}} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{128}{81\\pi} \\frac{\\text{in}}{\\text{min}}\n	}$\n</div>'),(507,'Example_4',4,123,'A particle is moving around the ellipse:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		4x^2 + 16y^2 = 64\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere at any time, $t$, the coordinates are given by:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x(t) = 4\\cos(t) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} y(t) = 2\\sin(t)\n	}$\n</div>\nAt what rate is the particles distance to the origin changing at any time? At what rate is the distance changing when $t = \\frac{\\pi}{4}$?','We can write away compute the derivatives since they will be needed:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x\'(t) = -4\\sin(t) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} y\'(t) = 2\\cos(t)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow using the Euclidean distance formula and differentiating:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(d(t))^2 &= (x(t) - 0)^2 + (y(t) - 0)^2 \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dt} (d(t))^2 &= \\frac{d}{dt} \\Big( (x(t))^2 + (y(t))^2 \\Big) \\\\\n		2dd\' &= 2xx\' + 2yy\' \\\\\n		d\'(t) &= \\frac{xx\' + yy\'}{d} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{xx\' + yy\'}{\\sqrt{x^2 + y^2}} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{6\\cos(t)\\sin(t)}{\\sqrt{4\\cos^2(t) + \\sin^2(t)}}\n	}$\n</div>\nThe above formula produces the rate at which the distance changes for any time. When looking at $t = \\frac{\\pi}{4}$ specifically:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		d\'\\Big( \\frac{\\pi}{4} \\Big) &= -\\frac{6\\cos\\Big( \\frac{\\pi}{4} \\Big) \\sin\\Big( \\frac{\\pi}{4} \\Big)}{\\sqrt{4\\cos^2\\Big( \\frac{\\pi}{4} \\Big) + \\sin^2\\Big( \\frac{\\pi}{4} \\Big)}} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{3}{\\sqrt{\\frac{5}{2}}} \\\\\n		&= -3\\sqrt{\\frac{2}{5}}\n	}$\n</div>'),(508,'Example_5',5,123,'Oil spilled from a ruptured tanker spreads out in a circle whose area increases at a constant rate of $6 \\frac{\\text{mi}^2}{\\text{hr}}$. How fast is the radius of the spill increasing when the area is $9 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{mi}^2$?','For a circle with a given area we can write the radius as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		A &= \\pi r^2 \\\\\n		r &= \\sqrt{\\frac{A}{\\pi}}\n	}$\n</div>\nand using differentiation on the area formula:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		A(t) &= \\pi (r(t))^2 \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dt} A(t) &= \\frac{d}{dt} \\pi (r(t))^2 \\\\\n		\\frac{dA}{dt} &= 2\\pi r \\frac{dr}{dt} \\\\\n		\\frac{dr}{dt} &= \\frac{1}{2\\pi r} \\frac{dA}{dt} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{2\\pi \\sqrt{\\frac{9 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{mi}^2}{\\pi}}} \\cdot \\Big( 6 \\frac{\\text{mi}^2}{\\text{hr}} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{\\sqrt{\\pi}} \\frac{\\text{mi}}{\\text{hr}}\n	}$\n</div>'),(509,'Example_6',6,123,'Ship $A$ is $15 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{mi}$ east of $P$ and is moving west at $20 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{mph}$; ship $B$ is $60 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{mi}$ south of $P$ and is moving north at $15 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{mph}$. At what rate is the distance between them changing after $1$ hour?','The situation can be modeled with the following image:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/Related_Rates/Example_6.png\">\n</div>\nUsing the Pythagorean Theorem and differentiation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(d(t))^2 &= (x(t))^2 + (y(t))^2 \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dt} (d(t))^2 &= \\frac{d}{dt} \\Big[ (x(t))^2 + (y(t))^2 \\Big] \\\\\n		2dd\' &= 2xx\' + 2yy\' \\\\\n		d\' &= \\frac{xx\' + yy\'}{\\sqrt{x^2 + y^2}}\n	}$\n</div>\nAfter one hour we have the following:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		d\' &= \\frac{xx\' + yy\'}{\\sqrt{x^2 + y^2}} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{(-5)(-20) + (-45)(15)}{\\sqrt{(-5)^2 + (-45)^2}} \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{mph} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{115}{\\sqrt{82}} \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{mph}\n	}$\n</div>'),(510,'Example_7',7,123,'Two parallel sides of a rectangle are being lengthened at the rate of $2 \\frac{\\text{in}}{\\text{sec}}$, while the other two sides are shortened in such a way that the figure remains a rectangle with constant area of $50 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{in}^2$. What is the rate of change of the perimeter when the length of an increasing side is $5 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{in}$?','For a rectangle with the given parameters the width is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		A &= lw \\\\\n		w &= \\frac{A}{l} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{50 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{in}^2}{5 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{in}} \\\\\n		&= 10 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{in}\n	}$\n</div>\nand by differentiation the width is changing at the rate:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dt} A(t) &= \\frac{d}{dt} l(t)w(t) \\\\\n		\\frac{dA}{dt} &= \\frac{dl}{dt}w + l\\frac{dw}{dt} \\\\\n		0 &= \\frac{dl}{dt}w + l\\frac{dw}{dt} \\\\\n		\\frac{dw}{dt} &= -\\frac{w}{l} \\frac{dl}{dt} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{10}{5} \\cdot \\Big( 2 \\frac{\\text{in}}{\\text{sec}} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= -4 \\frac{\\text{in}}{\\text{sec}}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this we can determine the rate of change for the perimeter:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dt} P(t) &= \\frac{d}{dt} \\Big( 2l(t) + 2w(t) \\Big) \\\\\n		\\frac{dP}{dt} &= 2\\frac{dl}{dt} + 2\\frac{dw}{dt} \\\\\n		&= 2\\Big( 2 \\frac{\\text{in}}{\\text{sec}} ) + 2\\Big( -4 \\frac{\\text{in}}{\\text{sec}} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= -4 \\frac{\\text{in}}{\\text{sec}}\n	}$\n</div>'),(511,'Example_8',8,123,'A balloon is $200 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{ft}$ off the ground and rising vertically at the constant rate of $15 \\frac{\\text{ft}}{\\text{sec}}$. An automobile passes beneath it traveling along a straight road at the constant rate of $66 \\frac{\\text{ft}}{\\text{sec}}$. How fast is the distance between them changing one second later?','The situation can be modeled with the following image:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/Related_Rates/Example_8.png\">\n</div>\nUsing the Pythagorean Theorem and differentiation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(d(t))^2 &= (x(t))^2 + (y(t))^2 \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dt} (d(t))^2 &= \\frac{d}{dt} \\Big[ (x(t))^2 + (y(t))^2 \\Big] \\\\\n		2dd\' &= 2xx\' + 2yy\' \\\\\n		d\' &= \\frac{xx\' + yy\'}{\\sqrt{x^2 + y^2}}\n	}$\n</div>\nAfter one sec we have the following:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		d\' &= \\frac{xx\' + yy\'}{\\sqrt{x^2 + y^2}} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{(66 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{ft})(66 \\frac{\\text{ft}}{\\text{sec}}) + (215 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{ft})(15 \\frac{\\text{ft}}{\\text{sec}})}{\\sqrt{(66 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{ft})^2 + (215 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{ft})^2}} \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{7581}{\\sqrt{50581}} \\frac{\\text{ft}}{\\text{sec}}\n	}$\n</div>'),(512,'Example_9',9,123,'Suppose that a raindrop is a perfect sphere. Assume that, through condensation, the raindrop accumulates moisture at a rate proportional to the rate of surface area change over time. Show that the radius increases at a constant rate.','Using the setup for the surface area of a sphere and differentiating:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		A(t) &= 4\\pi (r(t))^2 \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dt} A(t) &= \\frac{d}{dt} 4\\pi (r(t))^2 \\\\\n		\\frac{dA}{dt} &= 8\\pi r \\frac{dr}{dt}\n	}$\n</div>\nLet $\\kappa$ represent the rate for the raindrop accumulation and using the proportionality:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\kappa &\\sim \\frac{dA}{dt} \\\\\n		\\kappa &\\sim 8\\pi r \\frac{dr}{dt} \\\\\n		\\frac{dr}{dt} &\\sim \\frac{\\kappa}{8\\pi r} \n	}$\n</div>\nTherefore, for a constant radius, the radius increases at a constant rate.'),(513,'Example_10',10,123,'Two ships $A$ and $B$ are sailing away from the point $O$ along routes such that the angle $AOB = 120^\\circ$. How fast is the distance between them changing if, at a certain instant $|OA| = 8 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{mi}$, $|OB| = 6 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{mi}$, ship $A$ is sailing at the rate of $20 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{mph}$, and ship $B$ at the rate of $30 \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{mph}$?','The situation can be modeled with the following image:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/Related_Rates/Example_10.png\">\n</div>\nUsing the Law of Cosines and differentiation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(d(t))^2 &= (x(t))^2 + (y(t))^2 \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 2x(t)y(t)\\cos(\\theta) \\\\\n		(d(t))^2 &= (x(t))^2 + (y(t))^2 \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 2x(t)y(t)\\cos(120^\\circ) \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dt} (d(t))^2 &= \\frac{d}{dt} \\Big[ (x(t))^2 + (y(t))^2 \\Big] \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\frac{d}{dt} x(t)y(t) \\\\\n		2dd\' &= 2xx\' + 2yy\' + x\'y + xy\' \\\\\n		d\' &= \\frac{(2x + y)x\' + (2y + x)y\'}{2\\sqrt{x^2 + y^2 + xy}}\n	}$\n</div>\nAt the one instant:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		d\' &= \\frac{(2x + y)x\' + (2y + x)y\'}{2\\sqrt{x^2 + y^2 + xy}} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{(20)(30) + (22)((20))}{2\\sqrt{(6)^2 + (8)^2 + (48)}} \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{mph} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{260}{\\sqrt{37}} \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{mph}\n	}$\n</div>'),(514,'Example_11',11,127,'Prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (f(x) + g(x)) = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) + \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nby using the $(\\delta, \\epsilon)$ definition of the limit and assuming that the limits on the right-hand side exist.','Assuming that the limit of the functions exist:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) &= L_1 \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x) &= L_2\n	}$\n</div>\nthen we know $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\delta_1, \\delta_2 > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L_1| < \\frac{\\epsilon}{2} \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta_1 \\\\\n		|f(x) - L_2| < \\frac{\\epsilon}{2} \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta_2\n	}$\n</div>\nWe need to show:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|(f(x) + g(x)) - (L_1 + L_2)| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		\\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| &< \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nSo we choose $\\delta = \\min\\{\\delta_1, \\delta_2\\}$ to use the inequalities for $f(x)$ and $g(x)$ to obtain:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&|(f(x) + g(x)) - (L_1 + L_2)| \\\\\n		&= |(f(x) - L_1) + (g(x) - L_2)| \\\\\n		&\\leq |f(x) - L_1| + |g(x) - L_2| \\\\\n		&< \\frac{\\epsilon}{2} + \\frac{\\epsilon}{2} \\\\\n		&= \\epsilon\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the Triangle Inequality was used to break down the absolute value.'),(515,'Example_12',12,127,'You may assume the following properties:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} c = c \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} c \\in \\mathbb{R} \\\\\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (\\alpha f(x) + \\beta g(x)) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) + \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} \\alpha, \\beta \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nto prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x)g(x) = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\cdot \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nby using the $(\\delta, \\epsilon)$ definition of the limit and assuming that the limits on the right-hand side exist.','Assuming that the limit of the functions exist:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) &= L_1 \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x) &= L_2\n	}$\n</div>\nthen by the properties allowed to use we can state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (f(x) - L_1) &= 0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (g(x) - L_2) &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nIf these new limits exist, then we know $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\delta_1, \\delta_2 > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|(f(x) - L_1) &- 0| < \\sqrt{\\epsilon} \\\\\n		&\\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta_1 \\\\\n		|(g(x) - L_2) &- 0| < \\sqrt{\\epsilon} \\\\\n		&\\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta_2\n	}$\n</div>\nNow observe what happens to the multiplication of the two:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\Big| (f(x) - L_1)(g(x) - L_2) - 0 \\Big| \\\\\n		&= \\Big| f(x) - L_1 \\Big| \\Big| g(x) - L_2 \\Big| \\\\\n		&< \\sqrt{\\epsilon}\\sqrt{\\epsilon} \\\\\n		&= \\epsilon\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich proves that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (f(x) - L_1)(g(x) - L_2) = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nOf course this is not the limit we want, but it is going to be useful in what comes next. Notice what happens when we multiply out of the product:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&(f(x) - L_1)(g(x) - L_2) \\\\\n		&= f(x)g(x) - L_1g(x) - L_2f(x) + L_1L_2\n	}$\n</div>\nand rewriting gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&f(x)g(x) \\\\ \n		&= (f(x) - L_1)(g(x) - L_2) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + L_1g(x) + L_2f(x) - L_1L_2\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich provides a way to write out the multiplication of the two original functions. Applying the limit to both sides and using the allowed properties:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x)g(x) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} \\Big[ (f(x) - L_1)(g(x) - L_2) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + L_1g(x) + L_2f(x) - L_1L_2 \\Big] \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (f(x) - L_1)(g(x) - L_2) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + L_1\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x) + L_2\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) - \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} L_1L_2 \\\\\n		&= 0 + L_1L_2 + L_2L_1 - L_1L_2 \\\\\n		&= L_1L_2\n	}$\n</div>'),(516,'Example_13',13,127,'You may assume that $g(y)$ is continuous and:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) &= L_1 \\\\\n		\\lim_{y \\rightarrow L_1} g(y) &= L_2 \\\\\n	}$\n</div>\nUse this to prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(f(x)) = L_2\n	}$\n</div>\nby using the $(\\delta, \\epsilon)$ definition of the limit.','The given information can be reformatted. We know $\\forall \\epsilon,\\epsilon_1 > 0, \\exists \\delta, \\delta_1 > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|g(y) - L_2| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |y - L_1| < \\delta \\\\\n		|f(x) - L_1| < \\epsilon_1 \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta_1\n	}$\n</div>\nUsing the first line and setting $\\epsilon_1 = \\delta$ we are allowed to rewrite the second line as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L_1| < \\delta \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta_1\n	}$\n</div>\nSo now if $|x - a| < \\delta_1$, then:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|g(f(x)) &- L_2| < \\epsilon \\\\\n		&\\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |f(x) - L_1| < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich proves:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(f(x)) = L_2\n	}$\n</div>\nand is the same as saying:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(f(x)) = g\\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>'),(517,'Example_14',14,127,'Given that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x)g(x) = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\cdot \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nUse this to prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (f(x))^n = \\Big[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\Big]^n \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} n \\in \\mathbb{N}\n	}$\n</div>\nby assuming the limit on the right-hand side exists.','For the natural numbers, induction is a perfect method to prove the given statement. For the base case we can do $n = 1$, but a more interesting case is $n = 2$ which gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (f(x))^2 &= \\Big[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\Big]^2 \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x)f(x) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\cdot \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich holds true due to what we are given. Now we assume the original statement and try to see if it holds true for $n + 1$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (f(x))^{n + 1} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (f(x))^n f(x) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (f(x))^n \\cdot \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\\\\n		&= \\Big[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\Big]^n \\cdot \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\\\\n		&= \\Big[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\Big]^{n + 1}\n	}$\n</div>'),(518,'Example_15',15,127,'Given that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} cf(x) &= c\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(g(x)) &= f\\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x) \\Big) \n	}$\n</div>\nUse this to prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (f(x))^n = \\Big[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\Big]^n \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} n \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nby assuming the limit on the right-hand side exists.','Begin by defining a new function for the one of interest, take the logarithm of both sides, apply the limit, and simplify:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) &= (f(x))^n \\\\\n		\\ln(y(x)) &= \\ln((f(x))^n) \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} \\ln(y(x)) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} n\\ln(f(x)) \\\\\n		\\ln\\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} y(x) \\Big) &= n \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} \\ln(f(x)) \\\\\n		\\ln\\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} y(x) \\Big) &= n \\ln\\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\Big) \\\\\n		\\ln\\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} y(x) \\Big) &= \\ln\\Big( \\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\Big)^n \\Big) \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} y(x) &= \\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\Big)^n \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (f(x))^n &= \\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\Big)^n\n	}$\n</div>'),(519,'Example_1',1,124,'Using the Secant Method determine $x_6$, up to $5$ decimal places, as an approximation of the root to the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^3 - x + 1\n	}$\n</div>\non the interval $[-2,-1]$ and let $x_0$ and $x_1$ represent the two initial points.','In this scenario the Secant Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = x_n - \\frac{(x_n^3 - x_n + 1)(x_n - x_{n - 1})}{(x_n^3 - x_{n - 1}^3) - (x_n - x_{n - 1})}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe can choose the starting points to be $x_0 = -2$ and $x_1 = -1$. Now the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$-2.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.16667$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.39560$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.31366$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.32402$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$6$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.32473$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(520,'Example_2',2,124,'Given the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sin(x) = x^2\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate the solution up to $5$ decimal places by using the Secant Method to determine $x_6$ on the interval $\\Big[ \\frac{1}{2}, 1 \\Big]$. Let $x_0$ and $x_1$ represent the two initial points.','First we rewrite the equation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = \\sin(x) - x^2\n	}$\n</div>\nand in this scenario the Secant Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&x_{n + 1} \\\\ \n		&= x_n - \\Big[ (\\sin(x_n) - x_n^2)(x_n - x_{n - 1}) \\Big] \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.2cm} \\cdot \\Big[ \\sin(x_n) - \\sin(x_{n - 1}) - x_n^2 + x_{n - 1}^2 \\Big]^{-1}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe can choose the starting points to be $x_0 = \\frac{1}{2}$ and $x_1 = 1$. Now the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$0.50000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$1.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$0.79569$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$0.86491$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$0.87806$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$0.87671$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$6$</td>\n		    <td>$0.87673$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(521,'Example_3',3,124,'Given the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\sin(x) - x^2\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate the critical point up to $5$ decimal places by using the Secant Method to determine $x_6$ on the interval $[0,1]$. Let $x_0$ and $x_1$ represent the two initial points.','First we differentiate the equation since we want to determine the critical point:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = \\cos(x) - 2x\n	}$\n</div>\nand in this scenario the Secant Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&x_{n + 1} \\\\ \n		&= x_n - \\Big[ (\\cos(x_n) - 2x_n)(x_n - x_{n - 1}) \\Big] \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.2cm} \\cdot \\Big[ \\cos(x_n) - \\cos(x_{n - 1}) - 2x_n + 2x_{n - 1} \\Big]^{-1}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe can choose the starting point to be $x = 0$ and the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$0.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$1.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$0.40655$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$0.44651$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$0.45021$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$0.45018$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(522,'Example_4',4,124,'Given the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		6x = \\sqrt{1 - x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate the solution up to $5$ decimal places by using the Secant Method to determine $x_6$. Let $x_0$ and $x_1$ represent the two initial points.','Before anything else we need to determine a suitable interval to search. This can be accomplished by graphing the left and right hand sides independently:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/Secant_Method/Example_4.png\">\n</div>\nLooking at the graph shows that $[0,1]$ is a proper interval. Now we rewrite the equation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = 6x - \\sqrt{1 - x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nand in this scenario Newton\'s Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&x_{n + 1} \\\\\n		&= x_n - \\Big[ (6x_n - \\sqrt{1 - x_n^2})(x_n - x_{n - 1}) \\Big] \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.2cm} \\cdot \\Big[ 6x_n - 6x_{n - 1} - \\sqrt{1 - x_n^2} + \\sqrt{1 - x_{n - 1}^2} \\Big]^{-1}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe can choose the starting points to be $x_0 = 0$ and $x_1 = 1$. Now the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$0.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$1.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$0.14286$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$0.16139$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$0.16440$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$0.16440$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$6$</td>\n		    <td>$0.16440$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(523,'Example_5',5,124,'Given the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\ln(x) = x^2 - 4\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate the rightmost solution up to $5$ decimal places by using the Secant Method to determine $x_6$. Let $x_0$ and $x_1$ represent the two initial points.','Before anything else we need to determine a suitable interval to search. This can be accomplished by graphing the left and right hand sides independently:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/Secant_Method/Example_5.png\">\n</div>\nLooking at the graph shows that $[1,3]$ is a proper interval. Now we rewrite the equation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = \\ln(x) - x^2 + 4\n	}$\n</div>\nand in this scenario the Secant Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&x_{n + 1} \\\\\n		&= x_n - \\Big[ (\\ln(x_n) - x_n^2 + 4)(x_n - x_{n - 1}) \\Big] \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.2cm} \\cdot \\Big[ (\\ln(x_n) - \\ln(x_{n - 1})) - (x_n^2 - x_{n - 1}^2) \\Big]^{-1}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe can choose the starting points to be $x_0 = 1$ and $x_1 = 3$. Now the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$1.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$3.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$1.86939$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$2.12349$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$2.19334$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$2.18677$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$6$</td>\n		    <td>$2.18689$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(524,'Example_6',6,124,'Given the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		e^{\\sin(x)} = -x\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate the solution up to $5$ decimal places by using the Secant Method to determine $x_6$ on the interval $[-1,0]$. Let $x_0$ and $x_1$ represent the two initial points.','First we rewrite the equation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = e^{\\sin(x)} + x\n	}$\n</div>\nand in this scenario the Secant Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&x_{n + 1} \\\\\n		&= x_n - \\Big[ (e^{\\sin(x_n)} + x_n)(x_n - x_{n - 1}) \\Big] \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.2cm} \\cdot \\Big[ (e^{\\sin(x_n)} - e^{\\sin(x_{n - 2})}) + (x_n - x_{n - 1}) \\Big]^{-1}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe can choose the starting points to be $x_0 = -1$ and $x_1 = 0$. Now the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$0.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.63738$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.58698$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.57860$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.57871$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$6$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.57871$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(525,'Example_7',7,124,'Given the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^2 - c \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} c \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nshow that the sequence $x_0, x_1, x_2, \\dots$ of the Secant Method satisfies the difference equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = \\frac{x_nx_{n - 1} + c}{x_n + x_{n - 1}}\n	}$\n</div>','For the given function the Secant Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} &= x_n - \\frac{(x_n^2 - c)(x_n - x_{n - 1})}{x_n^2 - x_{n - 1}^2} \\\\\n		&= x_n - \\frac{x_n^2 + c}{x_n + x_{n - 1}} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{x_nx_{n - 1} + c}{x_n + x_{n - 1}}\n	}$\n</div>'),(526,'Example_8',8,124,'Given the recurrence relation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = \\frac{x_nx_{n - 1} + c}{x_n + x_{n - 1}}\n	}$\n</div>\nAssume that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} x_n = L\n	}$\n</div>\nand prove that $L = \\pm\\sqrt{c}$.','Given the limit we can also state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} x_{n + 1} = \\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} x_{n - 1} = L\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging all of this into the recurrence relation provides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} &= \\frac{x_nx_{n - 1} + c}{x_n + x_{n - 1}} \\\\\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} x_{n + 1} &= \\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{x_nx_{n - 1} + c}{x_n + x_{n - 1}} \\\\\n		L &= \\Big[ \\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} (x_nx_{n - 1} + c) \\Big] \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.2cm} \\cdot \\Big[ \\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} (x_n + x_{n - 1}) \\Big]^{-1} \\\\\n		L &= \\frac{L^2 + c}{2L} \\\\\n		2L^2 &= L^2 + c \\\\\n		L^2 &= c \\\\\n		L &= \\pm \\sqrt{c}\n	}$\n</div>'),(527,'Example_9',9,124,'Use the Secant Method to approximate $\\sqrt{2}$ up to $5$ decimal places at $x_6$. Let $x_0$ and $x_1$ represent the two initial points.','The number of interest is a root of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^2 - 2\n	}$\n</div>\nand looking at the graph:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/Secant_Method/Example_9.png\">\n</div>\nshows that a suitable interval to restrict ourselves to is $[1,2]$. Next up the Secant Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = x_n - \\frac{(x_n^2 - 2)(x_n - x_{n - 1})}{x_n^2 - x_{n - 1}^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nStarting at $x_0 = 1$ and $x_1 = 2$, the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$1.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$2.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$1.33333$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$1.40000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$1.41463$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$1.41421$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$6$</td>\n		    <td>$1.41421$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(528,'Example_10',10,124,'Use the Secant Method to approximate $\\sqrt{11}$ up to $5$ decimal places at $x_6$. Let $x_0$ and $x_1$ represent the two initial points.','The number of interest is a root of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^2 - 11\n	}$\n</div>\nand looking at the graph:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/Secant_Method/Example_10.png\">\n</div>\nshows that a suitable interval to restrict ourselves to is $[3,4]$. Next up the Secant Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = x_n - \\frac{(x_n^2 - 11)(x_n - x_{n - 1})}{x_n^2 - x_{n - 1}^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nStarting at $x_0 = 3$ aand $x_1 = 4$, the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$3.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$4.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$3.28571$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$3.31373$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$3.31664$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$3.31662$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$6$</td>\n		    <td>$3.31662$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(529,'Example_1',1,125,'Using Halley\'s Method determine $x_5$, up to $5$ decimal places, as an approximation of the root to the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^3 - x + 1\n	}$\n</div>\non the interval $[-2,-1]$.','In this scenario Halley\'s Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = x_n - \\frac{3x_n^2 - 1}{\\frac{(3x_n^2 - 1)^2}{x_n^3 - x_n + 1} - 3x_n}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe can choose the starting point to be $x = -1$ and the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.28571$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.32468$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.32472$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.32472$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.32472$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(530,'Example_2',2,125,'Given the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sin(x) = x^2\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate the solution up to $5$ decimal places by using Halley\'s Method to determine $x_5$ on the interval $\\Big[ \\frac{1}{2}, 1 \\Big]$.','First we rewrite the equation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = \\sin(x) - x^2\n	}$\n</div>\nand in this scenario Halley\'s Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = x_n - \\frac{2(\\cos(x_n) - 2x_n)}{\\frac{2(\\cos(x_n) - 2x_n)^2}{\\sin(x_n) - x_n^2} + \\sin(x_n) + 2}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe can choose the starting point to be $x = 1$ and the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$1.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$0.87856$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$0.87673$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$0.87673$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$0.87673$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$0.87673$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(531,'Example_3',3,125,'Given the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\sin(x) - x^2\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate the critical point up to $5$ decimal places by using Newton\'s Method to determine $x_5$ on the interval $[0,1]$.','First we differentiate the equation since we want to determine the critical point:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = \\cos(x) - 2x\n	}$\n</div>\nand in this scenario Newton\'s Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = x_n + \\frac{2(\\sin(x_n) + 2)}{\\frac{2(\\sin(x_n) + 2)^2}{\\cos(x_n) - 2x_n} + \\cos(x_n)}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe can choose the starting point to be $x = 0$ and the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$0.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$0.44444$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$0.45018$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$0.45018$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$0.45018$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$0.45018$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(532,'Example_4',4,125,'Given the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		6x = \\sqrt{1 - x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate the solution up to $5$ decimal places by using Halley\'s Method to determine $x_5$.','Before anything else we need to determine a suitable interval to search. This can be accomplished by graphing the left and right hand sides independently:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/HalleyAPOSTROPHEs_Method/Example_4.png\">\n</div>\nLooking at the graph shows that $[0,1]$ is a proper interval. Now we rewrite the equation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = 6x - \\sqrt{1 - x^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nand in this scenario Halley\'s Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = x_n - \\frac{2\\Big( 6 + \\frac{2x_n}{\\sqrt{1 - x_n^2}} \\Big)}{\\frac{2\\Big( 6 + \\frac{2x_n}{\\sqrt{1 - x_n^2}} \\Big)^2}{6x_n - \\sqrt{1 - x_n^2}} + \\frac{2x_n^2 + 2}{(1 - x_n^2)^{\\frac{3}{2}}}}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe can choose the starting point to be $x = 0$ and the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$0.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$0.17143$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$0.16460$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$0.16440$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$0.16440$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$0.16440$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(533,'Example_5',5,125,'Given the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\ln(x) = x^2 - 4\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate the rightmost solution up to $5$ decimal places by using Halley\'s Method to determine $x_5$.','Before anything else we need to determine a suitable interval to search. This can be accomplished by graphing the left and right hand sides independently:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/HalleyAPOSTROPHEs_Method/Example_5.png\">\n</div>\nLooking at the graph shows that $[1,3]$ is a proper interval. Now we rewrite the equation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = \\ln(x) - x^2 + 4\n	}$\n</div>\nand in this scenario Halley\'s Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = x_n - \\frac{2\\Big( \\frac{1}{x_n} - 2x_n \\Big)}{\\frac{2\\Big( \\frac{1}{x_n} - 2x_n \\Big)^2}{\\ln(x_n) - x_n^2 + 4} + \\frac{1}{x_n^2} + 2}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe can choose the starting point to be $x = 1$ and the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$1.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$1.54545$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$2.13759$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$2.18688$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$2.18689$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$2.18689$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(534,'Example_6',6,125,'Given the equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		e^{\\sin(x)} = -x\n	}$\n</div>\napproximate the solution up to $5$ decimal places by using Halley\'s Method to determine $x_5$ on the interval $[-1,0]$.','First we rewrite the equation as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = e^{\\sin(x)} + x\n	}$\n</div>\nand in this scenario Halley\'s Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&x_{n + 1} = x_n \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - \\frac{ \\frac{2(\\cos(x_n)e^{\\sin(x_n)} + 1)}{\\cos^2(x_n) - \\sin(x_n)}} {\\frac{2(\\cos(x_n)e^{\\sin(x_n)} + 1)^2}{\\Big( e^{\\sin(x_n)} + x_n \\Big)(\\cos^2(x_n) - \\sin(x_n))} - e^{\\sin(x_n)}}\n	}$\n</div>\nWe can choose the starting point to be $x = -1$ and the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.57721$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.57871$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.57871$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.57871$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$-0.57871$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(535,'Example_7',7,125,'Given the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^2 - c \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} c \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nshow that the sequence $x_0, x_1, x_2, \\dots$ of Halley\'s Method satisfies the difference equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = \\frac{x_n^3 + 3cx_n}{3x_n^2 + c}\n	}$\n</div>','For the given function Halley\'s Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} &= x_n - \\frac{2(x_n^2 - c)(2x_n)}{2(2x_n)^2 - (x_n^2 - c)(2)} \\\\\n		&= x_n - \\frac{2x_n^3 - 2cx_n}{3x_n^2 + c} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{x_n^3 + 3cx_n}{3x_n^2 + c}\n	}$\n</div>'),(536,'Example_8',8,125,'Given the recurrence relation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = \\frac{x_n^3 + 3cx_n}{3x_n^2 + c}\n	}$\n</div>\nAssume that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} x_n = L\n	}$\n</div>\nand prove that $L = 0, \\pm\\sqrt{c}$.','Given the limit we can also state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} x_{n + 1} = L\n	}$\n</div>\nPlugging all of this into the recurrence relation provides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} &= \\frac{x_n^3 + 3cx_n}{3x_n^2 + c} \\\\\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} x_{n + 1} &= \\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{x_n^3 + 3cx_n}{3x_n^2 + c} \\\\\n		L &= \\frac{L^3 + 3cL}{3L^2 + c} \\\\\n		3L^3 + cL &= L^3 + 3cL \\\\\n		0 &= 2L^3 - 2cL \\\\\n		0 &= 2L(L^2 - c) \\\\\n		L &= 0, \\pm \\sqrt{c}\n	}$\n</div>'),(537,'Example_9',9,125,'Use Halley\'s Method to approximate $\\sqrt{2}$ up to $5$ decimal places at $x_5$.','The number of interest is a root of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^2 - 2\n	}$\n</div>\nand looking at the graph:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/HalleyAPOSTROPHEs_Method/Example_9.png\">\n</div>\nshows that a suitable interval to restrict ourselves to is $[1,2]$. Next up Halley\'s Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = \\frac{x_n^3 + 6x_n}{3x_n^2 + 2}\n	}$\n</div>\nStarting at $x = 1$, the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$1.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$1.40000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$1.41421$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$1.41421$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$1.41421$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$1.41421$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(538,'Example_10',10,125,'Use Halley\'s Method to approximate $\\sqrt{11}$ up to $5$ decimal places at $x_5$.','The number of interest is a root of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^2 - 11\n	}$\n</div>\nand looking at the graph:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Applications_of_the_Derivative/HalleyAPOSTROPHEs_Method/Example_10.png\">\n</div>\nshows that a suitable interval to restrict ourselves to is $[3,4]$. Next up Halley\'s Method takes the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = \\frac{x_n^3 + 33x_n}{3x_n^2 + 11}\n	}$\n</div>\nStarting at $x = 3$, the iterations take on the values:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{n}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}_n$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$1.00000$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$1$</td>\n		    <td>$3.31579$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$2$</td>\n		    <td>$3.31662$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$3$</td>\n		    <td>$3.31662$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$4$</td>\n		    <td>$3.31662$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$5$</td>\n		    <td>$3.31662$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(539,'Example_1',1,126,'Determine all critical points of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = -x^3 + 3x^2 - 3x\n	}$\n</div>\nand identify each one\'s behavior according to the Higher-Order Derivative Test.','To determine the critical points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= -3x^2 + 6x - 3 \\\\\n		0 &= x^2 - 2x + 1 \\\\\n		0 &= (x - 1)^2 \\\\\n		x &= 1\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we keep taking derivatives at the critical point until it evaluates to something other than zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'\'(x) = -6x + 6 &\\implies f\'\'(1) = 0 \\\\\n		f\'\'\'(x) = -6 &\\implies f\'\'\'(1) = -6\n	}$\n</div>\nSo in our case $n = 3$ and $f^{(n)}(0) < 0$. According to the Higher-Order Derivative Test the critical point $x = 1$ is a strictly decreasing point of inflection for the original function.'),(540,'Example_2',2,126,'Determine all critical points of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^6 + \\ln(2)\n	}$\n</div>\nand identify each one\'s behavior according to the Higher-Order Derivative Test.','To determine the critical points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= 6x^5 \\\\\n		0 &= 6x^5 \\\\\n		x &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we keep taking derivatives at the critical point until it evaluates to something other than zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'\'(x) = 30x^4 &\\implies f\'\'(0) = 0 \\\\\n		f\'\'\'(x) = 120x^3 &\\implies f\'\'\'(0) = 0 \\\\\n		f^{(4)}(x) = 360x^2 &\\implies f^{(4)}(0) = 0 \\\\\n		f^{(5)}(x) = 720x &\\implies f^{(5)}(0) = 0 \\\\\n		f^{(6)}(x) = 720x &\\implies f^{(6)}(0) = 720\n	}$\n</div>\nSo in our case $n = 6$ and $f^{(n)}(0) > 0$. According to the Higher-Order Derivative Test the critical point $x = 0$ is a relative minimum for the original function.'),(541,'Example_3',3,126,'Determine all critical points of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\tan^3(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nand identify each one\'s behavior according to the Higher-Order Derivative Test.','To determine the critical points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= 3\\tan^2(x)\\sec^2(x) \\\\\n		0 &= 3\\tan^2(x)\\sec^2(x) \\\\\n		0 &= \\tan(x) \\\\\n		x &= k\\pi \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} k \\in \\mathbb{Z}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we keep taking derivatives at the critical points until it evaluates to something other than zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'\'(x) &= 6\\tan(x)\\sec^4(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 6\\tan^3(x)\\sec^2(x) \\\\\n		&\\implies f\'\'(k\\pi) = 0 \\\\\n		f\'\'\'(x) &= 6\\sec^6(x) + 42\\tan^2(x)\\sec^4(x) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 12\\tan^4(x)\\sec^2(x) \\\\\n		&\\implies f\'\'\'(k\\pi) = 6\n	}$\n</div>\nSo in our case $n = 3$ and $f^{(n)}(0) > 0$. According to the Higher-Order Derivative Test all of the critical points, $x = k\\pi$, are strictly increasing points of inflection for the original function.'),(542,'Example_4',4,126,'Determine all critical points of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = (\\ln(x))^3\n	}$\n</div>\nand identify each one\'s behavior according to the Higher-Order Derivative Test.','To determine the critical points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= \\frac{3\\ln^2(x)}{x} \\\\\n		0 &= \\frac{3\\ln^2(x)}{x} \\\\\n		0 &= \\ln(x) \\\\\n		x &= 1\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we keep taking derivatives at the critical point until it evaluates to something other than zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'\'(x) &= \\frac{3(2 - \\ln(x))\\ln(x)}{x^2} \\\\\n		&\\implies f\'\'(1) = 0 \\\\\n		f\'\'\'(x) &= \\frac{6(\\ln^2(x) - 3\\ln(x) + 1)}{x^3} \\\\\n		&\\implies f\'\'\'(1) = 6 \n	}$\n</div>\nSo in our case $n = 3$ and $f^{(n)}(0) > 0$. According to the Higher-Order Derivative Test the critical point $x = 1$ is a strictly increasing point of inflection for the original function.'),(543,'Example_5',5,126,'Determine all critical points of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^2\\arctan(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nand identify each one\'s behavior according to the Higher-Order Derivative Test.','To determine the critical points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= 2x\\arctan(x) + \\frac{x^2}{x^2 + 1} \\\\\n		0 &= x\\Big( \\frac{x}{x^2 + 1} + 2\\arctan(x) \\Big) \\\\\n		x &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $x = 0$ is the only solution since the other factor is strictly negative for $x < 0$ and positive for $x > 0$. Now we keep taking derivatives at the critical point until it evaluates to something other than zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'\'(x) &= \\frac{2(x^3 + 2x + (x^2 + 1)^2\\arctan(x))}{(x^2 + 1)^2} \\\\\n		&\\implies f\'\'(0) = 0 \\\\\n		f\'\'\'(x) &= -\\frac{2(x^2 - 3)}{(x^2 + 1)^3} \\\\\n		&\\implies f\'\'\'(0) = 6\n	}$\n</div>\nSo in our case $n = 3$ and $f^{(n)}(0) > 0$. According to the Higher-Order Derivative Test the critical point $x = 0$ is a strictly increasing point of inflection for the original function.'),(544,'Example_6',6,126,'Determine all critical points of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\frac{e^x}{x^2 + 1}\n	}$\n</div>\nand identify each one\'s behavior according to the Higher-Order Derivative Test.','To determine the critical points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= \\frac{e^x(x - 1)^2}{(x^2 + 1)^2} \\\\\n		0 &= \\frac{e^x(x - 1)^2}{(x^2 + 1)^2} \\\\\n		x &= 1\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we keep taking derivatives at the critical point until it evaluates to something other than zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'\'(x) &= \\frac{e^x(x^4 - 4x^3 + 8x^2 - 4x - 1)}{(x^2 + 1)^3} \\\\\n		&\\implies f\'\'(1) = 0 \\\\\n		f\'\'\'(x) &= \\frac{e^x(x^6 - 6x^5 + 21x^4)}{(x^2 + 1)^4} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - \\frac{e^x(36x^3 - 15x^2 - 18x + 5)}{(x^2 + 1)^4} \\\\\n		&\\implies f\'\'\'(1) = \\frac{e}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nSo in our case $n = 3$ and $f^{(n)}(0) > 0$. According to the Higher-Order Derivative Test the critical point $x = 1$ is a strictly increasing point of inflection for the original function.'),(545,'Example_7',7,126,'Determine all critical points of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = e^{x^3}\n	}$\n</div>\nand identify each one\'s behavior according to the Higher-Order Derivative Test.','To determine the critical points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= 3x^2e^{x^3} \\\\\n		0 &= 3x^2e^{x^3} \\\\\n		x &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we keep taking derivatives at the critical point until it evaluates to something other than zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'\'(x) &= 3x(3x^3 + 2)e^{x^3} \\\\\n		&\\implies f\'\'(0) = 0 \\\\\n		f\'\'\'(x) &= 3(9x^6 + 18x^3 + 2)e^{x^3} \\\\\n		&\\implies f\'\'\'(0) = 6\n	}$\n</div>\nSo in our case $n = 3$ and $f^{(n)}(0) > 0$. According to the Higher-Order Derivative Test the critical point $x = 0$ is a strictly increasing point of inflection for the original function.'),(546,'Example_8',8,126,'Determine all critical points of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\frac{x^2 + 1}{e^x}\n	}$\n</div>\nand identify each one\'s behavior according to the Higher-Order Derivative Test.','To determine the critical points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= -(x - 1)^2 e^{-x} \\\\\n		0 &= -(x - 1)^2 e^{-x} \\\\\n		x &= 1\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we keep taking derivatives at the critical point until it evaluates to something other than zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'\'(x) &= (x^2 - 4x + 3)e^{-x} \\\\\n		&\\implies f\'\'(1) = 0 \\\\\n		f\'\'\'(x) &= x(x^2 - 6x + 7)e^{-x} \\\\\n		&\\implies f\'\'\'(1) = 0 \\\\\n		f^{(4)}(x) &= (x^2 - 8x + 13)e^{-x} \\\\\n		&\\implies f^{(4)}(1) = 6e^{-1}\n	}$\n</div>\nSo in our case $n = 4$ and $f^{(n)}(0) > 0$. According to the Higher-Order Derivative Test the critical point $x = 1$ is a relative minimum for the original function.'),(547,'Example_9',9,126,'Determine all critical points of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = x^n \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} n \\in \\mathbb{N}\n	}$\n</div>\nand identify each one\'s behavior according to the Higher-Order Derivative Test.','To determine the critical points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= nx^{n - 1} \\\\\n		0 &= nx^{n - 1} \\\\\n		x &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we keep taking derivatives at the critical point until it evaluates to something other than zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'\'(x) &= n(n - 1)x^{n - 2} \\\\\n		&\\implies f\'\'(0) = 0 \\\\\n		f\'\'\'(x) &= n(n - 1)(n - 2)x^{n - 3} \\\\\n		&\\implies f\'\'\'(0) = 0 \\\\\n		&\\vdots \\\\\n		f^{(n - 1)}(x) &= n!x \\\\\n		&\\implies f^{(n - 1)}(0) = 0 \\\\\n		f^{(n)}(x) &= n! \\\\\n		&\\implies f^{(n)}(0) = n!\n	}$\n</div>\nWe know that $n!$ is strictly positive so now depending upon the nature of $n$ the behavior changes:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$n$</td>\n		    <td>Implication</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>Even</td>\n		    <td>$x = c$ is a relative minimum of $f$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>Odd</td>\n		    <td>$x = c$ is a strictly increasing point of inflection of $f$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(548,'Example_10',10,126,'Determine all critical points of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = g(x)(x - a)^n \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} n \\in \\mathbb{N} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} a \\in \\mathbb{R} \n	}$\n</div>\ngiven the conditions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(a) \\neq 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} g\'(x)(x - a) + ng(x) \\neq 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\forall x\n	}$\n</div>\nand identify each one\'s behavior according to the Higher-Order Derivative Test.','To determine the critical points:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= g\'(x)(x - a)^n + ng(x)(x - a)^{n - 1} \\\\\n		0 &= g\'(x)(x - a)^n + ng(x)(x - a)^{n - 1} \\\\\n		0 &= (x - a)^{n - 1}(g\'(x)(x - a) + ng(x)) \\\\\n		x &= a\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we keep taking derivatives at the critical point until it evaluates to something other than zero:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'\'(x) &= g\'\'(x)(x - a)^n \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 2ng\'(x)(x - a)^{n - 1} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + n(n - 1)g(x)(x - a)^{n - 2} \\\\\n		&\\implies f\'\'(a) = 0 \\\\\n		f\'\'\'(x) &= g\'\'\'(x)(x - a)^n \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 3ng\'\'(x)(x - a)^{n - 1} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + 3n(n - 1)g\'(x)(x - a)^{n - 2} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + n(n - 1)(n - 2)g(x)(x - a)^{n - 3} \\\\\n		&\\implies f\'\'\'(a) = 0 \\\\\n		&\\vdots \\\\\n		f^{(k)}(x) &= \\\\\n		&\\sum_{i = 0}^k {k \\choose i} \\frac{n!}{(n - i)!} g^{(k - i)}(x) (x - a)^{n - i} \\\\\n		&\\implies f^{(k)}(a) = 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{if} \\hspace{.3cm} k \\leq n \\\\\n		f^{(n)}(x) &= \\\\\n		&\\sum_{i = 0}^n {n \\choose i} \\frac{n!}{(n - i)!} g^{(n - i)}(x) (x - a)^{n - i} \\\\\n		&\\implies f^{(n)}(a) = n!g(a)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow depending on the specific parameters the result is different:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$n$</td>\n		    <td>Sign of $g(a)$</td>\n		    <td>Implication</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>Even</td>\n		    <td>$-$</td>\n		    <td>$x = c$ is a relative maximum of $f$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>Even</td>\n		    <td>$+$</td>\n		    <td>$x = c$ is a relative minimum of $f$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>Odd</td>\n		    <td>$-$</td>\n		    <td>$x = c$ is a strictly decreasing point of inflection of $f$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>Odd</td>\n		    <td>$+$</td>\n		    <td>$x = c$ is a strictly increasing point of inflection of $f$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>'),(549,'Example_1',1,127,'Prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 5} 7 = 7\n	}$\n</div>\nby using the $(\\delta, \\epsilon)$ definition of the limit.','By the formal definition a limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) = L\n	}$\n</div>\nwill exist if $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\delta > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nSo we want to find a $\\delta$ in terms of $\\epsilon$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|x - 5| < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nUsing the other inequality we arrive at:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		|(7) - 7| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		|0| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		0 &< \\epsilon\n	}$\n</div>\nFrom the above it seems that no matter the value of $\\delta$ the inequalities will hold true. So we can allow $\\delta \\in \\mathbb{R}$.'),(550,'Example_2',2,127,'Prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 10} (3x + 5) = 35\n	}$\n</div>\nby using the $(\\delta, \\epsilon)$ definition of the limit.','By the formal definition a limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) = L\n	}$\n</div>\nwill exist if $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\delta > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nSo we want to find a $\\delta$ in terms of $\\epsilon$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|x - 10| < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nUsing the other inequality we arrive at:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		|(3x + 5) - 35| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		|3x - 30| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		3|x - 10| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		|x - 10| &< \\frac{\\epsilon}{3}\n	}$\n</div>\nSo as long as we choose $\\delta = \\frac{\\epsilon}{3}$ the inequalities will hold true, thus making the limit true.'),(551,'Example_3',3,127,'Prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} (x^2 + x - 2) = 4\n	}$\n</div>\nby using the $(\\delta, \\epsilon)$ definition of the limit.','By the formal definition a limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) = L\n	}$\n</div>\nwill exist if $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\delta > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nSo we want to find a $\\delta$ in terms of $\\epsilon$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|x - 2| < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nUsing the other inequality we arrive at:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		|(x^2 + x - 2) - 4| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		|x^2 + x - 6| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		|(x + 3)(x - 2)| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		|x + 3||x - 2| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		|x - 2| &< \\frac{\\epsilon}{|x + 3|}\n	}$\n</div>\nThe only question remaining now is how do we get rid of the denominator. You can choose an arbitrary value such as $\\delta = 1$ which provides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|x - 2| < 1 \\implies 1 < x < 3\n	}$\n</div>\nUsing this we can deduce:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|x - 2| &< \\frac{\\epsilon}{|x + 3|} \\\\\n		&< \\frac{\\epsilon}{6}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich minimizes the right hand-side by letting $x = 3$. So now we have the issue that there are two possibilities for $\\delta$. With two choices, we should choose the smaller one to be more accurate. So as long as we choose $\\delta = \\min\\Big\\{ 1, \\frac{\\epsilon}{6} \\Big\\}$ the inequalities will hold true, thus making the limit true.'),(552,'Example_4',4,127,'Prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 3} \\frac{2}{x + 3} = \\frac{1}{3}\n	}$\n</div>\nby using the $(\\delta, \\epsilon)$ definition of the limit.','By the formal definition a limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) = L\n	}$\n</div>\nwill exist if $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\delta > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nSo we want to find a $\\delta$ in terms of $\\epsilon$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|x - 3| < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nUsing the other inequality we arrive at:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		\\Big| \\frac{2}{x + 3} - \\frac{1}{3} \\Big| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		\\Big| \\frac{2(3) - (x + 3)}{3(x + 3)} \\Big| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		\\Big| \\frac{3 - x}{3(3 + x)} \\Big| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		\\frac{|3 - x|}{|3(3 + x)|} &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		\\frac{|x - 3|}{3|x + 3|} &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		|x - 3| &< 3|x + 3|\\epsilon\n	}$\n</div>\nThe only question remaining now is how do we get rid of the linear factor on the right side. You can choose an arbitrary value such as $\\delta = 1$ which provides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|x - 3| < 1 \\implies 2 < x < 4\n	}$\n</div>\nUsing this we can deduce:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|x - 3| &< 3|x + 3|\\epsilon \\\\\n		&< 15\\epsilon\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich minimizes the right hand-side by letting $x = 2$. So now we have the issue that there are two possibilities for $\\delta$. With two choices, we should choose the smaller one to be more accurate. So as long as we choose $\\delta = \\min\\Big\\{ 1, 15\\epsilon \\Big\\}$ the inequalities will hold true, thus making the limit true.'),(553,'Example_5',5,127,'Prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 9} (2 + \\sqrt{x}) = 5\n	}$\n</div>\nby using the $(\\delta, \\epsilon)$ definition of the limit.','By the formal definition a limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) = L\n	}$\n</div>\nwill exist if $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\delta > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nSo we want to find a $\\delta$ in terms of $\\epsilon$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|x - 9| < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nUsing the other inequality we arrive at:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		|(2 + \\sqrt{x}) - 5| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		|\\sqrt{x} - 3| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		|\\sqrt{x} - 3||\\sqrt{x} + 3| &< |\\sqrt{x} + 3|\\epsilon \\\\\n		|x - 9| &< |\\sqrt{x} + 3|\\epsilon\n	}$\n</div>\nThe only question remaining now is how do we get rid of the factor on the right side. You can choose an arbitrary value such as $\\delta = 1$ which provides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|x - 9| < 1 \\implies 8 < x < 10\n	}$\n</div>\nUsing this we can deduce:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|x - 9| &< |\\sqrt{x} + 3|\\epsilon \\\\\n		&< (\\sqrt{8} + 3)\\epsilon\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich minimizes the right hand-side by letting $x = 8$. So now we have the issue that there are two possibilities for $\\delta$. With two choices, we should choose the smaller one to be more accurate. So as long as we choose $\\delta = \\min\\Big\\{ 1, (\\sqrt{8} + 3)\\epsilon \\Big\\}$ the inequalities will hold true, thus making the limit true.'),(554,'Example_6',6,127,'Prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 4} \\sqrt{x + 5} = 3\n	}$\n</div>\nby using the $(\\delta, \\epsilon)$ definition of the limit.','By the formal definition a limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) = L\n	}$\n</div>\nwill exist if $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\delta > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nSo we want to find a $\\delta$ in terms of $\\epsilon$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|x - 4| < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nUsing the other inequality we arrive at:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		|\\sqrt{x + 5} - 3| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		|\\sqrt{x + 5} - 3||\\sqrt{x + 5} + 3| &< |\\sqrt{x + 5} + 3|\\epsilon \\\\\n		|(x + 5) - 9| &< |\\sqrt{x + 5} + 3|\\epsilon \\\\\n		|x - 4| &< |\\sqrt{x + 5} + 3|\\epsilon\n	}$\n</div>\nThe only question remaining now is how do we get rid of the factor on the right side. You can choose an arbitrary value such as $\\delta = 1$ which provides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|x - 4| < 1 \\implies 3 < x < 5\n	}$\n</div>\nUsing this we can deduce:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|x - 4| &< |\\sqrt{x + 5} + 3|\\epsilon \\\\\n		&< (\\sqrt{8} + 3)\\epsilon\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich minimizes the right hand-side by letting $x = 8$. So now we have the issue that there are two possibilities for $\\delta$. With two choices, we should choose the smaller one to be more accurate. So as long as we choose $\\delta = \\min\\Big\\{ 1, (\\sqrt{8} + 3)\\epsilon \\Big\\}$ the inequalities will hold true, thus making the limit true.'),(555,'Example_7',7,127,'Prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 1} \\frac{3x^2 - 3x}{x - 1} = 3\n	}$\n</div>\nby using the $(\\delta, \\epsilon)$ definition of the limit.','By the formal definition a limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) = L\n	}$\n</div>\nwill exist if $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\delta > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nSo we want to find a $\\delta$ in terms of $\\epsilon$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|x - 1| < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nUsing the other inequality we arrive at:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		\\Big| \\frac{3x^2 - 3x}{x - 1} - 3 \\Big| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		\\Big| \\frac{3x(x - 1)}{x - 1} - 3 \\Big| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		|(3x) - 3| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		3|x - 1| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		|x - 1| &< \\frac{\\epsilon}{3}\n	}$\n</div>\nSo as long as we choose $\\delta = \\frac{\\epsilon}{3}$ the inequalities will hold true, thus making the limit true.'),(556,'Example_8',8,127,'Prove the $\\textit{Triangle Inequality}$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|x + y| \\leq |x| + |y| \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} x,y \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>','Begin by noting that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|x + y|^2 = (x + y)^2\n	}$\n</div>\nNow by expanding the right side and using properties of the absolute value:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|x + y|^2 &= (x + y)^2 \\\\\n		&= x^2 + 2xy + y^2 \\\\\n		&= |x|^2 + 2xy + |y|^2 \\\\\n		&\\leq |x|^2 + 2|xy| + |y|^2 \\\\\n		&= |x|^2 + 2|x||y| + |y|^2 \\\\\n		&= (|x| + |y|)^2\n	}$\n</div>\nWe finally arrive at:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|x + y|^2 &\\leq (|x| + |y|)^2 \\\\\n		|x + y| &\\leq |x| + |y|\n	}$\n</div>'),(557,'Example_9',9,127,'Prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} c = c \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} c \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nby using the $(\\delta, \\epsilon)$ definition of the limit.','By the formal definition a limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) = L\n	}$\n</div>\nwill exist if $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\delta > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nIn this scenario the function of interest is $f(x) = c$ giving:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		|c - c| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		|0| &< \\epsilon \\\\\n		0 &< \\epsilon\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich holds true because it is initially assumed that $\\epsilon > 0$. Now it does not matter what the value of $\\epsilon$ is, and as for $\\delta$ any positive value can be chosen because no matter the $\\delta$ the initial condition is already satisfied.'),(558,'Example_10',10,127,'Prove that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} cf(x) = c\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} c \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nby using the $(\\delta, \\epsilon)$ definition of the limit and assuming that the limit on the right-hand side exists.','Assuming that the limit of the function exists:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) = L\n	}$\n</div>\nthen we know $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\delta_1 > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L| < \\frac{\\epsilon}{|c|} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta_1\n	}$\n</div>\nWe need to show:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|cf(x) - cL| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nSo we choose $\\delta = \\delta_1$ to use the inequality for $f(x)$ to obtain:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|cf(x) - cL| &= |c||f(x) - L| \\\\\n		&< |c| \\cdot \\frac{\\epsilon}{|c|} \\\\\n		&= \\epsilon\n	}$\n</div>');
