INSERT INTO `section` VALUES (80,'Terminology',1,21,'Definition','Order','Linear','General vs. Particular Solution','Explicit vs. Implicit Solution','Interval of Existance',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'When discussing differential equations, there exist two main classes: ODEs and PDEs. PDEs, partial differential equations, which involve functions of more than a single independent variable are typically harder to approach and so will not be discussed further here. Thus, when referencing differential equations here, we are going to be talking about ODEs, ordinary differential equations, which involve only functions of a single variable and any of its derivatives. To be formal, an equation in the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y^{(n)} = F(x,y,y^{(1)},y^{(2)},\\dots,y^{(n-1)})\n	}$\n</div>\nis known as an $\\textit{explicit differential equation}$ where $y^{(n)}$ denotes the $n$th derivative, $x$ is the independent variable, and $F$ is some function of the independent variable and all derivatives of $y(x)$ except for the $n$th one. While this formulization gives a clear definition, it may not always be possible to solve for $y^{(n)}$ using known analytic methods. Therefore, an $\\textit{implicit}$ $\\textit{ differential equation}$ is one in the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = F(x,y,y^{(1)},y^{(2)},\\dots,y^{(n-1)},y^{(n)})\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $F$ is now a function of the independent variable and all the derivatives of $y(x)$.','A typical way to characterize a given differential equation is to use its $\\textit{order}$ where the order is defined to be the natural number corresponding to the highest derivative involved. For example:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y^{(5)} + x^2y^{(4)}y^2 = \\sin(x)y^{(3)}\n	}$\n</div>\nthis differential equation can be said to have order five since the highest derivative involved is the fifth derivative.','While order definitely gives a good characterization of a differential equation, it does not provide any means of understanding how the differential equation is actually structured. A differential equation is said to be $\\textit{linear}$ if it can be written in the format:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\sum_{i=0}^{n} a_i(x)y^{(i)} = k(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $a_i(x)$ are some functions of $x$ strictly attached to some derivative of $y(x)$ and $k(x)$ is a standalone part. If an equation cannot be written in this format, then it is known as a $\\textit{non-linear}$ differential equation. For example:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y^{(5)} + x^2y^{(4)}y^2 = \\sin(x)y^{(3)}\n	}$\n</div>\nis not a linear differential equation since the fourth derivative is multiplied by the original function squared. On the other hand:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		7\\sin(x)y^{(4)} + 3\\ln|x| = 2y + 3e^xy^{(2)}\n	}$\n</div>\nis a linear differential equation. Now using the setup for a linear differential equation, further classifications exist depending on the standalone part. If $k(x) = 0$ the linear differential equation is also classified as $\\textit{homogeneous}$, otherwise it is $\\textit{non-homogeneous}$.','Whenever solving a given differential equation, it will always come to the fact that solutions usually involve constants that cannot be determined unless more information is given. When no more information is available, the $\\textit{general solution}$ to a differential equation will model all the possible curves that satisfy the equation up to a constant(s). When an initial condition(s) is given, the problem turns into an IVP, initial value problem, which requires not only solving the differential equation for the general solution, but then using the general solution and the initial condition to get the $\\textit{particular solution}$. For example:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = C \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} C \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nis the general solution to the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'(x) = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nIf an initial condition is given that $y(x_0) = y_0$, then plugging in to determine the value of $C$ gives:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = y_0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich has now become a particular solution to the differential equation.','Whenever discussing functions, there exist two common ways to write them down. An $\\textit{explicit function}$ is one that is written in the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = f(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nsuch that it becomes clear that $x$ is the independent variable and $y$ is the dependent variable which is a function of the independent one. Any solution to a differential equation that can be written in this form is known as an $\\textit{explicit solution}$. On the other hand, not all solutions can be written in explicit form. Therefore, an $\\textit{implicit function}$ is one that is written as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		F(x,y) = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich allows for an interpretation where neither variable is dependent on the other. If asked which is preferred, there really is no good answer to the question. Some differential equations can always have solutions in explicit form, while other ones are always left in implicit form. So generally speaking, it depends on the scenario which is preferred.','Typically whenever a solution is found for a given differential equation, it is interesting to see where the solution exists. The domain of the solution is commonly known as the $\\textit{interval of existance}$ or $\\textit{interval of validity}$. For example given that the solution to some differential equation is given as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y(x) = \\frac{1}{x-1}\n	}$\n</div>\nthen the interval of existance is given as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(-\\infty,1) \\cup (1,\\infty)\n	}$\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(81,'Autonomous_Systems',1,22,'The Setup','Equilibrium Points and the Phase Plot',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'A differential equation in the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'(x) = f(y(x))\n	}$\n</div>\nis known as a first order autonomous system. It distinguishes itself from other first order differential equations because the derivative is only dependent on $y$ and not $x$.','When dealing with first order autonomous systems, $\\textit{equilibrium points}$ are typically of interest. To be formal, any $y = y_0$ that satisfies:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(y_0) = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nis known as an equilibrium point. After determining the equilibrium points we want to now observe how the derivative behaves on each of the intervals in between. For example take the autonomous system:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\'(x) = y(y + 1)(y - 1)^2\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the equilibrium points are $y = -1, 0, 1$. Now we want to determine the behavior of the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>Range</td>\n		    <td>$y\'(x)$ Behavior</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(-\\infty,-1)$</td>\n		    <td>+</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(-1,0)$</td>\n		    <td>-</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(0,1)$</td>\n		    <td>+</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$(1,\\infty)$</td>\n		    <td>+</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nPlotting this out as a slope field gives what is known as the $\\textit{phase plot}$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/First_Order/Autonomous_Systems/Autonomous_Example.png\">\n</div>\nNow notice that each equilibrium point behaves a little differently. At $y = -1$ we have the vectors pointing towards from both below and above. Whenever this occurs the equilibrium point is said to be $\\textit{stable}$. At $y = 0$ we have the vectors pointing away both below and above. Whenever this happens the equilibrium point is said to be $\\textit{unstable}$. Lastly for $y = 1$ from below the vectors are pointing towards and above the vectors are pointing away, and so this halfway situation describes the equilibrium point as $\\textit{semistable}$. Typically this type of information is enough to tell the behavior of a particular solution given the initial condition. For example consider that we have the initial condition $y(0) = -2$ for the differential equation above. What happens to $y(x)$ in the long run to the right:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} y(x) = ?\n	}$\n</div>\nIn order to make sense of this, plot the initial condition on the phase plot and notice that if we follow the pattern of the vectors it eventually lands us at $y = -1$. Sometimes books like to use what is known as a $\\textit{phase line}$ which represents the behavior of the derivative on a one dimensional line instead of using a plot to show it. I will agree that the phase line provides enough information to work with, but the phase plot gives a better picture of what the family of curves will look like so I will stick to them instead.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(82,'Slope_Fields_and_Solution_Curves',3,21,'Slope Fields','Solution Curves',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'In order to gain a better understanding of differential equations, slope fields provide a geometrical approach to a first order differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' = f(x,y)\n	}$\n</div>\nTo view the slope field, take $\\mathbb{R}^2$ and for every point evaluate the derivative. Then at each point draw a small vector and use the magnitude of the derivative to correspond to the magnitude of the vector. If the value is a large positive number, the vector will point more upwards. For values near zero the vector will point horizontally, and for very negative values it will point downwards. To make the patten clear, all of the vectors point in the \"right\" direction, thus all arrows will be bound between the angles $\\Big[ -\\frac{\\pi}{2}, \\frac{\\pi}{2} \\Big]$. For example consider the differential equation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' = x\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich provides the slope field:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/Introduction/Slope_Fields_and_Solution_Curves/Slope_Field.png\">\n</div>\nNotice how for each value of $x$ the vectors are consistent vertically. This happens because the derivative is independent of $y$, meaning that you can take a single horizontal section of the slope field and copy it above and below to generate the rest since they are identical. Unfortunately, not all cases are this easy if we consider:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' = 2x - y\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich provides the slope field:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/Introduction/Slope_Fields_and_Solution_Curves/Slope_Field_Example.png\">\n</div>','With the slope field in mind, consider that the vectors drawn typically follow some sort of pattern. This patten actually helps to identify the family of solutions. Using the previous example:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' = 2x - y\n	}$\n</div>\nprovides the solution curves:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Ordinary_Differential_Equations/Introduction/Slope_Fields_and_Solution_Curves/Solution_Curve_Example.png\">\n</div>\nThe solution to this is known to be:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = 2x - 2 + Ce^{-x}\n	}$\n</div>\nand for different values of $C$ the function may behave differently. Observing closely confirms that when $C = 0$ the solution is a straight line, and for all other values the solution will behave like a line at very large values of $x$ since the exponential term becomes negligible.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(83,'Separable',2,22,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(84,'Linear',3,22,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(85,'Bernoulli',4,22,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(86,'Exact',5,22,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(87,'Homogeneous_Substitution',6,22,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(88,'EulerAPOSTROPHEs_Method',8,22,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(90,'Linear_Substitution',7,22,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(91,'The_Principle_of_Superposition',2,23,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(92,'Constant_Coefficient_and_Linear',4,23,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(93,'Linear_Independence',1,23,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(94,'Reduction_of_Order',3,23,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(95,'Method_of_Undetermined_Coefficients',5,23,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(96,'Annihilator_Method',6,23,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(97,'CauchyANDEuler',8,23,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(98,'Variation_of_Parameters',9,23,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(99,'Power_Series_Solutions',7,23,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(100,'Laplace_Transforms',10,23,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(101,'Power_Rule',3,24,'Definition','Proof by Induction for $n \\in \\mathbb{N}$_hidden','Proof with Binomial Theorem for $n \\in \\mathbb{N}$_hidden','Proof by Chain Rule for $n \\in \\mathbb{Q}$_hidden','Proof for $n \\in \\mathbb{R}$_hidden',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Given $f(x) = x^n$ for some $n \\in \\mathbb{R}$, the derivative is defined as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">$f\'(x) = nx^{n-1}$</div>\nwhere the case at $n = 0$, a constant function, is the exception to the rule. This occurs because it is known that the derivative of a constant function is always going to be zero, but according to the power rule it would introduce an unnecessary singularity at $x = 0$.','First assume that the power rule holds true $\\forall n \\in \\mathbb{N}$. For the base case consider $n = 1$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">$f(x) = x \\implies f\'(x) = 1$</div>\nwhich is a known fact since the rate of change of a linear function is always equal to constant slope. Now for the inductive step, lets prove that for $n+1$ we have $f\'(x) = (n+1)x^n$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) &= x^{n+1} \\\\\n		f(x) &= x^n \\cdot x \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} f(x) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( x^n \\cdot x \\Big) \\\\\n		f\'(x) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( x^n \\Big) \\cdot x + x^n \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( x \\Big) \\\\\n		f\'(x) &= nx^{n-1} \\cdot x + x^n \\cdot 1 \\\\\n		f\'(x) &= nx^n + x^n \\\\\n		f\'(x) &= (n+1)x^n\n	}$\n</div>\n$\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$','A more rigorous approach is to exploit the Binomial Theorem which states that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">$\\eqalign{(1 + x)^n = \\sum_{i=0}^n {n \\choose i} x^i}$</div>\nwhere $n \\in \\mathbb{N}$ and\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		{n \\choose i} = \\frac{n!}{i!(n - i)!}\n	}$\n</div>\nis known as the binomial coefficient. Now approach finding the derivative through the normal limit definition:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&f\'(x) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{(x+h)^n - x^n}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{1}{h} \\Big( \\Big(h \\Big( 1 + \\frac{x}{h} \\Big) \\Big)^n - x^n \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{1}{h} \\Big( h^n \\Big( 1 + \\frac{x}{h} \\Big)^n - x^n \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{1}{h} \\Big( h^n \\sum_{i=0}^n {n \\choose i} \\Big( \\frac{x}{h} \\Big)^i - x^n \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{1}{h} \\Big( \\sum_{i=0}^n {n \\choose i} x^i h^{n-i} - x^n \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{1}{h} \\Big( \\sum_{i=0}^{n-1} {n \\choose i} x^i h^{n-i} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\sum_{i=0}^{n-1} {n \\choose i} x^i h^{n-i-1} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\Big( {n \\choose 0} h^{n-1} + \\dots + {n \\choose n-1} x^{n-1} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= {n \\choose n-1} x^{n-1} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{n!}{(n-1)!(n-(n-1))!} x^{n-1} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{n!}{(n-1)!} x^{n-1} \\\\\n		&= nx^{n-1}\n	}$\n</div>\n$\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$','First assume that the power rule holds true $\\forall n \\in \\mathbb{N}$. Now to prove for some $k \\in \\mathbb{Q}$, let $k = \\frac{p}{q}$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} x^k &= \\frac{d}{dx} x^\\frac{p}{q} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( x^p \\Big)^\\frac{1}{q} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{q} \\Big( x^p \\Big)^{\\frac{1}{q} - 1} \\cdot px^{p-1} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{p}{q} x^{\\frac{p}{q} - p} \\cdot x^{p-1} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{p}{q} x^{\\frac{p}{q} - 1} \\\\\n		&= k x^{k-1}\n	}$\n</div>\n$\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$','Surprisingly the following proof is the easiest of all in my opinion, and yet it covers the most general case:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} x^k &= \\frac{d}{dx} e^{\\ln(x^k)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} e^{k\\ln(x)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{d}{dx} (k\\ln(x)) \\cdot e^{k\\ln(x)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{k}{x} \\cdot x^k \\\\\n		&= kx^{k - 1}\n	}$\n</div>\nOf course this assumes that we know the chain rule and the derivative of the exponential function. $\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(102,'Product_Rule',4,24,'Definition','Proof by Formal Definition_hidden','Proof by Logarithmic Differentiation_hidden',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Given $k(x) = f(x)g(x)$, the derivative is defined as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k\'(x) = f\'(x)g(x) + f(x)g\'(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $f(x)$ and $g(x)$ are differentiable at $x$.','Using the limit definition of the derivative and some simple trickery:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&k\'(x) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{k(x+h) - k(x)}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x+h)g(x+h) - f(x)g(x)}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x+h)g(x+h) - f(x)g(x)}{h} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x)g(x+h) - f(x)g(x+h)}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\Big( \\frac{f(x+h) - f(x)}{h} \\cdot g(x+h) \\Big) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\Big( f(x+h) \\cdot \\frac{g(x+h) - g(x)}{h} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x+h) - f(x)}{h} \\cdot \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} g(x+h) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} f(x+h) \\cdot \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{g(x+h) - g(x)}{h} \\\\\n		&= f\'(x)g(x) + f(x)g\'(x)\n	}$\n</div>\n$\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$','This proof essentially consists of taking the logarithm of both sides, differentiating both sides, and simplifying:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k(x) &= f(x)g(x) \\\\\n		\\ln(k(x)) &= \\ln(f(x)g(x)) \\\\\n		\\ln(k(x)) &= \\ln(f(x)) + \\ln(g(x)) \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\ln(k(x)) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( \\ln(f(x)) + \\ln(g(x)) \\Big) \\\\\n		\\frac{k\'(x)}{k(x)} &= \\frac{f\'(x)}{f(x)} + \\frac{g\'(x)}{g(x)} \\\\\n		k\'(x) &= f(x)g(x) \\Big( \\frac{f\'(x)}{f(x)} + \\frac{g\'(x)}{g(x)} \\Big) \\\\\n		k\'(x) &= f\'(x)g(x) + f(x)g\'(x)\n	}$\n</div>\n$\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(103,'Quotient_Rule',5,24,'Definition','Proof by Formal Definition_hidden','Proof by Product Rule_hidden','Proof by Logarithmic Differentiation_hidden',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Given $k(x) = \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}$ with the condition that $g(x) \\neq 0$, the derivative is defined as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k\'(x) = \\frac{f\'(x)g(x) - f(x)g\'(x)}{(g(x))^2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $f(x)$ and $g(x)$ are differentiable at $x$.','Using the limit definition of the derivative and some simple trickery:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&k\'(x) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{k(x + h) - k(x)}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{\\frac{f(x + h)}{g(x + h)} - \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)}}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{1}{h} \\cdot \\frac{f(x + h)g(x) - f(x)g(x + h)}{g(x + h)g(x)} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{1}{h} \\cdot \\frac{f(x + h)g(x) - f(x)g(x + h)}{g(x + h)g(x)} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{1}{h} \\cdot \\frac{f(x)g(x) - f(x)g(x)}{g(x + h)g(x)} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x + h)g(x) - f(x)g(x)}{hg(x + h)g(x)} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x)g(x + h) - f(x)g(x)}{hg(x + h)g(x)} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{1}{g(x + h)} \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x + h) - f(x)}{h} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x + h)g(x)} \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{g(x + h) - g(x)}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{1}{g(x)} \\cdot f\'(x) - \\frac{f(x)}{(g(x))^2} \\cdot g\'(x) \\\\\n		&= \\frac{f\'(x)g(x) - f(x)g\'(x)}{(g(x))^2}\n	}$\n</div>\n$\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$','By cross multiplying, differentiating using the product rule, and simplifying we arrive at the quotient rule:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k(x) &= \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} \\\\\n		g(x)k(x) &= f(x) \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( g(x)k(x) \\Big) &= \\frac{d}{dx} f(x) \\\\\n		g(x)k\'(x) &= f\'(x) - g\'(x) \\cdot \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} \\\\\n		k\'(x) &= \\frac{f\'(x)}{g(x)} - \\frac{f(x)g\'(x)}{(g(x))^2} \\\\\n		k\'(x) &= \\frac{f\'(x)g(x) - f(x)g\'(x)}{(g(x))^2}\n	}$\n</div>\n$\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$','This proof essentially consists of taking the logarithm of both sides, differentiating both sides, and simplifying:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) &= \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} \\\\\n		\\ln(h(x)) &= \\ln \\Big( \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} \\Big) \\\\\n		\\ln(h(x)) &= \\ln(f(x)) - \\ln(g(x)) \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\ln(h(x)) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\Big( \\ln(f(x)) - \\ln(g(x)) \\Big) \\\\\n		\\frac{h\'(x)}{h(x)} &= \\frac{f\'(x)}{f(x)} - \\frac{g\'(x)}{g(x)} \\\\\n		h\'(x) &= \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} \\Big( \\frac{f\'(x)}{f(x)} - \\frac{g\'(x)}{g(x)} \\Big) \\\\\n		h\'(x) &= \\frac{f\'(x)}{g(x)} - \\frac{f(x)g\'(x)}{(g(x))^2} \\\\\n		h\'(x) &= \\frac{f\'(x)g(x) - f(x)g\'(x)}{(g(x))^2}\n	}$\n</div>\n$\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(104,'Chain_Rule',6,24,'Definition','Proof by Formal Definition_hidden','Determining the Derivative of the Inverse',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Given $k(x) = g(f(x))$, the derivative is defined as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k\'(x) = g\'(f(x)) \\cdot f\'(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $f(x)$ and $g(x)$ must be differentiable at $x$ and $f(x)$ respectively.','Using the limit definition of the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&k\'(x) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{k(x + h) - k(x)}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{g(f(x + h)) - g(h(x))}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\Bigg[ \\frac{g(f(x + h)) - g(f(x))}{h} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} \\cdot \\frac{f(x + h) - f(x)}{f(x + h) - f(x)} \\Bigg] \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\Bigg[ \\frac{g(f(x + h)) - g(f(x))}{h(x + h) - h(x)} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} \\cdot \\frac{f(x + h) - f(x)}{h} \\Bigg] \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\Bigg[ \\frac{g(f(x + h)) - g(f(x))}{f(x + h) - f(x)} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} \\cdot \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x + h) - f(x)}{h} \\Bigg]\n	}$\n</div>\nNow the trick is to let $\\Delta = h(x+h) - h(x)$ and note that as $h \\rightarrow 0$ we have $\\Delta \\rightarrow 0$ so that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&k\'(x) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{\\Delta \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{g(f(x) + \\Delta) - g(f(x))}{\\Delta} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} \\cdot \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x + h) - f(x)}{h} \\\\\n		&= g\'(f(x)) \\cdot f\'(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nNow to be a little formal we should consider the fact that during the evaluation an extra factor was brought into the denominator. Usually this does not present a problem unless that factor is zero. So what happens if $\\Delta = 0$? To figure this out go back to the beginning of the proof:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k\'(x) &= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{k(x+h) - k(x)}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{g(f(x + h)) - g(f(x))}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{g(f(x + \\Delta)) - g(f(x))}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{g(f(x)) - g(f(x))}{h} \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nSo in the end if that extra factor happens to be zero, then the derivative is equivalently zero. $\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$','A rather useful consequence of the chain rule is the following relationship:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		(f^{-1})\'(x) = \\frac{1}{f\'(f^{-1}(x))}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich provides a method of determining the derivative of the inverse function. Deriving this takes one step when starting from the fundamental relationship between a continuous function and its inverse:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(f^{-1}(x)) &= x \\\\\n		\\frac{d}{dx} f(f^{-1}(x)) &= \\frac{d}{dx} x \\\\\n		f\'(f^{-1}(x)) \\cdot (f^{-1})\'(x) &= 1 \\\\\n		(f^{-1})\'(x) &= \\frac{1}{f\'(f^{-1}(x))}\n	}$\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(105,'Introduction',1,24,'Definition','Consequence of Differentiability',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Given some arbitrary function, $f(x)$, consider the following setup:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/The_Derivative/Introduction/Secant.png\">\n</div>\nwhere the line that passes through the two points is known as the $\\textit{secant}$ line. Formally we would write down the average rate of change, the slope of the secant line, as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{f(x_1) - f(x_0)}{x_1 - x_0}\n	}$\n</div>\nIdeally say that we want to find the $\\textit{instantaneous}$ rate of change at $x = x_0$, how would this be attained given the current setup? With an understanding of limits, we can develop a systematic way of approaching a point infinitesimally close. To do this just let $x_1 \\rightarrow x_0$, giving:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{df}{dx} \\Big|_{x = x_0} = f\'(x_0) = \\lim_{x_1 \\rightarrow x_0} \\frac{f(x_1) - f(x_0)}{x_1 - x_0}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the above is known as the derivative of $f(x)$ evaluated at $x = x_0$. Formally we state a function is $\\textit{differentiable}$ at $x = x_0$ iff $f\'(x_0)$ exists. The above can also be rewritten if the following substitutions are used:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h &= x_1 - x_0 \\\\\n		x_1 \\rightarrow x_0 &\\implies h \\rightarrow 0\n	}$\n</div>\ngiving:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{df}{dx} \\Big|_{x = x_0} = f\'(x_0) = \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x_0 + h) - f(x_0)}{h}\n	}$\n</div>\nEither definition is valid and can be generalized to determining the derivative function as whole and not just at a point. Formally:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{df}{dx} = f\'(x) = \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x + h) - f(x)}{h}\n	}$\n</div>\nthe above is known as the derivative function and determines the instantaneous rate of change of the original function at any $x$. ','I say consequence, but do not mean it in a bad way. Actually if a function is differentiable at a point, then it is also continuous at that point. Extending this we say that if a function is differentiable on some interval, then it is also continuous on that interval.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(106,'Implicit_Differentiation',7,24,'Explicit Function','Implicit Function','Implicit Differentiation','Proof of Implicit Differentiation_hidden',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Any function that can be written as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y = f(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nis known as an $\\textit{explicit}$ function.','Any function that cannot be written in explicit form, but rather as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		F(x,y) = C \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} C \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nis known as an $\\textit{implicit}$ function.','Even though $y$ cannot be written as a function of $x$ when dealing with an implicit function, the derivative of $y$ with respect to $x$ can still be determined. The general approach is to take the derivative of both sides. Consider $y$ to be a second variable and apply all of the standard differentiation rules. The only difference that comes up is when $y$ is differentiated, a $y\'$ always has to be attached. At the end we solve for $y\'$ by isolating it. As an example take the unit circle:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x^2 + y^2 = 1\n	}$\n</div>\nand differentiate both sides to arrive at:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		2x + 2yy\' = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nNow solving for $y\'$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		y\' = -\\frac{x}{y}\n	}$\n</div>','To understand why the derivative of $y$ with respect to $x$ can be determined when dealing with an implicit function, I must first show you the chain rule for a multivariable function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dt} F(x(t), y(t)) = \\frac{\\partial F}{\\partial x} \\frac{dx}{dt} + \\frac{\\partial F}{\\partial y} \\frac{dy}{dt} \n	}$\n</div>\nSo applying this to our situation we arrive at:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} F(x(x), y(x)) &= \\frac{d}{dx} C \\\\\n		\\frac{\\partial F}{\\partial x} \\frac{dx}{dx} + \\frac{\\partial F}{\\partial y} \\frac{dy}{dx} &= 0 \\\\\n		\\frac{\\partial F}{\\partial x} + \\frac{\\partial F}{\\partial y} \\frac{dy}{dx} &= 0 \\\\\n		\\frac{\\partial F}{\\partial y} \\frac{dy}{dx} &= -\\frac{\\partial F}{\\partial x} \\\\\n		\\frac{dy}{dx} &= -\\frac{\\frac{\\partial F}{\\partial x}}{\\frac{\\partial F}{\\partial y}} \\\\\n	}$\n</div>\na consistent formula to determine the derivative of $y$ with respect to $x$ so long as the denominator is not equal to zero, which happens only if there are no $y$\'s present. $\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(107,'Logarithmic_Differentiation',8,24,'General Approach',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Logarithmic differentiation is not really a topic on its own, but is definitely worth a quick look. In certain scenarios taking the logarithm before differentiating might make the latter easier. Specifically consider the following fact:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} \\ln(f(x)) = \\frac{f\'(x)}{f(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich leads to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= f(x) \\cdot \\frac{d}{dx} \\ln(f(x))\n	}$\n</div>\nSo essentially in the case where taking the derivative of the logarithm is easier, this method should be used.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(108,'Introduction',1,25,'Definition','Graphical Approach','Numerical Approach','Analytical Approach','Indeterminate Forms',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'The $\\textit{limit}$ of a function, $f(x)$, as $x \\rightarrow a$ is written as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) = L\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $L$ is some real number. A limit in essense is the process of determining what value $f(x)$ approaches as we look near $a$. Note that during this process we have to consider that the image at hand is a one dimensional line for $x$ and so there are two directions in which we can approach $a$, left and right. As a consequence we say that a limit will only exist if it is the same value being approached from both sides.','One of the standard approaches to evaluating limits is a graphical one. Take for example the following graph of a piecewise function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Limits/Introduction/Example_Function.gif\">\n</div>\nLets say that we want to determine what the limit of the function is as $x \\rightarrow 1$. To do this look at the graph and observe that as $x$ approaches $1$ from both the left side and right side, the function approaches $1$. So formally:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 1} f(x) = 1\n	}$\n</div>\nNotice that even though the limit says the function approaches $1$, in reality $f(1) = 2$. So in general the function evaluated at a point and the limit at the point do not have to equate. As another example consider the scenario where $x \\rightarrow 2$, what is the limit of the function now? As we approach from the left side we get a value of $2$, but from the right side we get $3$. So formally:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 2} f(x) = \\text{DNE}\n	}$\n</div>\nsince the two sides do not approach the same value. ','Another standard method to evaluate limits is to use a numerical approach. Essentially the goal is to check the pattern of the function near the point of interest by directly calculating the function. For example consider the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\frac{x^2 - 1}{x + 1}\n	}$\n</div>\nYou should be able to note that the function has a vertical asymptote at $x = -1$, but what is the limit as $x \\rightarrow -1$? To do this numerically, just create a table of values and observe the patten from both sides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{x}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{f(x)}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-1.100$</td>\n		    <td>$-2.100$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-1.010$</td>\n		    <td>$-2.010$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-1.001$</td>\n		    <td>$-2.001$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-0.999$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.999$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-0.990$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.990$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-0.900$</td>\n		    <td>$-1.900$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nHopefully you notice from the table that as $x \\rightarrow -1$, the function approaches $-2$. So formally:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow -1} f(x) = -2\n	}$\n</div>','Besides the graphical approach which involves just looking at a graph to determine the limit and the numerical approach which is nothing more than a brute force method to determine the limit, there also exists the analytical approach to evaluating a limit. This approach involves nothing more than using some mathematical intuition to evaluate the limit. For example consider the same function as before:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = \\frac{x^2 - 1}{x + 1}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich officially has a vertical asymptote at $x = -1$. To evaluate the limit directly:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow -1} f(x) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -1} \\frac{x^2 - 1}{x + 1} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -1} \\frac{(x - 1)(x + 1)}{x + 1} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -1} (x - 1) \\\\\n		&= -2\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich happens to work since the vertical asymptote is a removable singularity. Yet, this brings up an interesting point when evaluating the second to last line. Why is it that I am allowed to just plug in the value of $x = -1$ to evaluate the limit? It so happens that in general if we have a known continuous function, $g(x)$, we are allowed to say that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x) = g(a)\n	}$\n</div>\nBesides the removable singularity, another common trick involves using the conjugate. For example consider the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k(x) = \\frac{x - 1}{\\sqrt{x} - 1}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the limit as $x \\rightarrow 1$ is:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow 1} k(x) &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 1} \\frac{x - 1}{\\sqrt{x} - 1} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 1} \\frac{x - 1}{\\sqrt{x} - 1} \\cdot \\frac{\\sqrt{x} + 1}{\\sqrt{x} + 1} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 1} \\frac{(x - 1)(\\sqrt{x} + 1)}{x - 1} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow 1} (\\sqrt{x} + 1) \\\\\n		&= 2\n	}$\n</div>','When dealing with limits, something that you may typically run across are $\\textit{indeterminate forms}$, which are expressions that do not hold any numerical expression since they approach different values under certain conditions. In the context of literature, some common examples of indetermine forms include, but are not limited to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{0}{0}, \\frac{\\infty}{\\infty}, 0 \\times \\infty, \\infty - \\infty, 0^0, 1^\\infty, \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.1cm} \\infty^0\n	}$\n</div>\nIf a limit does take on one of these values, it does not guarantee that the limit does not exist, but rather it implies that more work will have to be performed to figure out the limit. ',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(109,'OneANDSided_Limits',2,25,'Definition','Existence of a Limit','Vertical Asymptotes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'In the previous section I discussed the idea of a limit and mentioned that it only exists if the function approaches the same value from the left and right sides. Now to be more formal, I provide for you a representation of the left-limit as $x \\rightarrow a$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^-} f(x) = L_1\n	}$\n</div>\nand right-limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^+} f(x) = L_2\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $L_1$ and $L_2$ are some real numbers that do not necessarily have to be the same. To determine the above limits, we only have to observe one side of the function now rather than making sure both sides equate.','With the above notation for one-sided limits, we can now state that a limit of a function, $f(x)$, as $x \\rightarrow a$ will exist iff:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^-} f(x) = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^+} f(x)\n	}$\n</div>','If any one of the following occurs as $x \\rightarrow a$ for a function $f(x)$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^-} f(x) &= -\\infty \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^-} f(x) &= \\infty \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^+} f(x) &= -\\infty \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^+} f(x) &= \\infty\n	}$\n</div>\nthen the funciton has a $\\textit{vertical asymptote}$ at $x = a$.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(110,'Limit_Properties',3,25,'Introduction','Linearity','Multiplication','Division','Constant','Power Function','Power',NULL,NULL,NULL,'Having seen limits and how they are determined, you should now wonder if there exist properties that could simplify calculations for us. Fortunately, there are and below you will a list of the properties exhibited by all limits.','Limits are linear operators, thus:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (\\alpha f(x) + \\beta g(x)) &= \\alpha \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) + \\beta \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x) \\\\\n		\\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} &\\alpha, \\beta \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\niff the limit of each function exists.','Limits involving multiplication can be split:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (f(x) \\cdot g(x)) = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\cdot \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x)\n	}$\n</div>\niff the limit of each function exists.','Limits involving division can be split\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} &= \\Big[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\Big] \\Big[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x) \\Big]^{-1} \\\\\n		\\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} g(x) &\\neq 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x) \\neq 0\n	}$\n</div>\niff the limit of each function exists.','All limits involving just a constant do nothing:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} c = c \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} c \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>','All limits involving a power function are evaluated as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} x^n = a^n \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} n \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>','All limits involving a function raised to a power are evaluated as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} (f(x))^n = \\Big[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\Big]^n \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} n \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL),(111,'Limits_with_Infinity',4,25,'Limits at Infinity','Horizontal Asymptotes',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'To analyze a function\'s end behavior, we look at the two limits all the way on the left and right:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} f(x) &= L_1 \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} f(x) &= L_2\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $L_1$ and $L_2$ are some real numbers, generally not the same.','Determining the $\\textit{horizontal asymptotes}$ for a given rational function is exactly the same as computing the limit at infinity. In general given the rational function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x) = \\frac{a_0 + a_1x + a_2x^2 + \\dots + a_nx^n}{b_0 + b_1x + b_2x^2 + \\dots + b_mx^m}\n	}$\n</div>\nthere exist a couple of different scenarios:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{Situation}$</td>\n		<td>$\\eqalign{\\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} g(x)}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\eqalign{\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} g(x)}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$n > m$: One odd, the other even</td>\n		    <td>$-\\infty$</td>\n		    <td>$\\infty$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$n > m$: Both odd, or even</td>\n		    <td>$\\infty$</td>\n		    <td>$\\infty$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$n = m$</td>\n		    <td>$\\frac{a_n}{b_m}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\frac{a_n}{b_m}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$n < m$</td>\n		    <td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>$0$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(112,'Continuity',5,25,'Introduction','Continuity at a Point','Continuity on an Interval','Continuous Functions','Limit of Composition of Functions','Squeeze Theorem','Bolzano\'s Theorem','Proof of Bolzano\'s Theorem_hidden','Intermediate Value Theorem','Proof of Intermediate Value Theorem_hidden','Now we finally introduce continuity and unravel the \"nice\" behavior that is seen across all continuous functions.','A function, $f(x)$, is said to be $\\textit{continuous at a point}$, $x = a$, if:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} &f(x) \\hspace{.2cm} \\text{exists}, \\hspace{.1cm} f(a) \\hspace{.2cm} \\text{is defined,} \\\\\n		&\\text{and} \\hspace{.2cm} f(a) = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x)\n	}$\n</div>','A function, $f(x)$, is said to be $\\textit{continuous}$ on an interval, $S \\subseteq \\mathbb{R}$, if it is continuous at every point in $S$.','Given two continuous functions, $f(x)$ and $g(x)$, the following are also continuous:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\text{Scalar Multiple:}& \\hspace{.3cm} \\alpha f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} \\alpha \\in \\mathbb{R} \\\\\n		\\text{Sum:}& \\hspace{.3cm} f(x) + g(x) \\\\\n		\\text{Product:}& \\hspace{.3cm} f(x)g(x) \\\\\n		\\text{Quotient:}& \\hspace{.3cm} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} g(x) \\neq 0\n	}$\n</div>','Given that a function, $f(x)$, is continuous at $x = L$ where:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x) = L\n	}$\n</div>\nthen:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(g(x)) = f\\Big( \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x) \\Big)\n	}$\n</div>','Limits are known to preserve inequalities, so given two functions s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) \\leq g(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nthen:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) \\leq \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nUsing this information consider a scenario where we have three functions s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) \\leq f(x) \\leq g(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nand it is known that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} h(x) = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} g(x) = L\n	}$\n</div>\nthen:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) = L\n	}$\n</div>','Given a continuous function on the closed interval $[a,b]$ where $f(a)$ and $f(b)$ have opposite signs, then:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.2cm} c \\in (a,b) \\hspace{.5cm} \\text{s.t.} f(c) = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nIn other words Bolzano\'s Theorem guarantees that a continuous function attains a zero on the interval so long as the function evaluation at the endpoints produces opposite signs.','While the theorem is very straight forward, the proof requires a bit more insight. First lets assume that we have a continuous function on the compact interval $[a,b]$ s.t. $f(a) < 0$ and $f(b) > 0$. Now define a new point:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		a_1 = \\frac{a + b}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nto be the average of the two endpoints where three cases can occur:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(a_1) = 0 \\implies &\\text{the theorem is proved} \\\\\n		f(a_1) > 0 \\implies &\\text{define a new interval} \\\\\n		& I_1 = (a, a_1) \\\\\n		f(a_1) < 0 \\implies &\\text{define a new interval} \\\\\n		& I_1 = (a_1, b) \\\\\n	}$\n</div>\nIgnoring the trivial case we now have the original interval $I_0 = (a,b)$ and $I_1 \\subset I_0$ where the length of the new interval is $|I_1| = \\frac{|I_0|}{2}$. Repeating the above procedure will define a succession of open intervals $I_n = (a_n, b_n)$ s.t. $I_{n + 1} \\subset I_n$, $|I_n| = 2^{-n} |I_0|$, and $f(a_n) < 0 < f(b_n)$. The succession $c_n = a_n$ and $c_{n + 1} = b_n$ is Cauchy by construction since:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\forall m > n \\hspace{.5cm} |c_m - c_n| < 2^{-\\frac{n}{2}} |I_0|\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich implies that $c_n$ is convergent, $c_n \\rightarrow c \\in (a,b)$. Since $a_n$ and $b_n$ are sub-successions they also tend to the same limit. So by construction:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(a_n) &< 0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} f(a_n) &< 0 \\\\\n		f\\Big( \\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} a_n \\Big) &\\leq 0 \\\\\n		f(c) &\\leq 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(b_n) &> 0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} f(b_n) &> 0 \\\\\n		f\\Big( \\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} b_n \\Big) &\\geq 0 \\\\\n		f(c) &\\geq 0\n	}$\n</div>\nWith both of the restrictions in mind we must have it s.t. $f(c) = 0$. To finish up we state that $c \\in (a,b)$ because $f(a) < 0$ and $f(b) > 0$. Of course it is the same process for proving the case where $f(a) > 0$ and $f(b) < 0$ if you consider the scenario for $-f(x)$.','Given a continuous function on the closed interval $[a,b]$, according to the $\\textit{Intermediate Value Theorem}$ the function is guaranteed to attain the range:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\mathcal{R}(f) = \\Big[ \\min\\{f(a),f(b)\\}, \\max\\{f(a),f(b)\\} \\Big]\n	}$\n</div>\nIn other words:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\forall \\alpha \\in \\mathcal{R}(f) \\hspace{.1cm} \\exists \\hspace{.1cm} c \\in [a,b] \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\hspace{.3cm} f(c) = \\alpha\n	}$\n</div>','Begin by assuming we have a continuous function, $f(x)$, on the compact interval $[a,b]$ and want to know whether a $c \\in (a,b)$ exists s.t. $f(c) = L$ where $L$ is a real number between $f(a)$ and $f(b)$. Define a new function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x) = f(x) - L\n	}$\n</div>\nand now we know that $g(a)$ and $g(b)$ will have opposite signs. Therefore, by Bolzano\'s Theorem there will exist a $c \\in (a,b)$ s.t. $g(c) = 0$ which implies:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(c) = L\n	}$\n</div>\nSince $L$ is any arbitrary number in between $f(a)$ and $f(b)$, we know that the function must attain every value in between including the boundaries.'),(113,'Bisection_Method',6,25,'Introduction','Algorithm','Convergence_hidden',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Having Bolzano\'s Theorem in your arsenal actually provides the foundation necessary for a fundamental root-finding algorithm. Known as the $\\textit{Bisection Method}$, the process provides a systematic approach to determine the root of a function given that the function evaluation at the endpoints is of opposite signs.','Given a continuous function on the closed interval $[a,b]$ where $f(a)$ and $f(b)$ have opposite signs, then $\\exists c \\in (a,b)$ s.t. $f(c) = 0$ according to Bolzano\'s Theorem. To determine the value of $c$ follow the steps:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		1. &\\text{Calculate the midpoint of the interval:} \\hspace{.2cm} c = \\frac{a + b}{2} \\\\\n		2. &\\text{Evaluate} \\hspace{.2cm} f(c) \\\\\n		3. &\\text{If the evaluation is close enough to zero} \\\\\n		&\\text{return the value of} \\hspace{.2cm} c \\\\\n		4. &\\text{If the evaluation is not close enough then begin by} \\\\\n		&\\text{checking the sign of} \\hspace{.2cm} f(c). \\hspace{.2cm} \\text{If} \\hspace{.2cm} f(a) \\hspace{.2cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.2cm} f(c) \\\\\n		&\\text{have the same sign then:} \\hspace{.2cm} b = c, \\hspace{.2cm} \\text{otherwise} \\hspace{.2cm} a = c \\\\\n		&\\text{and you repeat the steps starting from number one.}\n	}$\n</div>\nAt the end of the day the Bisection Method is nothing more than a process of determining the root by guessing the middle value of subintervals.','While the algorithm is very straight forward, the proof requires a bit more insight. First assume that we have a continuous function on the compact interval $[a,b]$ s.t. $f(a) < 0$ and $f(b) > 0$. Now define the middle point:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		a_1 = \\frac{a + b}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the evaluation can result in three cases:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(a_1) = 0 \\implies &\\text{the value is found} \\\\\n		f(a_1) > 0 \\implies &\\text{define a new interval} \\\\\n		& I_1 = (a, a_1) \\\\\n		f(a_1) < 0 \\implies &\\text{define a new interval} \\\\\n		& I_1 = (a_1, b) \\\\\n	}$\n</div>\nIgnoring the trivial case we now have the original interval $I_0 = (a,b)$ and $I_1 \\subset I_0$ where the length of the new interval is $|I_1| = \\frac{|I_0|}{2}$. Repeating the above procedure will define a succession of open intervals $I_n = (a_n, b_n)$ s.t. $I_{n + 1} \\subset I_n$, and $|I_n| = 2^{-n} |I_0|$. Using the restriction:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|I_n| &= 2^{-n} |I_0| \\\\\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} |I_n| &= \\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} 2^{-n} |I_0| \\\\\n		\\lim_{n \\rightarrow \\infty} |I_n| &= 0\n	}$\n</div>\nstates that the interval eventually becomes just a single point, specifically the point we are looking for. By Bolzano\'s Theorem we also know that this point will always exist.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(114,'Common_Derivatives_and_Properties',2,24,'Derivative Properties','Common Derivatives',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'$\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\sech}{sech}\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\csch}{csch}\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\arcsec}{arcsec}\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\arccot}{arccot}\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\arccsc}{arccsc}\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\arccosh}{arccosh}\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\arcsinh}{arcsinh}\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\arctanh}{arctanh}\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\arcsech}{arcsech}\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\arccsch}{arccsch}\n	\\DeclareMathOperator{\\arccoth}{arccoth}\n$\n\nSince the derivative is defined through a limit, it is also a linear operator satisfying:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{d}{dx} (\\alpha f(x) + \\beta g(x)) = \\alpha\\frac{d}{dx} f(x) + \\beta\\frac{d}{dx} g(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nfor some constants $\\alpha$ and $\\beta$ which can be seen by direct evaluation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\frac{d}{dx} (\\alpha f(x) + \\beta g(x)) \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{1}{h} \\Bigg[ (\\alpha f(x + h) + \\beta g(x + h)) - (\\alpha f(x) + \\beta g(x)) \\Bigg] \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{1}{h} \\Bigg[ \\alpha(f(x + h) - f(x)) + \\beta(g(x + h) - g(x)) \\Bigg] \\\\\n		&= \\alpha \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x + h) - f(x)}{h} + \\beta \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{g(x + h) - g(x)}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\alpha\\frac{d}{dx} f(x) + \\beta\\frac{d}{dx} g(x)\n	}$\n</div>','In the following sections I will introduce you to rules that apply to handling all common cases of differentiation, but before doing that you must first know the fundamental derivatives. I will not go into proving how these are attained here, but perhaps in later examples you will see how the derivative is determined in some specific cases. So for now just accept the following:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{f(x)}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\frac{d}{dx} \\textbf{f(x)}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$c$ where $c \\in \\mathbb{R}$</td>\n		    <td>$0$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$x^n$ where $n \\in \\mathbb{R} \\setminus \\{0\\}$</td>\n		    <td>$nx^{n - 1}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$e^x$</td>\n		    <td>$e^x$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$a^x$ where $a \\in \\mathbb{R}_{> 0}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\ln(a)a^x$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\ln(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\frac{1}{x}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\log_{a}(x)$ where $a \\in \\mathbb{R}_{> 0}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\frac{1}{\\ln(a)x}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\sin(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\cos(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\cos(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$-\\sin(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\tan(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\sec^2(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\csc(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$-\\csc(x)\\cot(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\sec(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\sec(x)\\tan(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\cot(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$-\\csc^2(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\arcsin(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1 - x^2}}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\arccos(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$-\\frac{1}{\\sqrt{1 - x^2}}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\arctan(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\frac{1}{1 + x^2}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\arccsc(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$-\\frac{1}{|x|\\sqrt{x^2 - 1}}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\arcsec(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\frac{1}{|x|\\sqrt{x^2 - 1}}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\arccot(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$-\\frac{1}{1 + x^2}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\sinh(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\cosh(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\cosh(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\sinh(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\tanh(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\sech^2(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\csch(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$-\\csch(x)\\coth(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\sech(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$-\\sech(x)\\tanh(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$\\coth(x)$</td>\n		    <td>$-\\csch^2(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(115,'Implications_of_the_First_Derivative',3,26,'Critical Points','A Function\'s Behavior Due to the First Derivative','Relative Extremas',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'A $\\textit{critical point}$ of a function is any value that satisfies:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{or} \\hspace{.3cm} f\'(x) = \\text{DNE}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere there are no restrictions on the amount of critical points that a function may attain.','From the definition of the derivative:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) = \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(x + h) - f(x)}{h}\n	}$\n</div>\nobserve what happens under different conditions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{f\'(x)}$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{h}$</td>\n		    <td>Implication</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$+$</td>\n		    <td>$+$</td>\n		    <td>$f(x + h) > f(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$+$</td>\n		    <td>$-$</td>\n		    <td>$f(x + h) < f(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$-$</td>\n		    <td>$+$</td>\n		    <td>$f(x + h) < f(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$-$</td>\n		    <td>$-$</td>\n		    <td>$f(x + h) > f(x)$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nSo in essense if we are given a derivative that is positive the original function is increasing, and decreasing for negative behavior. To finish off we still have to consider the case where the derivative is exactly zero. So assuming that the derivative is zero on an interval, $I$, and we have a differentiable function, then by the Mean Value Theorem:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.1cm} c \\in &[x_1,x_2] \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\hspace{.3cm} f(x_2) - f(x_1) = f\'(c)(x_2 - x_1) \\\\\n		& \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} [x_1,x_2] \\subseteq I\n	}$\n</div>\nSince the derivative is zero on the interval:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x_2) = f(x_1)\n	}$\n</div>\nand since $x_1$ and $x_2$ are two arbitrary points in the interval, this holds true for all values in the interval.','According to Fermat\'s Theorem, if we want to identify extremas we have to look at the critical points. Not all critical points will produce an extrema, but under certain conditions they do. Specifically the following situations can arise when observing the left and right behaviors of the derivative relative to the critical point:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$\\textbf{f\'(x)}$ to the Left</td>\n		<td>$\\textbf{f\'(x)}$ to the Right</td>\n		    <td>Type of Extrema</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$+$</td>\n		<td>$+$</td>\n		    <td>None</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$+$</td>\n		<td>$-$</td>\n		    <td>Maximum</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$-$</td>\n		<td>$+$</td>\n		    <td>Minimum</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$-$</td>\n		<td>$-$</td>\n		    <td>None</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nIn other words, a local maximum or minimum will occur iff there is a switch in sign for the derivative. This system of identifying the type of extrema is known as the $\\textit{First Derivative Test}$.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(116,'Implications_of_the_Second_Derivative',4,26,'Inflection Points','A Function\'s Behavior Due to the Second Derivative','Proof of Concavity Behavior_hidden','The Second Derivative Test','Proof of the Second Derivative Test_hidden',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'An $\\textit{inflection point}$ of a function is any value that satisfies:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'\'(x) = 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{or} \\hspace{.3cm} f\'\'(x) = \\text{DNE}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere there are no restrictions on the amount of inflection points that a function may attain.','Any function that satisfies the condition\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) > f(a) &+ f\'(a)(x - a) \\hspace{.3cm} \\forall x \\in I \\\\\n		&\\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} a \\in I \\subseteq \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nis a $\\textit{strictly concave upwards}$ function. In other terms a continuously differentiable function is $\\textit{convex}$ iff the function lies above all of its tangents. The behavior is attained exactly when the second derivative is positive, but on the other hand any function with a negative second derivative will satisfy:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) < f(a) &+ f\'(a)(x - a) \\hspace{.3cm} \\forall x \\in I \\\\\n		&\\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} a \\in I \\subseteq \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich is to say that the function is $\\textit{strictly concave downwards}$. In other terms a continuously differentiable function is $\\textit{concave}$ iff the function lies below all of its tangents. Lastly if the second derivative is exactly zero, then the function must be a line since it is exactly the shape with no bending anywhere.','By the Mean Value Theorem we have the setup:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.1cm} c &\\in (a,x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\\\\n		&f(x) - f(a) = f\'(c)(x - a)\n	}$\n</div>\nIf we now assume that the second derivative is positive, then the first derivative must be increasing:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(c) &> f\'(a) \\\\\n		f\'(c)(x - a) &> f\'(a)(x - a) \\\\\n		f(a) + f\'(c)(x - a) &> f(a) + f\'(a)(x - a) \\\\\n		f(x) &> f(a) + f\'(a)(x - a)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the last line states that our function will lie strictly above its tangents. $\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$ Now for the second case we assume that the second derivative is negative, thus the first derivative is decreasing:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(c) &< f\'(a) \\\\\n		f\'(c)(x - a) &< f\'(a)(x - a) \\\\\n		f(a) + f\'(c)(x - a) &< f(a) + f\'(a)(x - a) \\\\\n		f(x) &< f(a) + f\'(a)(x - a)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the last line states that our function will lie strictly below its tangents. $\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$ For the final case where the second derivative is zero, we begin by noting that with the Mean Value Theorem:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.1cm} c &\\in (a,x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\\\\n		&f\'(x) - f\'(a) = f\'\'(c)(x - a)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich provides that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = f(a)\n	}$\n</div>\nsince the second derivative is zero, and holds true for all points in the interval since $a$ and $x$ are arbitrary. Using this setup again:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.1cm} c &\\in (a,x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\\\\n		&f(x) - f(a) = f\'(c)(x - a)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich provides us with:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) - f(a) &= f\'(c)(x - a) \\\\\n		f(x) &= f(a) + f\'(c)(x - a)\n	}$\n</div>\nwith a line because the first derivative is constant for all values in the interval. $\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$','Similar to the first derivative, the second derivative also has a test associated to it that can determine the extrema type for a critical point. Specifically, according to the $\\textit{Second Derivative Test}$ we identify a critical point, $x = c$, as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$f\'\'(c)$</td>\n		    <td>$\\textbf{Type of Extrema}$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$+$</td>\n		    <td>Minimum</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$-$</td>\n		    <td>Maximum</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>$0$</td>\n		    <td>Can be either or neither</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>','By the Mean Value Theorem we have the setup:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.1cm} c &\\in (a,x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\\\\n		&f\'(x) - f\'(a) = f\'\'(c)(x - a)\n	}$\n</div>\nIf the point we center ourselves at $x = a$ is the critical point then we reduce the above down to:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.1cm} c &\\in (a,x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\\\\n		&f\'(x) = f\'\'(c)(x - a)\n	}$\n</div>\nSo now if the second derivative is positive, then we must have the first derivative be positive as we approach from the right side and negative from the left side. With this behavior we can classify this critical point as a minimum due to the First Derivative Test. $\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$ On the other hand if the second derivative is negative the exact opposite behavior occurs giving a maximum due to the First Derivative Test. $\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$ Lastly to see why the second derivative equating to zero is useless information, observe the three following functions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f_1(x) &= x^2 \\\\\n		f_2(x) &= -x^2 \\\\\n		f_3(x) &= x^3\n	}$\n</div>\nAll three have a single critical point at $x = 0$. The first one will produce a minimum, the second a maximum, and the third neither. What makes this setup the most interesting is that all of the second derivatives evaluate to zero at the critical point. It is exactly because of a counterexample like this that we cannot say anything about critical points with zero second derivative. $\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(117,'Absolute_Extremas',6,26,'Setup',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Given:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&f(x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} x \\in [a,b] \\\\\n		&\\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} f\'(x) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{exists on} \\hspace{.3cm} (a,b)\n	}$\n</div>\nwe want to determine the function\'s $\\textit{absolute}$ maximum and minimum on the interval. In essense given a bounded interval we want to determine the values of $x$ s.t. the function is at its greatest and lowest. Due to the Extreme Value Theorem we know that these $x$ values do exist in the given domain, so now we have to construct a methodology to determine the values. To start we know from Fermat\'s Theorem that any extremum is identified by a critical point, but this only applies to the interior. So to take into account the boundary we have to manually check those points, thereby giving the general strategy:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>Step</td>\n		    <td>Instructions</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>1</td>\n		    <td>Determine all of the critical points in the region $(a,b)$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>2</td>\n		    <td>Evaluate the original function at each of the critical points and $x = a, b$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>3</td>\n		    <td>Compare all of the values from Step 2 and identify the biggest one as the absolute maximum and vice versa for the absolute minimum</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nThe benefit of this approach is that we do not have to use either of the derivative tests to identify the critical points since it does not interest us, thus really making this a process of determining all of the necessary values and comparing the evaluations. Also note that in some context the terminology global is used in place of absolute, but I will purely stick to absolute.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(118,'Optimization',7,26,'General Approach',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Optimization references the process of determining absolute maximums or minimums of a function given some constraint. Typically our objective function will take the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x,z) = y\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $x$, $y$, and $z$ are all variables. Occasionally we will want to determine the extremas of $y$ so we have the constraint function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x,z) = L\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $L$ is a constant. For problems of an undergraduate course the constraint function will be able to produce an explicit function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x,z) = L \\rightarrow z = h(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nWith this $z$ can be replaced in the objective function s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x,h(x)) = y\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we recongnize that the original scenario has been reduced into a problem of determining the absolute extremas of the above single variable function. We also have both Derivative Tests at our disposal to determine the type of extrema.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(119,'Linear_Approximation',8,26,'Derivation',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Given a function, $f \\in C^{1}$, we have:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(a) = \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0} \\frac{f(a + h) - f(a)}{h}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow assuming that $h$ is very small we can approximate the derivative as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(a) \\approx \\frac{f(a + h) - f(a)}{h}\n	}$\n</div>\nand with a little reorganization:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(a)h &\\approx f(a + h) - f(a) \\\\\n		f(a + h) &\\approx f(a) + f\'(a)h\n	}$\n</div>\nwe arrive at what is known as the linear approximation for a given function near $a$. By letting $h = x - a$ the above becomes:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) &\\approx f(a) + f\'(a)(x - a)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich is equivalent to the first form.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(120,'LAPOSTROPHEHospitalAPOSTROPHEs_Rule',9,26,'Statement','Proof of $\\frac{0}{0}$_hidden','Proof of $\\frac{0}{0}$ Using Cauchy\'s Mean Value Theorem_hidden','Proof of $\\pm \\frac{\\infty}{\\infty}$_hidden','Proof of Limits at Infinity_hidden',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Given two differentiable functions $f(x)$ and $g(x)$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} f(x) = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} g(x) = 0 \\\\\n		&\\text{or} \\hspace{.3cm} \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} f(x) = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} g(x) = \\pm \\infty \\hspace{.3cm} \\\\\n		&\\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} c \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nthen $\\textit{L\'Hospital\'s Rule}$ states that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{f\'(x)}{g\'(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\nIn essense this provides a systematic approach to determining limits that involve indeterminate forms, but note that if the limit does not approach either $\\frac{0}{0}$ or $\\pm \\frac{\\infty}{\\infty}$, then the rule cannot be used. In some cases the new limit may also approach an indeterminate form which gives reason to use the rule again, except using the second derivatives. In general if you keep getting the indeterminate forms you keep taking derivatives until it approaches something either finite or non-existant.','Given two differentiable functions $k(x)$ and $j(x)$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k(c) = j(c) = 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} j\'(c) \\neq 0\n	}$\n</div>\nthen assuming that $x \\neq c$ we do the following:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&\\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{f(x)}{g(x)} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{f(x) - 0}{g(x) - 0} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{f(x) - f(c)}{g(x) - g(c)} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{\\frac{f(x) - f(c)}{x - c}}{\\frac{g(x) - g(c)}{x - c}} \\\\\n		&= \\Bigg[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{f(x) - f(c)}{x - c} \\Bigg]\\Bigg[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{g(x) - g(c)}{x - c} \\Bigg]^{-1} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{f\'(c)}{g\'(c)} \\\\\n		&= \\Bigg[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} f\'(x) \\Bigg]\\Bigg[ \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} g\'(x) \\Bigg]^{-1} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{f\'(x)}{g\'(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\n$\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$','Given two differentiable functions $k(x)$ and $j(x)$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k(a) = j(a) = 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} j\'(a) \\neq 0\n	}$\n</div>\nthen by Cachy\'s Mean Value Theorem on the interval $[a,b]$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.1cm} c &\\in (a,b) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\\\\n		k\'(c)(j(b) - j(a)) &= j\'(c)(k(b) - k(a))\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we can take any pair of domains $[a,x]$ and $(a,x)$ s.t. both functions are continuous and differentiable on them respectively where $x \\leq b$. Using the Mean Value Theorem and our given situation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k\'(c)j(x) &= j\'(c)k(x) \\\\\n		\\frac{k\'(c)}{j\'(c)} &= \\frac{k(x)}{j(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\nTo finish up we carefully apply limits that will push the variables to the same spot:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\frac{k\'(c)}{j\'(c)} &= \\frac{k(x)}{j(x)} \\\\\n		\\lim_{c \\rightarrow a^+} \\frac{k\'(c)}{j\'(c)} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^+} \\frac{k(x)}{j(x)} \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^+} \\frac{k\'(x)}{j\'(x)} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^+} \\frac{k(x)}{j(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\nSince $a$ was chosen randomly this applies to any real number, and not just from the right side. $\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$','Given two differentiable functions $k(x)$ and $j(x)$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		k, j \\rightarrow \\pm \\infty \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{as} \\hspace{.3cm} x \\rightarrow c\n	}$\n</div>\nNow suppose that we define the limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		L = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{k(x)}{j(x)} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} L \\in \\mathbb{R} \\setminus \\{0\\}\n	}$\n</div>\nIf we accept L\'Hospital\'s Rule for the case of $\\frac{0}{0}$, then we can state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		L &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{k(x)}{j(x)} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{\\frac{1}{j(x)}}{\\frac{1}{k(x)}} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{-\\frac{j\'(x)}{(j(x))^2}}{-\\frac{k\'(x)}{(k(x))^2}} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{(k(x))^2j\'(x)}{(j(x))^2k\'(x)} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\Big( \\frac{k(x)}{j(x)} \\Big)^2 \\cdot \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{j\'(x)}{k\'(x)} \\\\\n		&= L^2 \\cdot \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{j\'(x)}{k\'(x)} \\\\\n		0 &= L\\Big( L \\cdot \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{j\'(x)}{k\'(x)} - 1 \\Big) \\\\\n		L &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{k\'(x)}{j\'(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $L$ cannot be zero at the last line due to our initial assumption. To handle the zero case let us assume:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 = \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{k(x)}{j(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\nObserve how the above can be used with some trickery:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		1 + \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{k(x)}{j(x)} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{j(x) + k(x)}{j(x)} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{j\'(x) + k\'(x)}{j\'(x)} \\\\\n		&= 1 + \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{k\'(x)}{j\'(x)} \\\\\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{k(x)}{j(x)} &= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow c} \\frac{k\'(x)}{j\'(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\n$\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$','Say we have the following scenario:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{k(x)}{j(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we define a new variable:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		t = \\frac{1}{x}\n	}$\n</div>\nso as to rewrite the limit and use L\'Hospital\'s Rule for a case we have already proven:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{k(x)}{j(x)} &= \\lim_{t \\rightarrow 0^+} \\frac{k\\Big( \\frac{1}{t} \\Big)}{j\\Big( \\frac{1}{t} \\Big)} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{t \\rightarrow 0^+} \\frac{-\\frac{k\'\\Big( \\frac{1}{t} \\Big)}{t^2}}{-\\frac{j\'\\Big( \\frac{1}{t} \\Big)}{t^2}} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{t \\rightarrow 0^+} \\frac{k\'\\Big( \\frac{1}{t} \\Big)}{j\'\\Big( \\frac{1}{t} \\Big)} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} \\frac{k\'(x)}{j\'(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\nThe remaining case can be accomplished in a similar fashion:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} \\frac{k(x)}{j(x)} &= \\lim_{t \\rightarrow 0^-} \\frac{k\\Big( \\frac{1}{t} \\Big)}{j\\Big( \\frac{1}{t} \\Big)} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{t \\rightarrow 0^-} \\frac{-\\frac{k\'\\Big( \\frac{1}{t} \\Big)}{t^2}}{-\\frac{j\'\\Big( \\frac{1}{t} \\Big)}{t^2}} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{t \\rightarrow 0^-} \\frac{k\'\\Big( \\frac{1}{t} \\Big)}{j\'\\Big( \\frac{1}{t} \\Big)} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} \\frac{k\'(x)}{j\'(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\n$\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(121,'The_Mean_Value_Theorem',1,26,'Introduction','Fermat\'s Theorem','Proof of Fermat\'s Theorem_hidden','Extreme Value Theorem','Proof of Extreme Value Theorem_hidden','Rolle\'s Theorem','Proof of Rolle\'s Theorem_hidden','Mean Value Theorem','Proof of Mean Value Theorem_hidden',NULL,'In this section I introduce a couple of theorems that pertain deeply to differential calculus starting with Fermat\'s Theorem, the Extreme Value Theorem, Rolle\'s Theorem, and finally the Mean Value Theorem.','A differentiable function has a local extremum at some point if its derivative is exactly zero at that point.','This proof requires showing implication in both directions. So to begin I will first assume that for our function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f: \\hspace{.1cm} (a,b) \\rightarrow \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nwe have:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		c \\in (a,b) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{s.t.} \\hspace{.3cm} f(c) \\geq f(c + h) \\\\\n		&\\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} h \\neq 0\n	}$\n</div>\nUsing the inequality:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(c + h) - f(c) &\\leq 0 \\\\\n		\\frac{f(c + h) - f(c)}{h} &\\leq 0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^+} \\frac{f(c + h) - f(c)}{h} &\\leq \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^+} 0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^+} \\frac{f(c + h) - f(c)}{h} &\\leq 0\n	}$\n</div>\nI assumed that $h$ is positive and determined the restriction for the right-hand limit. Now for the left-hand limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(c + h) - f(c) &\\leq 0 \\\\\n		\\frac{f(c + h) - f(c)}{h} &\\geq 0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^-} \\frac{f(c + h) - f(c)}{h} &\\geq \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^-} 0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^-} \\frac{f(c + h) - f(c)}{h} &\\geq 0\n	}$\n</div>\nNow if the derivative exists at that point we must have:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(c) &= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^-} \\frac{f(c + h) - f(c)}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^+} \\frac{f(c + h) - f(c)}{h} \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>\n$\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$ To tackle the minimum we state that we have:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		d \\in (a,b) \\hspace{.3cm} &\\text{s.t.} \\hspace{.3cm} f(d) \\leq f(d + h) \\\\\n		&\\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} h \\neq 0\n	}$\n</div>\nUsing the inequality:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(d + h) - f(d) &\\geq 0 \\\\\n		\\frac{f(d + h) - f(d)}{h} &\\geq 0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^+} \\frac{f(d + h) - f(d)}{h} &\\geq \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^+} 0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^+} \\frac{f(d + h) - f(d)}{h} &\\geq 0\n	}$\n</div>\nI assumed that $h$ is positive and determined the restriction for the right-hand limit. Now for the left-hand limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(d + h) - f(d) &\\geq 0 \\\\\n		\\frac{f(d + h) - f(d)}{h} &\\leq 0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^-} \\frac{f(d + h) - f(d)}{h} &\\leq \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^-} 0 \\\\\n		\\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^-} \\frac{f(d + h) - f(d)}{h} &\\leq 0\n	}$\n</div>\nNow if the derivative exists at that point we must have:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(d) &= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^-} \\frac{f(d + h) - f(d)}{h} \\\\\n		&= \\lim_{h \\rightarrow 0^+} \\frac{f(d + h) - f(d)}{h} \\\\\n		&= 0\n	}$\n</div>\n$\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$','Given a continuous function, $f(x)$, on the interval $[a,b]$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.1cm} c,d \\in [a,b] \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\hspace{.3cm} f(c) \\leq f(x) \\leq f(d) \\hspace{.3cm} \\forall x \\in [a,b]\n	}$\n</div>','To approach a proof by contradiction we assume there is a least upper bound on the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		M = \\sup_{x \\in [a,b]} f(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nbut no associated value in the domain that attains it:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\nexists \\hspace{.1cm} d \\in [a,b] \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\hspace{.3cm} f(d) = M\n	}$\n</div>\nNext up we form a new function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x) = \\frac{1}{M - f(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich is continuous on our interval since both the numerator and denominator are continuous functions. There is also the restriction that the botton never equates to zero on our interval from what we have assumed. Similar to our original function, we define a least upper bound:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		N = \\sup_{x \\in [a,b]} g(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nand use it:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x) &\\leq N \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{M - f(x)} &\\leq N \\\\\n		1 &\\leq MN - Nf(x) \\\\\n		Nf(x) &\\leq MN - 1 \\\\\n		f(x) &\\leq M - \\frac{1}{N}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the last line provides us with a contradiction since we assumed that $M$ was the least upper bound for our function. Therefore:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.1cm} d \\in [a,b] \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\hspace{.3cm} f(d) = M \\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}\n	}$\n</div>\nTo prove the existance of the minimum, the approach is similar. We begin by defining the greatest lower bound for the function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		P = \\inf_{x \\in [a,b]} f(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nbut no associated value in the domain that attains it:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\nexists \\hspace{.1cm} c \\in [a,b] \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\hspace{.3cm} f(c) = P\n	}$\n</div>\nNext up we form a new function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) = \\frac{1}{f(x) - P}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich is continuous on our interval since both the numerator and denominator are continuous functions. There is also the restriction that the botton never equates to zero on our interval from what we have assumed. Now we define a least upper bound:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		Q = \\sup_{x \\in [a,b]} h(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nand use it:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		h(x) &\\leq Q \\\\\n		\\frac{1}{f(x) - P} &\\leq Q \\\\\n		1 &\\leq Qf(x) - PQ \\\\\n		PQ + 1 &\\leq Qf(x) \\\\\n		P + \\frac{1}{Q} &\\leq f(x)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the last line provides us with a contradiction since we assumed that $P$ was the greatest lower bound for our function. Therefore:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.1cm} c \\in [a,b] \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\hspace{.3cm} f(c) = P \\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}\n	}$\n</div>','Given a function, $f(x)$, that satisfies all of the following:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&1. \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{Continuous on the closed interval} \\hspace{.1cm} [a,b] \\\\\n		&2. \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{Differentiable on the open interval} \\hspace{.1cm} (a,b) \\\\\n		&3. \\hspace{.3cm} f(a) = f(b)\n	}$\n</div>\nthen:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.1cm} c \\in (a,b) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\hspace{.3cm} f\'(c) = 0\n	}$\n</div>','The proof can be split into three separate cases. The first case deals with constant functions, and Rolle\'s Theorem clearly holds true since $c$ can be chosen to be any value on the open interval. The next case deals with assuming:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.1cm} d \\in (a,b) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\hspace{.3cm} f(d) > f(a)\n	}$\n</div>\nBy the Extreme Value Theorem we know there must exist some value in the open interval where a maximum is achieved. Since this value is in the interior the function will actually attain a relative maximum there and by the second condition we know that the derivative exists at that point. By Fermat\'s Theorem we conclude that since this is a relative extrema and the derivative exists at the point, then it is a critical point s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(c) = 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} c \\in (a,b)\n	}$\n</div>\nThe third case deals with assuming:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.1cm} d \\in (a,b) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\hspace{.3cm} f(d) < f(a)\n	}$\n</div>\nBy the Extreme Value Theorem we know there must exist some value in the open interval where a minimum is achieved. Since this value is in the interior the function will actually attain a relative minimum there and by the second condition we know that the derivative exists at that point. By Fermat\'s Theorem we conclude that since this is a relative extrema and the derivative exists at the point, then it is a critical point s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(c) = 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} c \\in (a,b) \\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}\n	}$\n</div>','Given a function, $f(x)$, that satisfies all of the following:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&1. \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{Continuous on the closed interval} \\hspace{.1cm} [a,b] \\\\\n		&2. \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{Differentiable on the open interval} \\hspace{.1cm} (a,b)\n	}$\n</div>\nthen:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.1cm} c \\in (a,b) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\hspace{.3cm} f\'(c)(b - a) = f(b) - f(a)\n	}$\n</div>','To prove the mean value theorem we define a new function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x) = f(x) - \\kappa x \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} \\kappa \\in \\mathbb{R}\n	}$\n</div>\nthat also satisfies the two conditions. We now want to determine a value for $\\kappa$ s.t. the function satisfies Rolle\'s Theorem:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(a) - \\kappa a &= f(b) - \\kappa b \\\\\n		\\kappa(b - a) &= f(b) - f(a) \\\\\n		\\kappa &= \\frac{f(b) - f(a)}{b - a}\n	}$\n</div>\nWith our constant chosen, all of the conditions are met for Rolle\'s Theorem. Therefore:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.1cm} c \\in (a,b) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\hspace{.3cm} g\'(c) = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand directly by our definition of $g$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g\'(c) &= 0 \\\\\n		f\'(c) - \\kappa &= 0 \\\\\n		f\'(c) &= \\kappa \\\\\n		f\'(c) &= \\frac{f(b) - f(a)}{b - a} \\\\\n		f\'(c)(b - a) &= f(b) - f(a)\n	}$\n</div>\n$\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$',NULL),(122,'NewtonAPOSTROPHEs_Method',10,26,'Derivation','Convergence_hidden',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'By now it is known that a function can be approximated as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = f(x_0) + f\'(x_0)(x - x_0)\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere $x_0$ is the point we choose to center ourselves at. Now what if we wanted to find the root of the function, $x = \\alpha$, given some interval $[\\alpha - r,\\alpha + r]$ with $x = x_0$, where $x_0 \\in [\\alpha - r,\\alpha + r]$, as the starting point? To accomplish this we set the function equal to zero and solve for $x$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= f(x_0) + f\'(x_0)(x - x_0) \\\\\n		0 &= f(x_0) + f\'(x_0)x - f\'(x_0)x_0 \\\\\n		f\'(x_0)x &= f\'(x_0)x_0 - f(x_0) \\\\\n		x &= x_0 - \\frac{f(x_0)}{f\'(x_0)}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the result is exactly what we want, but when working with machines we typically like to use recursive algorithms so by discretization:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = x_n - \\frac{f(x_n)}{f\'(x_n)}\n	}$\n</div>\nThe result is known as $\\textit{Newton\'s Method}$, which is one of the most widely known numerical algorithms used to determine the roots of a function.','Deriving the method itself and understanding it is certainly not that challenging, but discussing the convergence of the algorithm requires a bit more insight. This is typically accomplished by analyzing the behavior of the error sequence which we define as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\epsilon_n = x - x_n\n	}$\n</div>\nIf the errors approach zero for larger values of $n$, then the algorithm converges to our final solution $x$. To begin I must first introduce a higher order approximation to the function. If we assume that our function can take the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = a_0 + a_1(x - x_0) + a_2(x - x_0)^2\n	}$\n</div>\nthen by differentiation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= a_1 + 2a_2(x - x_0) \\\\\n		f\'\'(x) &= 2a_2\n	}$\n</div>\nand evaluation at $x = x_0$ we determine that the coefficients have to be:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		a_0 &= f(x_0) \\\\\n		a_1 &= f\'(x_0) \\\\\n		a_2 &= \\frac{f\'\'(x_0)}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich is nothing more than an extension of the linear approximation, specifically known as a $\\textit{quadratic approximation}$. So we have:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = f(x_0) + f\'(x_0)(x - x_0) + \\frac{f\'\'(x_0)}{2}(x - x_0)^2\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere we assume that the second derivative is continuous. So at $x_n$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = f(x_n) + f\'(x_n)(x - x_n) + \\frac{f\'\'(x_n)}{2}(x - x_n)^2\n	}$\n</div>\nNow equating the function to zero and applying the error defined earlier provides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= f(x) \\\\\n		&= f(\\epsilon_n + x_n) \\\\\n		&= f(x_n) + f\'(x_n)\\epsilon_n + \\frac{f\'\'(x_n)}{2}\\epsilon_n^2\n	}$\n</div>\nand if $f\'(x_n) \\neq 0$ we may use the above to deduce:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= f(x_n) + f\'(x_n)\\epsilon_n + \\frac{f\'\'(x_n)}{2}\\epsilon_n^2 \\\\\n		0 &= \\frac{f(x_n)}{f\'(x_n)} + \\epsilon_n + \\frac{f\'\'(x_n)}{2f\'(x_n)}\\epsilon_n^2 \\\\\n		-\\frac{f(x_n)}{f\'(x_n)} &= \\epsilon_n + \\frac{f\'\'(x_n)}{2f\'(x_n)}\\epsilon_n^2\n	}$\n</div>\nFinally we have everything we need, going back to the error definition and using the above we write:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\epsilon_{n + 1} &= x - x_{n + 1} \\\\\n		&= x - \\Big( x_n - \\frac{f(x_n)}{f\'(x_n)} \\Big) \\\\\n		&= x - \\Big( x_n + \\epsilon_n + \\frac{f\'\'(x_n)}{2f\'(x_n)}\\epsilon_n^2 \\Big) \\\\\n		&= -\\frac{f\'\'(x_n)}{2f\'(x_n)}\\epsilon_n^2 \\\\\n		|\\epsilon_{n + 1}| &= \\frac{1}{2} \\Bigg| \\frac{f\'\'(x_n)}{f\'(x_n)} \\Bigg| |\\epsilon_n|^2\n	}$\n</div>\nThe last line is the one that shows the rate of convergence is quadratic due to the right side. Of course to say this we have to assume a couple of conditions:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&1. \\hspace{.1cm} f\'(x) \\neq 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\forall x \\in [\\alpha - r,\\alpha + r] \\\\\n		&2. \\hspace{.1cm} f\'\'(x) \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{is continuous} \\hspace{.1cm} \\forall x \\in [\\alpha - r,\\alpha + r] \\\\\n		&3. \\hspace{.1cm} x_0, \\hspace{.1cm} \\text{the starting point}, \\text{is sufficiently close} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} \\text{to the root} \\hspace{.1cm} \\alpha\n	}$\n</div>\nWe can even go on to show explicitly that the sequence of errors is decreasing by determining an upper bound, $\\Omega \\in \\mathbb{R}$, s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|\\epsilon_{n + 1}| \\leq \\Omega |\\epsilon_n|^2\n	}$\n</div>\nTo define the upper bound we can use our conclusion from above and choose the maximal value that the ratio of the two derivatives take:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\Omega = \\sup_x \\frac{1}{2} \\Bigg| \\frac{f\'\'(x)}{f\'(x)} \\Bigg|\n	}$\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(123,'Related_Rates',5,26,'General Approach',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'Relates Rates is the name given to the application of implicit differentiation in word problems. Typically the process involves determining the equation that models the situation and using differentiation to solve for the needed rate.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(124,'Secant_Method',11,26,'Derivation','Convergence_hidden',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'From the previous section we already know Newton\'s Method as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = x_n - \\frac{f(x_n)}{f\'(x_n)}\n	}$\n</div>\nIn order to arrive at the $\\textit{Secant Method}$ we approximate the derivative as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x_n) \\approx \\frac{f(x_n) - f(x_{n - 1})}{x_n - x_{n - 1}}\n	}$\n</div>\nand plug into Newton\'s Method:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = x_n - f(x_n) \\cdot \\frac{x_n - x_{n - 1}}{f(x_n) - f(x_{n - 1})}\n	}$\n</div>\nUnlike Newton\'s Method, the Secant Method does not require computing the derivative which is definitely an advantage. On the other hand the disadvantage is that two initial points are necessary now.','Let us assume that we are trying to determine the root $x$ s.t. $f(x) = 0$, then the sequence of errors is defined as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\epsilon_n = x - x_n\n	}$\n</div>\nTo prove the convergence of the algorithm we will show that this sequence approaches zero. Using a quadratic approximation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x_n) &= f(x) + f\'(x)(x_n - x) + \\frac{f\'\'(x)}{2}(x_n - x)^2 \\\\\n	}$\n</div>\nour situation turns into the following:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x_n) &= f\'(x)(x_n - x) + \\frac{f\'\'(x)}{2}(x_n - x)^2 \\\\\n		f(x - \\epsilon_n) &= -f\'(x)\\epsilon_n + \\frac{f\'\'(x)}{2}\\epsilon_n^2 \\\\\n		&= \\epsilon_n f\'(x) \\Big[ M\\epsilon_n - 1 \\Big] \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} M = \\frac{f\'\'(x)}{2f\'(x)}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich provides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		&f(x - \\epsilon_n) - f(x - \\epsilon_{n - 1}) \\\\\n		&= \\epsilon_n f\'(x) \\Big[ M\\epsilon_n - 1 \\Big] - \\epsilon_{n - 1} f\'(x) \\Big[ M\\epsilon_{n - 1} - 1 \\Big] \\\\\n		&= f\'(x) \\Big[ M(\\epsilon_n^2 - \\epsilon_{n - 1}^2) - (\\epsilon_n - \\epsilon_{n - 1}) \\Big] \\\\\n		&= (\\epsilon_n - \\epsilon_{n - 1})f\'(x)\\Big[ M(\\epsilon_n - \\epsilon_{n - 1}) - 1 \\Big]\n	}$\n</div>\nNow we have the necessary tools the see the convergence:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} &= x_n - f(x_n) \\cdot \\frac{x_n - x_{n - 1}}{f(x_n) - f(x_{n - 1})} \\\\\n		x - \\epsilon_{n + 1} &= (x - \\epsilon_n) - f(x - \\epsilon_n) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} \\cdot \\hspace{.1cm} \\frac{(x - \\epsilon_n) - (x - \\epsilon_{n - 1})}{f(x - \\epsilon_n) - f(x - \\epsilon_{n - 1})} \\\\\n		\\epsilon_{n + 1} &= \\epsilon_n - \\epsilon_n f\'(x) \\Big[ M\\epsilon_n - 1 \\Big] \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} \\cdot \\hspace{.1cm} \\frac{\\epsilon_n - \\epsilon_{n - 1}}{(\\epsilon_n - \\epsilon_{n - 1})f\'(x)\\Big[ M(\\epsilon_n - \\epsilon_{n - 1}) - 1 \\Big]} \\\\\n		&= \\epsilon_n - \\frac{\\epsilon_n\\Big[ M\\epsilon_n - 1 \\Big]}{M(\\epsilon_n - \\epsilon_{n - 1}) - 1} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{M\\epsilon_n\\epsilon_{n - 1}}{M(\\epsilon_n - \\epsilon_{n - 1}) - 1} \\\\\n		&\\approx M\\epsilon_n\\epsilon_{n - 1}\n	}$\n</div>\nand unlike Newton\'s Method which has quadratic convergence, the Secant Method converges a bit slower. From the above it is hard to tell the degree of convergence without using a bit of algebraic manipulation. Formally an algorithm is said to be convergent with convergence rate $p$ if:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\exists \\hspace{.1cm} C \\in \\mathbb{R} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{s.t.} \\hspace{.3cm} |\\epsilon_{n + 1}| \\approx C|\\epsilon_n|^p\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich allows us to state:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|\\epsilon_n| \\approx C|\\epsilon_{n - 1}|^p\n	}$\n</div>\nUsing the error defined for $n + 1$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C|\\epsilon_n|^p &= |M||\\epsilon_n||\\epsilon_{n - 1}| \\\\\n		|\\epsilon_n|^{p - 1} &= \\frac{|M|}{c}|\\epsilon_{n - 1}| \\\\\n		|\\epsilon_n| &= \\Big( \\frac{|M|}{C} \\Big)^{\\frac{1}{p - 1}}|\\epsilon_{n - 1}|^{\\frac{1}{p - 1}}\n	}$\n</div>\nand now comparing this to the error defined for $n$ we arrive at:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\require{cancel}\n		p &= \\frac{1}{p - 1} \\\\\n		0 &= p^2 - p - 1 \\\\\n		p &= \\cancel{\\frac{1 - \\sqrt{5}}{2}}, \\frac{1 + \\sqrt{5}}{2}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the negative value is ignored due the fact that $p$ by definition must be positive and in this scenario it comes out to be exactly the $\\textit{Golden Ratio}$. With this we can also determine the constant:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		C &= \\Big( \\frac{|M|}{C} \\Big)^{\\frac{1}{p - 1}} \\\\\n		C^p &= |M| \\\\\n		C &= |M|^{\\frac{1}{p}} \\\\\n		&= \\Bigg| \\frac{f\'\'(x)}{2f\'(x)} \\Bigg|^{p - 1}\n	}$\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(125,'HalleyAPOSTROPHEs_Method',12,26,'Derivation','Convergence_hidden',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'We already know Newton\'s Method as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} = x_n - \\frac{f(x_n)}{f\'(x_n)}\n	}$\n</div>\nIn order to arrive at $\\textit{Halley\'s Method}$ we define a new function:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g(x) = \\frac{f(x)}{\\sqrt{|f\'(x)|}}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere any root of $f$ and not of $f\'$ is a root of $g$ and any root of $g$ is a root of $f$. Next we will need the derivative which can be obtained easily when ignoring the absolute value and assuming the derivative is positive:: \n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		g\'(x) &= \\frac{d}{dx} \\frac{f(x)}{\\sqrt{f\'(x)}} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{f\'(x)\\sqrt{f\'(x)} - \\frac{1}{2}f(x)f\'\'(x)\\sqrt{f\'(x)}}{f\'(x)} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{2(f\'(x))^2 - f(x)f\'\'(x)}{2f\'(x)\\sqrt{f\'(x)}} \\\\\n		&= \\frac{2(f\'(x))^2 - f(x)f\'\'(x)}{2f\'(x)\\sqrt{|f\'(x)|}}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere the absolute value is plugged back in on the last line to ensure the existence of the derivative. Plugging into Newton\'s Method provides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		x_{n + 1} &= x_n - \\frac{g(x_n)}{g\'(x_n)} \\\\\n		&= x_n - \\frac{f(x_n)}{\\sqrt{|f\'(x_n)|}} \\cdot \\frac{2f\'(x_n)\\sqrt{|f\'(x_n)|}}{2(f\'(x_n))^2 - f(x_n)f\'\'(x_n)} \\\\\n		&= x_n - \\frac{2f(x_n)f\'(x_n)}{2(f\'(x_n))^2 - f(x_n)f\'\'(x_n)}\n	}$\n</div>','Let us assume that we are trying to determine the root $x$ s.t. $f(x) = 0$, then the sequence of errors is defined as:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\epsilon_n = x - x_n\n	}$\n</div>\nIf the errors approach zero for larger values of $n$, then the algorithm converges to our final solution $x$. To begin I must first introduce a higher order approximation to the function. If we assume that our function can take the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) = a_0 + a_1(x - x_0) + a_2(x - x_0)^2 + a_3(x - x_0)^3\n	}$\n</div>\nthen by differentiation:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f\'(x) &= a_1 + 2a_2(x - x_0) + 3a_3(x - x_0)^2 \\\\\n		f\'\'(x) &= 2a_2 + 6a_3(x - x_0) \\\\\n		f\'\'\'(x) &= 6a_3\n	}$\n</div>\nand evaluation at $x = x_0$ we determine that the coefficients have to be:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		a_0 &= f(x_0) \\\\\n		a_1 &= f\'(x_0) \\\\\n		a_2 &= \\frac{f\'\'(x_0)}{2} \\\\\n		a_3 &= \\frac{f\'\'\'(x_0)}{6}\n	}$\n</div>\nwhich is nothing more than an extension of the quadratic approximation, specifically known as a $\\textit{cubic approximation}$. So we have:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) &= f(x_0) + f\'(x_0)(x - x_0) + \\frac{f\'\'(x_0)}{2}(x - x_0)^2 \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\frac{f\'\'\'(x_0)}{6}(x - x_0)^3\n	}$\n</div>\nwhere we assume that the first, second, and third derivatives are continuous. So at $x_n$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) &= f(x_n) + f\'(x_n)(x - x_n) + \\frac{f\'\'(x_n)}{2}(x - x_n)^2 \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\frac{f\'\'\'(x_n)}{6}(x - x_n)^3\n	}$\n</div>\nNow multiplying the cubic approximation by $2f\'(x_n)$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) &= 2f(x_n)f\'(x_n) + 2[f\'(x_n)]^2(x - x_n) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + f\'(x_n)f\'\'(x_n)(x - x_n)^2 \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\frac{f\'(x_n)f\'\'\'(x_n)}{3}(x - x_n)^3\n	}$\n</div>\nand the quadratic approximation by $f\'\'(x_n)(x - x_n)$:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) &= f(x_n)f\'\'(x_n)(x - x_n) + f\'(x_n)f\'\'(x_n)(x - x_n)^2 \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\frac{(f\'\'(x_n))^2}{2}(x - x_n)^3\n	}$\n</div>\ngives us the tools needed. Subtracting the first equation from the second one right above results in:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		0 &= -2f(x_n)f\'(x_n) + \\Big[ f(x_n)f\'\'(x_n) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - 2(f\'(x_n))^2 \\Big](x - x_n) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\Big[ \\frac{(f\'\'(x_n))^2}{2} - \\frac{f\'(x_n)f\'\'\'(x_n)}{3} \\Big](x - x_n)^3 \\\\\n		0 &= -\\frac{2f(x_n)f\'(x_n)}{f(x_n)f\'\'(x_n) - 2(f\'(x_n))^2} + (x - x_n) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} + \\frac{3(f\'\'(x_n))^2 - 2f\'(x_n)f\'\'\'(x_n)}{6(f(x_n)f\'\'(x_n) - 2(f\'(x_n))^2)}(x - x_n)^3 \\\\\n		x - x_n &= -\\frac{2f(x_n)f\'(x_n)}{2(f\'(x_n))^2 - f(x_n)f\'\'(x_n)} \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - \\frac{2f\'(x_n)f\'\'\'(x_n) - 3(f\'\'(x_n))^2}{6(2(f\'(x_n))^2 - f(x_n)f\'\'(x_n))}(x - x_n)^3 \\\\\n		x - x_n &= (x_{n + 1} - x_{n}) \\\\\n		& \\hspace{.4cm} - \\frac{2f\'(x_n)f\'\'\'(x_n) - 3(f\'\'(x_n))^2}{12(f\'(x_n))^2 - 6f(x_n)f\'\'(x_n)}(x - x_n)^3 \\\\\n		x - x_{n + 1} &= -\\frac{2f\'(x_n)f\'\'\'(x_n) - 3(f\'\'(x_n))^2}{12(f\'(x_n))^2 - 6f(x_n)f\'\'(x_n)}(x - x_n)^3 \\\\\n		\\epsilon_{n + 1} &= -\\frac{2f\'(x_n)f\'\'\'(x_n) - 3(f\'\'(x_n))^2}{12(f\'(x_n))^2 - 6f(x_n)f\'\'(x_n)}\\epsilon_n^3 \\\\\n		|\\epsilon_{n + 1}| &= \\Bigg| \\frac{2f\'(x_n)f\'\'\'(x_n) - 3(f\'\'(x_n))^2}{12(f\'(x_n))^2 - 6f(x_n)f\'\'(x_n)} \\Bigg| |\\epsilon_n|^3 \\\\\n	}$\n</div>\nThe last line is the one that shows the rate of convergence is cubic due to the right side. We can even go on to show explicitly that the sequence of errors is decreasing by determining an upper bound, $\\Omega \\in \\mathbb{R}$, s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|\\epsilon_{n + 1}| \\leq \\Omega |\\epsilon_n|^3\n	}$\n</div>\nTo define the upper bound we can use our conclusion from above and choose the maximal value that the ratio takes on our domain:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\Omega = \\sup_x \\Bigg| \\frac{2f\'(x)f\'\'\'(x) - 3(f\'\'(x))^2}{12(f\'(x))^2 - 6f(x)f\'\'(x)} \\Bigg|\n	}$\n</div>',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(126,'Implications_of_the_nth_Derivative',5,26,'Higher-Order Derivative Test','Inconclusive Cases','Proof by Induction_hidden','Proof by Recursive Use of The First Derivative Test_hidden',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,'So when it comes to determining the behavior of the critical point in relation to its function we have the First and Second Derivative Tests at our disposal and generally speaking most cases can be handled with just those two, but what about the case of when the second derivative equates to zero at the critical point? To tackle this issue I introduce to you the $\\textit{Higher-Order Derivative Test}$ which is needed when we have a critical point, $x = c$, s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f \\in C^n(I) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} &I \\subset \\mathbb{R} \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} n \\in \\mathbb{N} \\\\\n		f^{(n)}(c) \\neq 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} f^{(k)} = 0& \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} 1 \\leq k \\leq n - 1\n	}$\n</div>\nThe test states the following depending on the scenario:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$n$</td>\n		    <td>Sign of $f^{(n)}(c)$</td>\n		    <td>Implication</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>Even</td>\n		    <td>$-$</td>\n		    <td>$x = c$ is a relative maximum of $f$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>Even</td>\n		    <td>$+$</td>\n		    <td>$x = c$ is a relative minimum of $f$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>Odd</td>\n		    <td>$-$</td>\n		    <td>$x = c$ is a strictly decreasing point of inflection of $f$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>Odd</td>\n		    <td>$+$</td>\n		    <td>$x = c$ is a strictly increasing point of inflection of $f$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>','As much as I want to say that the above test is a generalization that could handle all cases, it unfortunately is not. Specifically there are a couple of bad scenarios, the first of which occurs for critical points that have a derivative that does not exist. In another scenario we can have a function that has $n$ derivatives evaluating to zero, but the $n + 1$th derivative not being defined. Lastly it can also happen that all higher order derivatives go to zero. No matter the scenario, the test cannot be used to determine the behavior of the critical point.','We begin this proof by noting the base case $n = 2$ which provides:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f \\in C^2(I) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} f\'\'(c) \\neq 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} f\' = 0\n	}$\n</div>\nand states:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		    <td>Sign of $f\'\'(c)$</td>\n		    <td>Implication</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$-$</td>\n		    <td>$x = c$ is a relative maximum of $f$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		    <td>$+$</td>\n		    <td>$x = c$ is a relative minimum of $f$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nHopefully you notice that this is exactly the Second Derivative Test which we already know to be true. So now we assume the Higher-Order Test and try to show it holds true for $n + 1$. The situation will take the form:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f \\in &C^{n + 1}(I) \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\\\\n		&I \\subset \\mathbb{R}, \\hspace{.3cm} n \\in \\mathbb{N} \\\\\n		&f^{(n + 1)}(c) \\neq 0 \\\\\n		&\\text{and} \\hspace{.3cm} f^{(k)} = 0 \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{where} \\hspace{.3cm} 1 \\leq k \\leq n\n	}$\n</div>\nand if true state the following:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<table>\n	<tr>\n		<td>$n + 1$</td>\n		    <td>Sign of $f^{(n + 1)}(c)$</td>\n		    <td>Implication</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>Odd</td>\n		    <td>$-$</td>\n		    <td>$x = c$ is a relative maximum of $f$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>Odd</td>\n		    <td>$+$</td>\n		    <td>$x = c$ is a relative minimum of $f$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>Even</td>\n		    <td>$-$</td>\n		    <td>$x = c$ is a strictly decreasing point of inflection of $f$</td>\n		</tr>\n		<tr>\n		<td>Even</td>\n		    <td>$+$</td>\n		    <td>$x = c$ is a strictly increasing point of inflection of $f$</td>\n		</tr>\n	</table>\n</div>\nsince we expect $n$ and $n + 1$ to basically switch roles. Let us start with the first case where $n + 1$ is odd and the $n + 1$th derivative is negative. By the assumed Higher-Order Derivative Test we state that our critical point is a strictly decreasing point of inflection for $f\'$. If this is true, then we must have the second derivative of $f\'$ transition from positive to negative. Hence $f\'\'\'$ transitions from positive to negative and by the First Derivative Test $x = c$ is a relative maximum for $f\'\'$. We also know that at the critical point $f\'\' = 0$ which tells us that for some neighborhood around the point $f\'\' < 0$. Now we use the fact that $f\' = 0$ at $x = c$ and its slope is always negative. For this situation to hold true we must have $f\'$ pass through the critical point transitioning from positive to negative. Finally by the First Derivative Test we state that this critical point is a relative maximum for $f$.\n<br><br>\nNow for the second case where $n + 1$ is odd and the $n + 1$th derivative is positive we state that by the assumed Higher-Order Derivative Test our critical point is a strictly increasing point of inflection for $f\'$. If this is true, then we must have the second derivative of $f\'$ transition from negative to positive. Hence $f\'\'\'$ transitions from negative to positive and by the First Derivative Test $x = c$ is a relative minimum for $f\'\'$. We also know that at the critical point $f\'\' = 0$ which tells us that for some neighborhood around the point $f\'\' > 0$. Now we use the fact that $f\' = 0$ at $x = c$ and its slope is always positive. For this situation to hold true we must have $f\'$ pass through the critical point transitioning from negative to positive. Finally by the First Derivative Test we state that this critical point is a relative minimum for $f$.\n<br><br>\nFor the third case where $n + 1$ is even and the $n + 1$th derivative is negative we state that by the assumed Higher-Order Derivative Test our critical point is a relative maximum for $f\'$. If this is true, then we must have the first derivative of $f\'$ transition from positive to negative by the First Derivative Test. So if $f\'\'$ is transitioning from positive to negative it is a strictly decreasing point of inflection for $f$.\n<br><br>\nLastly for the case where $n + 1$ is even and the $n + 1$th derivative is positive we state by the assumed Higher-Order Derivative Test we state that our critical point is a relative minimum for $f\'$. If this is true, then we must have the first derivative of $f\'$ transition from negative to positive by the First Derivative Test. So if $f\'\'$ is transitioning from negative to positive it is a strictly increasing point of inflection for $f$. $\\tag*{$\\blacksquare$}$','First lets assume that $n$ is odd and $f^{(n)}(c) < 0$. If the slope of $f^{(n - 1)}$ is strictly negative and $f^{(n - 1)}(c) = 0$, we must have $f^{(n - 1)}$ transition from positive to negative and by the First Derivative Test $x = c$ is a relative maximum for $f^{(n - 2)}$. Next we consider that we have a relative maximum and $f^{(n - 2)}(c) = 0$, then $f^{(n - 2)} < 0$ in a neighborhood around the critical point. So now we apply the process just used for $f^{(n)} < 0$ on $f^{(n - 2)} < 0$. If you keep doing this eventually you will arrive at $f\'\'\' < 0$ in a neighborhood around the critical point. Since $f\'\'(c) = 0$ and the slope is strictly negative we must have $f\'\'$ transition from positive to negative and by the First Derivative Test $x = c$ is a relative maximum for $f\'$. The important part here is that $f\'\'$ transitions from positive to negative, thus $x = c$ is a strictly decreasing point of inflection.\n<br><br>\nNow lets assume that $n$ is odd and $f^{(n)}(c) > 0$. If the slope of $f^{(n - 1)}$ is strictly positive and $f^{(n - 1)}(c) = 0$, we must have $f^{(n - 1)}$ transition from negative to positive and by the First Derivative Test $x = c$ is a relative minimum for $f^{(n - 2)}$. Next we consider that we have a relative minimum and $f^{(n - 2)}(c) = 0$, then $f^{(n - 2)} > 0$ in a neighborhood around the critical point. So now we apply the process just used for $f^{(n)} > 0$ on $f^{(n - 2)} > 0$. If you keep doing this eventually you will arrive at $f\'\'\' > 0$ in a neighborhood around the critical point. Since $f\'\'(c) = 0$ and the slope is strictly positive we must have $f\'\'$ transition from negative to positive and by the First Derivative Test $x = c$ is a relative minimum for $f\'$. The important part here is that $f\'\'$ transitions from negative to positive, thus $x = c$ is a strictly increasing point of inflection.\n<br><br>\nSwitch it up and now consider the scenario with even $n$ and $f^{(n)}(c) < 0$. If the slope of $f^{(n - 1)}$ is strictly negative and $f^{(n - 1)}(c) = 0$, we must have $f^{(n - 1)}$ transition from positive to negative and by the First Derivative Test $x = c$ is a relative maximum for $f^{(n - 2)}$. Next we consider that we have a relative maximum and $f^{(n - 2)}(c) = 0$, then $f^{(n - 2)} < 0$ in a neighborhood around the critical point. So now we apply the process just used for $f^{(n)} < 0$ on $f^{(n - 2)} < 0$. If you keep doing this eventually you will arrive at $f\'\' < 0$ in a neighborhood around the critical point. Since $f\'\'(c) = 0$ and the slope is strictly negative we must have $f\'$ transition from positive to negative and by the First Derivative Test $x = c$ is a relative maximum for $f$.\n<br><br>\nFinally consider even $n$ and $f^{(n)}(c) > 0$. If the slope of $f^{(n - 1)}$ is strictly positive and $f^{(n - 1)}(c) = 0$, we must have $f^{(n - 1)}$ transition from negative to positive and by the First Derivative Test $x = c$ is a relative minimum for $f^{(n - 2)}$. Next we consider that we have a relative minimum and $f^{(n - 2)}(c) = 0$, then $f^{(n - 2)} > 0$ in a neighborhood around the critical point. So now we apply the process just used for $f^{(n)} > 0$ on $f^{(n - 2)} > 0$. If you keep doing this eventually you will arrive at $f\'\' > 0$ in a neighborhood around the critical point. Since $f\'(c) = 0$ and the slope is strictly positive we must have $f\'$ transition from negative to positive and by the First Derivative Test $x = c$ is a relative minimum for $f$.',NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL,NULL),(127,'Formal_Definitions',7,25,'Introduction','Definition of a Limit','Left Limit','Right Limit','Limit Leading to Positive Infinity','Limit Leading to Negative Infinity','Limit at Positive Infinity','Limit at Negative Infinity','Continuity at a Point',NULL,'All previous sections talked about limits in terms of how they are evaluated and the associated properties, but not once mentioned the basic notion of where limits actually come from and any formal definitions. To fix this, below I present to you the formal definitions of everything covered in the previous sections with proof-based examples to follow.','The formal definition states that the limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) = L\n	}$\n</div>\nexists if $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\delta > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nIn all essense this is just a rigorous way of stating that a limit at a point will exist if for every range close to the limit, a value can be determined that also instills a range on the independent variable. So no matter how close you get to the limit, there will always exist a restriction on the domain s.t. the closer you get to the limit, the closer you get to $x = a$. Visually this looks like:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	<img src=\"/content/Differential_Calculus/Limits/Formal_Definitions/Limit_Definition.png\">\n</div>','The left-hand limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^-} f(x) = L_1\n	}$\n</div>\nexists if $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\delta > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L_1| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} -\\delta < x - a < 0\n	}$\n</div>\nThis is exactly the same as the definition of the limit, except we now only care about the behavior on the left-hand side as seen on the restriction of $x$.','The right-hand limit:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a^+} f(x) = L_2\n	}$\n</div>\nexists if $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\delta > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - L_2| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} 0 < x - a < \\delta\n	}$\n</div>\nThis is exactly the same as the definition of the limit, except we now only care about the behavior on the right-hand side as seen on the restriction of $x$.','We say that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) = \\infty\n	}$\n</div>\nif $\\forall \\Omega > 0, \\exists \\delta > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) > \\Omega \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta \n	}$\n</div>\nIn essense this states that no matter how large a value you pick, $f(x)$ will always attain a larger value on some domain close to the value $x = a$.','We say that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow a} f(x) = -\\infty\n	}$\n</div>\nif $\\forall \\Gamma < 0, \\exists \\delta > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		f(x) < \\Gamma \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta \n	}$\n</div>\nIn essense this states that no matter how small a value you pick, $f(x)$ will always attain a smaller value on some domain close to the value $x = a$.','We say that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow \\infty} f(x) = \\kappa_1\n	}$\n</div>\nif $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\Omega > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - \\kappa_1| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} x > \\Omega \n	}$\n</div>\nIn essense this states that $f(x)$ will attain values close to $\\kappa_1$ at large values of $x$, and as $x$ gets larger $f(x)$ will tend towards exactly $\\kappa_1$.','We say that:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		\\lim_{x \\rightarrow -\\infty} f(x) = \\kappa_2\n	}$\n</div>\nif $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\Gamma < 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - \\kappa_2| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} x < \\Gamma \n	}$\n</div>\nIn essense this states that $f(x)$ will attain values close to $\\kappa_2$ at small values of $x$, and as $x$ gets smaller $f(x)$ will tend towards exactly $\\kappa_2$.','We say that a function is continuous at a point $x = a$ if $\\forall \\epsilon > 0, \\exists \\delta > 0$ s.t.:\n<div class=\"latex_equation\">\n	$\\eqalign{\n		|f(x) - f(a)| < \\epsilon \\hspace{.3cm} \\text{whenever} \\hspace{.3cm} |x - a| < \\delta \n	}$\n</div>\nIn essense this statement is exactly the same as definition of the limit, except we replace the arbitrary real number, $L$, with the function at that point, $f(a)$.',NULL);
