INSERT INTO `topic` VALUES (21,'Introduction',1,5,'When first approaching ordinary differential equations, it is important to understand the terminology typically associated with the subject. Different classifications give rise to different cases that typically have unique methods utilized. Following the basics, slope fields provide a geometrical representation of a first order differential equation that gives the means of seeing the family of solutions, each based on a unique initial condition.'),(22,'First_Order',2,5,'First order differential equations are typically the first equations of interest since they are understood extensively when compared to higher orders. Cases of significance typically include separable, linear, exact, and homogeneous equations that have a systematic approach to solving the equations. All of these share the unique feature that they are linear in nature, which is what makes the Bernoulli differential equation rather intriguing in comparison. Even though it is non-linear, it actually has a method to attain the exact solution. Along with these equations, autonomous systems study the special case where the derivative is only a function of the original function. To finish off, Newton\'s Method provides a numerical algorithm to calculate the function at a point given some initial condition and the derivative. This especially becomes important when no there is no analytical method to solve the differential equation.'),(23,'Second_Order',3,5,NULL),(24,'The_Derivative',2,6,'With an understanding of limits at hand, next up is the derivative. We begin with introduction and properties sections that provide the detailing of the derivative as a tool followed by four systematic rules that simplify the process of finding the derivative for a given function. To finish up there is implicit differentiation which handles the case of implicit functions and logarithmic differentiation which is a common trick that comes in handy for many cases.'),(25,'Limits',1,6,'Prior to tackling the derivative, it is important to first understand what limits are. It all begins with an introduction that explains what limits are, their purpose, and their one-sided counterparts. Once a fundamental comprehension of limits has been grasped, we move on to study properties of limits, limits that deal with infinity, and the application of limits towards the definition of continuity. In the last section I present to you the formal definition of a limit and its properties from an analytical perspective.'),(26,'Applications_of_the_Derivative',3,6,'After having learned what the derivative is, its associated properties, and how it is computed, we finally move towards its applications. The first four sections deal with the physical implications of the derivative in relation to the original function\'s extremas and concavity behavior. Next up related rates and optimization present real world applications of implicit differentiation and function extremas respectively. To finish up linear approximation presents how a function can be estimated when observing locally, L\'Hospital\'s Rule presents a systematic technique to evaluating limits that approach indeterminate forms, and Newton\'s method presents a numerical algorithm to determine the root of a function on a given interval.');
